<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends At Record 10,007.33 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology issues propelled the stock market  
sharply higher Monday, lifting the Dow Jones industrial average 
back above 10,000, as investors stopped worrying about interest 
rates and looked forward to strong first-quarter earnings reports. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue chip index rose 174.82 at 10,007.33, just squeezing  
past the Dow's previous closing high of 10,006.78, set March 29. 
Monday's session was just the second time that the Dow has finished 
above 10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq composite index and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index  
also set new records. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq rose 66.69 to 2,560.06, passing its previous high  
close of 2,510.09, reached Feb. 1. The S&AMP;P 500 rose 27.40 to 
1,321.12, breaking its record of 1,316.55 set March 18. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a herd instinct out there, as everyone wants to buy the  
winners,'' said David Orr, chief economist at First Union Capital 
Markets in Charlotte, N.C. ``This is not economics; it's 
psychological.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were buoyed by Friday's Labor Department report that  
just 46,000 new jobs were created in February, the smallest 
increase in three years. The report calmed investor fears that the 
economy was growing too fast and that the Federal Reserve might 
raise interest rates to slow it down. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts said the rally exceeded their expectations from the  
jobs report. Monday was the first chance the market, which was 
closed for Good Friday, had to react to the numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is nothing wrong with the economy, but is the economy  
that good? The answer is probably no,'' Orr said. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks once again set the tone for trading.  
</P>
<P>
	Among Dow stocks, IBM was up 6 5/8 to 183 5/8 and Hewlett-Packard rose  
3 9/16 to 71 7/16. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Nasdaq, Yahoo! shot up 39 3/16 to 219 1/8 as traders  
anticipated a strong earnings report from the Internet company on 
Wednesday. GeoCities and Broadcast.com, two companies Yahoo! is 
buying also rose more than 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Computer maker Dell was up 2 7/8 at 44 1/16, Sun Microsystems  
gained 3 13/16 at 130, and Microsoft was up 2 1/4 at 94 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online rose 16 15/16 to 166 15/16 on the New York Stock  
Exchange. The online services giant declined to comment Monday on a 
published report that revived rumors that AOL was in talks to buy 
CBS. The takeover talk was the subject of a report Monday in the 
online edition of the San Jose Mercury News. 
</P>
<P>
	Online stock trading companies also traded higher after a Credit  
Suisse First Boston analyst issued positive comments about the 
sector. E-Trade Group rose 11 3/4 to 72 5/8 Charles Schwab rose 9 1/8 to 
103 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Blue chip stocks also rose amid optimism about first-quarter  
earnings reports that will be released starting this week. That 
included oil companies -- Exxon was up 2 1/16 to 72 3/16 and Chevron 
rose 3 13/16 to 90 5/8. 
</P>
<P>
	``Expectations are very solid for the larger companies,'' said  
Richard Cripps, chief market strategist for Legg Mason of 
Baltimore. ``Microsoft, GE and these types of companies will show 
robust double-digit growth in sales and earnings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Online bookseller Amazon.com rose 15 1/2 to 186 1/2 and retailer  
Wal-Mart gained 2 1/8 to 95 3/8. The two companies settled a suit brought 
by Wal-Mart charging that Amazon hired computer system managers 
away from Wal-Mart to steal the retailer's trade secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the  
NYSE with 1,689 up, 1,321 down and 558 unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 863.84 million shares vs. 872.44 million in  
the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 9.64 to 614.63, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 9.94 to 721.24 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 3.55 to 402.29.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
