<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aerospace Engineer Denney Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) -- Aerospace engineer Corwin Dwight  
Denney, an entrepreneur and philanthropist who began by personally 
flight-testing his own products, has died. He was 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Denney died of pneumonia April 1 at his home here, following a  
yearlong bout with cancer, according to a statement from the 
University of Southern California, where he served on the Board of 
Trustees. 
</P>
<P>
	The lifelong pilot began manufacturing aerospace components and  
flight-test equipment in 1947 when he founded American Helicopter 
Co., forming the core of what would become his Fortune 500 company, 
Automation Industries Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Denney served as the lone test pilot for the Van Nuys-based  
company, before several veterans joined the business at the end of 
World War II and it became known as Mid-Continent Manufacturing. 
</P>
<P>
	The company was soon commissioned by the federal government to  
create complex aircraft structures and nondestructive test 
materials. That funding enabled Denney to merge the business with 
tiny Pasadena-based Automation Instruments in 1952 to form 
Automation Industries. 
</P>
<P>
	While still at the helm of that company, he branched off into  
oil drilling in 1962, forming the independent San Antonio-based 
Venus Oil Co. In later years he also invested in the Beverly 
Wilshire Hotel in Beverly Hills, helping to restore it to 
profitability before selling his share in 1985 for $33 million. 
</P>
<P>
	But he is perhaps best known for orchestrating a score of  
mergers during his three decades as president, chairman of the 
board and chief executive officer of Automation Industries Inc., 
which he sold to General Cable in 1978 for $106 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in the small town of Washington Court House, Ohio, Denney  
earned a degree in aeronautical engineering from the University of 
Michigan in 1943. During the next four years, he developed aircraft 
and jet engine projects in the Army Air Corps. 
</P>
<P>
	Denney also served as a trustee and benefactor for several  
colleges, museums and hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife, three daughters, two sons, and three  
stepchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	Funeral services will be private.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
