<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A new governor took office Monday in Quintana  
Roo state, while the official he replaced remained missing amid an 
intensifying investigation into his alleged ties to drug 
traffickers. 
</P>
<P>
	Mario Villanueva, whose six-year term expired Monday, has  
repeatedly failed to appear for further interrogation after one 
session of questioning by Mexico's anti-drug czar last month. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. authorities have joined Mexican police in the search for  
Villanueva, who has denied any wrongdoing, saying he is being 
targeted by political enemies. 
</P>
<P>
	The state's new governor, Joaquin Hendricks, told the Reforma  
daily that he would order an independent audit of Villanueva's 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Quintana Roo is located on Mexico's Caribbean coast.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- A leftist opposition  
congressman hopes to persuade Cuban authorities to spare the lives 
of two Salvadoran men condemned to death for their roles in a 
string of bombings. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruben Zamora, a former guerrilla and two-time presidential  
candidate, said Monday he will travel to Havana this week in hopes 
of speaking with Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina and other 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The two men -- Otto Rene Rodriguez Llerena, 40, and Ernesto Cruz  
Leon, 27 -- were convicted last month on terrorism charges and 
sentenced to death. Under Cuban law, the sentences are 
automatically appealed. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez Llerena was convicted of planting a bomb in a hotel  
and attempting to import explosives to launch other attacks. Cruz 
Leon was found guilty of planting bombs at six tourist locales, 
killing an Italian tourist and wounding 11 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban prosecutors say both men were hired by Cuban exiles to  
bomb tourist sites in order to hurt a prime source of income for 
the island. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexican authorities searched Monday for 25  
men who escaped from prisons in two states over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest escape took place Sunday in the Gulf state of  
Tabasco, where 19 felons fled a state prison through an underground 
tunnel. 
</P>
<P>
	Police were trying to determine how the tunnel had been dug.  
</P>
<P>
	The escaped men were serving sentences of up to 30 years for  
drug trafficking, kidnapping and homicide. Many were believed to be 
part of the region's most dangerous kidnapping gang. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's breakout was the third in six months at the prison in  
Villahermosa, the state capital, prison director Fredy Chable told 
the government news agency Notimex. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Pacific state of Sinaloa, six convicts escaped from a  
local jail Saturday after giving their prison guards chicken and 
fruit juices laced with sedatives, deputy attorney general Melchor 
Cota said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
