<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury To Be Seated in Gotti Jr. Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- Nobody got whacked.  
</P>
<P>
	In the entire federal indictment against John A. ``Junior''  
Gotti, there is no mention of murder. No cement shoes, no sleeping 
with the fishes, no kiss on the cheek followed by a bullet to the 
head. There isn't even any leg-breaking. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not that kind of mob case,'' said Ronald Goldstock,  
former director of the state Organized Crime Task Force. ``You 
might not get those much anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So many Mafia leaders are in prison and so many mobsters are  
willing to cooperate that it's difficult now to carry out ``the 
kind of blatant criminal activity people associate with organized 
crime,'' Goldstock said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jury selection begins Tuesday in the case against the  
35-year-old Gotti, who is accused of succeeding his father, John J. 
Gotti, to the top of the Gambino crime family after the elder Gotti 
was sent to prison for life in 1992. The younger Gotti could get 15 
years behind bars. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Gotti, known as the Teflon Don for avoiding conviction  
in three trials, was finally found guilty in a racketeering case 
that alleged five murders -- including that of his predecessor, Paul 
Castellano -- and featured the Mafia's highest-ranking turncoat, 
Salvatore ``Sammy Bull'' Gravano. 
</P>
<P>
	The case against the younger Gotti consists in large part of  
extortion and loansharking charges that involve only the implied 
threat of violence. 
</P>
<P>
	If the younger Gotti's case is less glamorous, so is the  
defendant himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``Junior,'' whose father was called the Dapper Don for his fine  
suits and silvery hair, has gone to court in sneakers and jeans. 
Unlike his swaggering father, he rushes past the cameras and talks 
to reporters in half-sentences. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger Gotti's lawyer Gerald Shargel said that his client  
has apparently been targeted because of his name, which ``has 
become the metaphor for organized crime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the things we expect this trial to show is that the  
government has for years, since he was in his late teens or early 
20s, targeted him,'' Shargel said. ``The time has come for this 
trial to be held and for him to show that the government's wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Gotti said of his impending trial: ``I'm excited.  
It's like my first day of school. It's like I'm starting 
kindergarten again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gotti is charged with racketeering -- taking part in a criminal  
enterprise known as the Gambino family -- and extortion, robbery, 
labor racketeering, loansharking, gambling and bribery. He also is 
charged with lying about his income on a home refinancing 
application. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is like a kitchen sink approach,'' Shargel said. ``The  
government says, `We're charging him with robbery, and if you don't 
believe robbery, well, he also made a false statement on his 
mortgage application.''' 
</P>
<P>
	The extortion charges allege a virtual mob takeover of the New  
York topless club Scores. 
</P>
<P>
	But Shargel said that Gotti had nothing to do with the club and  
that his money is earned legitimately, with investments in several 
businesses and ``income-producing property that he acquired by 
lawful sources.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The evidence assembled by the government includes thousands of  
taped conversations, some between Gotti and his father at the 
federal prison in Marion, Ill. There are boxes of documents, 
including one that former state Attorney General Dennis Vacco 
called the ``Holy Grail'' -- a list of past and present members of 
New York's five Mafia families. 
</P>
<P>
	That list was found in a search of a Queens basement that also  
turned up $358,000 in cash, which Gotti claims was gift money from 
his wedding; three guns; and a photo of his father. 
</P>
<P>
	Gotti, who originally had 22 co-defendants, has just one left.  
Most of the rest have pleaded guilty, including John ``Jackie 
Nose'' D'Amico, who prosecutors said shared the family leadership 
with ``Junior'' Gotti. The possible witnesses for the government 
include former mobsters Dominic ``Fat Dom'' Borghese, Alphonso 
``Little Al'' D'Arco and William Marshall. 
</P>
<P>
	The proliferation of such traitors has been a key to the decline  
of the mob. 
</P>
<P>
	``People within the mob who want to carry out complex criminal  
activities don't know who they can trust,'' Goldstock said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker has ordered up a jury pool  
of 400. But he turned down a prosecution request that the jurors' 
names be kept secret, saying none of the charges involve the sort 
of violence that warrants an anonymous jury. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not that kind of mob case.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
