<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 05:45:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Software That Will Have You Hopping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	``Hip hop'' is what the Easter Bunny does, and ``scratching'' is  
a nasty thing to do to a phonograph record, right? 
</P>
<P>
	Not entirely. Those words take on new meanings in ``Hip Hop  
eJay,'' multimedia PC software from Voyetra Turtle Beach, in 
Yonkers, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	As any young person can tell you, hip hop is rap music with a  
melody line. And Voyetra, which has been doing nice things with 
sound for multimedia PCs for years, has created software that 
allows you to compose and play hip hop on your PC. 
</P>
<P>
	To compose a piece you need only select the desired effect --  
such as bass, guitar or drum -- to have a selection of sound clips 
appear. You can preview the clip with a mouse click and, if you 
approve, drag it to one of eight tracks at the top of the screen. 
(A track is an element in an overall musical composition. A 
symphony has a violin track, oboe track and so on.) 
</P>
<P>
	Zero musical knowledge is required. ``Hip Hop eJay'' handles the  
issue of keeping time by making sound elements of various lengths. 
If you want Track 1 and Track 2 to finish together, just make sure 
the elements are the same length visually. You just keep dragging 
various elements to tracks and listening to the result. 
</P>
<P>
	Scratch, it turns out, is the weird sounds you can make when a  
phonograph's tone arm is on the record and you move the turntable 
back and forth. It's what disc jockeys do at dance clubs, where 
young people gather, apparently to encourage hearing loss 
rhythmically. 
</P>
<P>
	In the software version, you can play your creation on the  
left-side turntable while manipulating the right-side turntable 
with a mouse. 
</P>
<P>
	You can also import sounds or record your voice. I recorded a  
one-minute hip-hop plea for my daughter to pay more attention to 
her books and less to her boyfriend, complete with seven other 
tracks of effects. The result made the dog growl at the speakers, 
and my daughter would have ignored it anyway, so it was on to new 
compositions. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if your idea of hip hop is what you do when that balky knee  
flares up, you'll find the software fun. And it's even more fun for 
a 20-something who actually understands what it's about. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hip Hop eJay'' requires a Pentium PC running Windows 95-98-NT,  
16 megabytes of RAM, 50 megabytes of hard disk space, a 256-color 
display, a 16-bit Direct Sound-compatible sound card, a doublespeed 
or better CD-ROM drive and, for recording, a microphone. 
</P>
<P>
	Voyetra products are available at retail. The street price is  
about $30. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Voyetra Web site: www.voyetra.com.  
</P>
<P>
