<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 02:23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 76ers Coach Ends Spat With Iverson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Larry Brown knows the drill by now.  
</P>
<P>
	The Philadelphia 76ers coach has heard Allen Iverson bark at him  
every time he's taken the 23-year-old superstar out of a game for 
the past two years. He doesn't expect that to change, no matter how 
their latest dispute ends. 
</P>
<P>
	He just wants it to end.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a battle between me and him,'' Brown said Sunday as  
Iverson skipped the team's trip to Toronto after the two got into 
an argument on the bench. ``This is over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown told The Associated Press in a telephone interview that  
Iverson said he was too injured to go back into a game against 
Cleveland on Friday night after the two exchanged words on the 
sideline. Brown said both agreed Iverson would skip the team's 
brief road trip and get treatment on his leg. 
</P>
<P>
	Without Iverson, the NBA's leading scorer, the Sixers lost to  
the Raptors 97-82 Sunday night. Although Iverson said he's doubtful 
to play Tuesday night against Milwaukee, Brown expected him to be 
at practice today. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's not even an issue,'' Brown said. ``He's still part of  
the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Iverson, who played for two weeks with a deeply bruised thigh,  
did not play the opening 2:03 of the second quarter against the 
Cavaliers Friday night after going 0-for-7 in the first quarter. 
Brown generally rests Iverson at the end of the first or beginning 
of the second quarter to buy him a few extra minutes with the break 
between periods. 
</P>
<P>
	When Brown told Iverson to go back into the game, Iverson  
muttered something that reporters sitting near the Sixers' bench 
reported as, ``It's about ... time you put me back in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``So I sat him back down,'' Brown said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Sixers, slipping out of contention for the final playoff  
spot in the Eastern Conference because of a rash of injuries and 
spotty play, lost 85-80. Iverson sat out the final three quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown said it was Iverson's decision not to return to the game  
after the spat. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said he couldn't go and that was it,'' Brown said. ``I'm  
not going to question any player on my team when he tells me he's 
injured.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Philadelphia Inquirer, quoting team sources it did not name,  
reported Sunday that Iverson considered leaving the arena during 
the Cleveland game and had to be persuaded by teammates to stay. 
</P>
<P>
	Iverson was in Philadelphia getting treatment, and attempts by  
the Sixers to reach him for comment were unsuccessful. He severely 
bruised his right thigh in a collision with the Los Angeles Lakers' 
Shaquille O'Neal March 19, but tried to keep playing. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown said Iverson told him Saturday he was too hurt to play,  
and the two agreed he should stay home and get treatment. After the 
game Friday night, Iverson tried to downplay the dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	``There ain't no problems,'' Iverson said. ``Everything ain't  
going to be peaches and cream all the time. But I don't have any 
problems with him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown said Iverson objects every time the coach takes him out of  
a game, so he didn't see why this time became such a controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only big difference is, people heard his response when I  
put him in,'' Brown said. ``The biggest disappointment is, it was a 
big game, a game we really needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do I like getting yelled at every game? Absolutely not. But  
that's him. I understand that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown is not considering disciplinary action.  
</P>
<P>
	``My thing is, let's get over it,'' Brown said. ``What good is  
it going to do? How is it going to change anything unless it makes 
it worse?'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was the latest in a series of flaps between Iverson and  
Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the two publicly criticized each other to the point  
that Iverson vowed to ``remember everything come contract time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After signing a six-year, $70.9 million contract extension in  
January, Iverson said he and Brown had put their differences behind 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just had to mature,'' Iverson said. ``I realized that he was  
a great coach when I looked at his resume. It was important for me 
to put my pride aside and listen to what was said to me as a 
positive. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was just young, I had to do a lot of growing up.''  
</P>
<P>
	Then, Iverson had an unexcused absence from practice March 11.  
Forcing Iverson to be accountable to his teammates, Brown had the 
team decide how to handle it. Brown followed the players' 
recommendation not to suspend Iverson, but the 23-year-old guard 
was warned that further transgressions would be punished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
