<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises As Stocks Advance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against major currencies Monday  
as stocks rallied to record levels on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen retreated against the dollar after a report showing that  
sentiment among major Japanese manufacturers has improved, but 
remains lukewarm. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also gained against the euro amid the continuing  
turmoil in Yugoslavia, where NATO missiles and aircraft blasted 
Serbian targets for a 13th straight day while the allies readied a 
massive airlift for ethnic Albanian refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no trading in Europe and some Asia-Pacific countries  
due Easter observances. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0708, down  
from $1.0779 late Friday. The dollar also was quoted at 121.83 
Japanese yen, up from 120.55 yen on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the dollar drew some strength from Wall Street,  
where a stock rally drove the Dow Jones industrial average back 
above 10,000. The Dow rose 174.82 points to 10,007.33, squeezing 
past the March 29 closing high of 10,006.78. The Nasdaq composite 
index and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index also set new records. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign investors desiring U.S. stocks must buy dollars to  
transact business. 
</P>
<P>
	``The renewed strength of the Dow is pulling funds into the U.S.  
again. That's lifting the dollar against all currencies,'' said 
Douglas Porter, a senior economist with Nesbitt Burns Inc., a 
Toronto-based investment company subsidiary of the Bank of 
Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar started its rise, however, during Asian trading as  
traders reacted negatively to the latest Tankan report, a quarterly 
survey of business sentiment in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey, released Monday, showed that Japan manufacturers  
grew more optimistic about the economy during the first three 
months of 1999, but not as much as had been forecast. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, according to the survey, big companies are spending  
9.4 percent less on capital investment in the current fiscal year 
and smaller companies are projecting a 26 percent falloff. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Eisuke Sakakibara, Japan's influential vice Finance  
Minister for international affairs, reiterated his position that a 
sharp rise in the yen is undesirable, adding to fears the Bank of 
Japan would intervene in foreign exchange markets to support the 
dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4895 Swiss francs, up from  
1.4799, and 1.5020 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4960. The British 
pound fell to $1.6000 from $1.6036. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Monday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8265 German 
marks, up from 1.8146; 6.1275 French francs, up from 6.0864; and 
1,808.32 Italian lire, up from 1,795.33. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
