<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Cloudy and wet weather dawned over most of the nation today as  
snow fell over the northern Plains and rain dampened both coasts. 
Thunderstorms threatened to flash in the Mississippi Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Light rain falling over the mid-Atlantic states was expected to  
end later today, leaving partly cloudy skies over the Northeast and 
Southeast. Showers also were forecast in the Tennessee Valley and 
Carolinas. 
</P>
<P>
	Storms were expected to gradually move out of the Plains and  
into the Mississippi Valley and southern Great Lakes, bringing 
powerful winds and large hail. 
</P>
<P>
	Tornadoes were reported Sunday in East Texas, while tornado  
watches remained in effect for most of northern Louisiana following 
a deadly weekend of twisters. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Weather Service issued severe thunderstorm and  
tornado warnings for the Oklahoma and the Texas Panhandle late 
Sunday. Some parts of North Texas were also under tornado watches 
and thunderstorm warnings. 
</P>
<P>
	A few isolated tornadoes were possible today over the southern  
Plains and lower Mississippi Valley. Rain was forecast over the 
northern Plains and Great Lakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Some wet snow was likely over northern North Dakota and  
Minnesota. Windy conditions should dominate before the system 
spreads into the Ohio Valley by evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Snow also was forecast along the Rockies, Cascades and  
Bitterroots while another storm system could hit areas of the 
Pacific Northwest. Rain and snow was expected to lash Washington, 
Oregon and northern California. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain and wind were expected in the Northwest, especially along  
the coast. Elsewhere, partly cloudy skies and dry weather were 
forecast in the Southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest temperature in the continental United States on  
Sunday was 93 degrees in McAllen, Texas. The low was 2 degrees at 
Yellowstone National Park, Wyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast to reach the 30s and 40s in the  
northern Plains, Rockies and Northwest; the 50s and 60s along the 
Northeast, Great Lakes, Ohio Valley, central Plains, California and 
mid-Atlantic states; and the 70s and 80s in the Southeast, 
Mississippi Valley, Southwest and Gulf Coast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
