<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minn. Research Labs Vandalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Twelve University of Minnesota medical  
research labs were ransacked early Monday and 75 rats, pigeons, 
salamanders and mice were taken. 
</P>
<P>
	Computers were smashed, lab equipment was tipped over, and  
microscopes and photocopiers were wrecked. 
</P>
<P>
	Graffiti at the scene pointed to a group called the Animal  
Liberation Front, and later in the day a spokesman claimed 
responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ALF is taking action immediately to free these animals  
from their exploitation,'' Kevin Kjonaas said. He said the group 
had seized 100 animals and had found homes for them. 
</P>
<P>
	The animals were being used to research cancer, Parkinson's and  
other diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Walter Low, a researcher, said the damage set back the  
Alzheimer's studies alone by two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
