<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed generally mixed  
Monday, with the key indexes rising in Tokyo and Singapore, but 
falling in Bangkok and Kuala Lumpur. Many other bourses remained 
closed for the Easter holidays. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo stocks rose after the Japanese central bank announced an  
improvement in corporate sentiment. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 44.59 points,  
or 0.27 percent, to finish the day at 16,334.78 points. On Friday, 
the average closed down 37.37 points, or 0.23 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In its closely-watched quarterly ``tankan'' survey, the Bank of  
Japan reported business sentiment at large manufacturers improved 
moderately from the previous tankan, prompting hope that the 
economy has bottomed out. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei average was up more than 300 points at one point in  
morning trading after the release of the survey, but share prices 
fell back in the afternoon as traders pocketed profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the moderate upswing in corporate confidence cheered the  
market, and investors were eager to buy on any significant dips, 
analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 121.36 yen in late  
afternoon trading, up 0.70 yen from late Friday in Tokyo and also 
above its late New York level of 120.55 yen on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Singapore, share prices closed sharply higher on growing  
optimism about an economic recovery in Asia. The benchmark Straits 
Times Index rose 2.4 percent, or 36.41 points, to 1,581.60. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealers noted that the perception that Asian economies, led by  
Japan, have hit a bottom is encouraging an inflow of funds into the 
region. 
</P>
<P>
	Philippine shares also closed higher in thin trading, buoyed by  
bargain hunting of selected blue chips and second-tier companies, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 12.96  
points, or 0.6 percent, to 2,041.17. 
</P>
<P>
	Thai share prices closed lower as investors sold finance stocks  
on worries about the financial status of some of the weaker finance 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stock Exchange of Thailand index (SET) fell 6.37 points, or  
1.8 percent, to 350.73. 
</P>
<P>
	Malaysian share prices also closed lower as investors took  
profits following recent gains. The key Composite Index, which 
tracks 100 blue-chip stocks, fell 4.23 points, or 0.7 percent, to 
535.84. 
</P>
<P>
	In Indonesia, share prices closed mixed. The key Composite Index  
edged up 0.904 point, or 0.2 percent, to 395.337. 
</P>
<P>
	The markets were closed in Australia, New Zealand, Taiwan and  
South Korea for the Easter holidays. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
