<DOCNO> APW19990405.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 05:56:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Refugee Office in D.C. Busy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sorrowful tales about refugees streaming out  
of Kosovo got gloomier as the day unfolded at this tiny United 
Nations office. Relief workers called with frantic accounts of 
refugees herded onto trains at gunpoint. E-mails told of torched 
villages. Situation reports detailed the exodus by the numbers -- 
the tents, blankets and sanitation kits required. 
</P>
<P>
	Tucked into the third floor of an office building a few blocks  
from the White House, the Washington office of the U.N. High 
Commissioner for Refugees is in crisis mode. 
</P>
<P>
	At this nerve center, which coordinates U.S. efforts to help  
Kosovo, workers jog-walk from desk to desk. Road maps of the 
Balkans are taped to the wall. The telephone rings incessantly with 
calls from Capitol Hill, volunteers, donors and humanitarian 
workers handling a crisis some 4,700 miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	There are logistical problems, political problems,  
communications problems. Links between the office and the high 
commissioner's headquarters in Geneva often are jammed. 
Conversations with humanitarian workers on static-filled mobile 
phones end abruptly when satellite connections fail. 
</P>
<P>
	``Can you tell me about the situation in Blace?'' Jennifer Dean,  
an employee at the U.N. office, asked Benny Otim, a worker 
stationed at a Kosovo-Macedonia border crossing in a weekend call. 
``Are they processing people through there smoothly right now?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The line goes dead. ``Benny? Benny?'' Dean shouted into the  
receiver. ``Lost him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before it's even 8 a.m. in Washington (2 p.m. in Kosovo), Ms.  
Dean has already updated refugee numbers, called headquarters and 
reviewed her telephone voice mail. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm getting telephone calls from Georgia, Kentucky, Tennessee,  
Oregon, California -- people wanting to help, wanting to give 
donations, wanting to organize fund drives,'' she says. Money is 
the best gift now when emergency supplies need to be purchased 
locally, she advises. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Dean also fields calls from Americans who have relatives in  
Kosovo. ``They're just terrified,'' she says. ``They can't get a 
hold of them. It's really awful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Televised images of the refugees make it easy for Americans to  
understand their humanitarian needs. 
</P>
<P>
	More challenging is comprehending their political problems.  
</P>
<P>
	In simple terms, Kosovo is a province of Serbia, the dominant  
republic of the Yugoslav federation. The Serbs view Kosovo, which 
is about the size of Connecticut, as ancestral land. They want it 
to remain a part of Serbia. Ninety percent of the people who live 
in Kosovo, however, are ethnic Albanians. They want independence 
from the Serbs. 
</P>
<P>
	Since NATO airstrikes began March 24, the Serbs have forced more  
than 360,000 Kosovars out of the province. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kosovars are leaving by train, bus, car, tractor and wagon.  
Some have trekked in snow over mountain passes to the safety of 
neighboring Macedonia to the south, Albania to the southwest and 
Montenegro to the west. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is really an organized emptying of Kosovo,'' Panos  
Moumtzis, senior public information officer at the refugee office , 
says between answering the phone and scanning 100 e-mails received 
overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	One day last week, Moumtzis kept one eye on a television set  
where his boss, Karen Koning AbuZayd, the U.S. representative to 
the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, was appearing on C-SPAN. 
``The majority of people coming out are women and children,'' she 
tells the TV audience. ``We do need to ask `Where are the men?''' 
</P>
<P>
	Every day, Moumtzis scans a stack of e-mails, such as one  
received over the weekend from Geneva. Written by a relief worker 
in Albania, it said: ``People arriving on foot are mostly women and 
children. People exhausted. ... Staff worked all night transferring 
new arrivals to a school nearby. Also distributed blankets, water 
and (high protein) bisquits. Many elderly are sick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Moumtzis talks on the phone to relief workers like Otim at a  
border crossing in Macedonia. Otim tells him that refugee 
registration slowed again when buses transporting refugees inland 
couldn't return to the border. 
</P>
<P>
	Otim says 300 refugees refused to get out of the buses at a  
camp. They preferred to stay with host families -- an issue now moot 
because the swelling number of refugees has forced the government 
to set up camps. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hang in there, Benny,'' Ms. Dean says before he signs off.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
