<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 19:12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Good Start to New Baseball Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Right off the bat, baseball showed signs that 1999 might be a  
repeat of a most remarkable season. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa took their first swings,  
fans had plenty to marvel at Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cal Ripken, of all people, hurt himself and had to leave the  
game. Kevin Brown, the $105 million man, was knocked out in his 
matchup with Randy Johnson. Detroit's Brian Moehler took a no-hit 
bid into the seventh inning. 
</P>
<P>
	And, just like last year, there were home runs. Lots of them.  
</P>
<P>
	Albert Belle broke loose for Baltimore. Raul Mondesi went wild  
for Los Angeles. Jose Canseco connected for Tampa Bay. Bernard 
Gilkey hit two off Brown. Juan Encarnacion wasted no time -- he 
homered for the Tigers on the first pitch of the afternoon at 
Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	After an opening day appetizer Sunday night in Mexico between  
Colorado and San Diego, baseball began in earnest Monday with 11 
more openers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I call this my holy day,'' Orioles fan Robin Steel said at  
Camden Yards. ``That's what it is for those of us who worship in 
the church of baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The morning began with the traditional opening-day parade in  
Cincinnati. Later, ailing Andres Galarraga threw out the first ball 
at Atlanta, via TV hook-up from his home. At night, Roger Clemens 
was to make his debut for the World Series champion New York 
Yankees at Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire, coming off his record 70-homer season, and the St.  
Louis Cardinals had to wait out rain showers to start their opener 
against Milwaukee. When they began, McGwire got a standing ovation 
at Busch Stadium before walking in his first plate appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa, who hit 66 last year, and the Chicago Cubs open Tuesday  
night at Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year I was ready, but I think in 1999 I am more ready  
because a lot of people are expecting me and Mark to come back and 
do the same way,'' Sosa said after a workout. ``I have to say that 
he's ready and I'm ready.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Belle was ready, too.  
</P>
<P>
	Playing his first game for the Orioles, the star who figures to  
challenge for the home-run lead this year in cozy Camden Yards hit 
a three-run homer that highlighted a 10-7 win over Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle's teammates and the crowd of 46,733 gave him a standing  
ovation, and the surly slugger responded with a rare curtain call. 
Belle also had an RBI single, more than enough to offset Canseco's 
398th career homer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles won despite losing Ripken, who left in the third  
inning because of a stiff lower back. There was no word on whether 
Ripken, who voluntarily ended his record streak of 2,632 straight 
games last year, would miss any more time. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the game, the Orioles unveiled a large, orange ``7'' in  
the third-base coaching box to honor Cal Ripken Sr., who died March 
24 of lung cancer at 63. 
</P>
<P>
	Cal Jr. did not get any hits, leaving him 122 short of 3,000.  
But Wade Boggs singled twice for the Devil Rays, giving him 76 
short of the milestone. 
</P>
<P>
	Mondesi delivered the biggest hits. His three-run homer with two  
outs in the bottom of the ninth tied it, and his two-run homer in 
the 11th lifted Los Angeles over Arizona 8-6. 
</P>
<P>
	Moehler, meanwhile, was the day's pitching star -- rather than  
Brown or Johnson. There was no evidence that umpires were calling 
higher strikes, as the commissioner's office ordered them to do. 
</P>
<P>
	Moehler came within eight outs of joining Bob Feller as the only  
pitchers to throw no-hitters on opening day as Detroit defeated 
Texas 11-5. Juan Gonzalez broke up Moehler's bid with a one-out 
single in the seventh. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sure, I was thinking about it,'' Moehler said.  
</P>
<P>
	His performance was far better than anything from the day's two  
marquee matchups -- Johnson vs. Brown at Dodger Stadium or Curt 
Schilling vs. Tom Glavine at Turner Field. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, baseball's first $100 million man, gave up three home  
runs for the Dodgers. Johnson, who signed for $52.4 million, was 
so-so for the Diamondbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	At Atlanta, neither Schilling nor Glavine was especially sharp  
as Philadelphia beat the Braves 7-4. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kansas City Royals once again proved that nothing counts  
until opening day. After posting baseball's best exhibition record 
at 22-9, they lost 5-3 to Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida Marlins, however, got off to a fine start. Worst in  
the majors last year with 108 losses, they beat the New York Mets 
6-2. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have a lot of fun this year,'' new Marlins  
owner John Henry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 05:51:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Sends Ship to Mediterranean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia has sent only one warship into the  
Mediterranean to monitor NATO operations against Yugoslavia, 
although it has permission to send seven more, a navy spokesman 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov again called for a  
halt to the NATO airstrikes in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to say again that the barbaric NATO bombardments are a  
tragic mistake,'' Primakov told the ITAR-Tass news agency. ``They 
not only destabilize the situation in Kosovo, but lead todirectly 
opposite results in this region, the Balkans, and Europe as a 
whole.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Russia strongly opposes the strikes, but its response has been  
largely symbolic. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscow has sent one intelligence-gathering ship, the Liman, from  
its Black Sea port, through the Bosporus strait and on to the 
Mediterranean. Russia dispatched the ship to keep an eye on NATO 
warships participating in the attacks on Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkey, a NATO member that controls the Bosporus, has given  
Russia permission to send seven additional ships through the narrow 
strait and on to the Mediterranean. The timetable authorized three 
ships to pass through the strait on Sunday and another four by 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	But Russia said today that six additional ships that might be  
sent to the region were still on standby at the Black Sea port of 
Sevastopol. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Liman is in the Mediterranean now,'' said Navy spokesman  
Igor Dygalo. ``The other six ships are in full readiness at their 
base. If a political decision is adopted ... they can go at any 
minute.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was not clear why Russia had not sent the additional ships.  
</P>
<P>
	NATO would prefer that the Russian ships stay out of the  
Mediterranean, although President Boris Yeltsin has said repeatedly 
that Moscow will not become involved militarily in the conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, an anti-NATO group said more than 800 Russians had  
volunteered to fight alongside Yugoslav forces. However, the 
Popular Patriotic Front said it was only registering volunteers at 
this point and was not sending anyone to Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is an ally of Yugoslavia, but Russia's desperate economic  
situation and declining military might have put severe constraints 
on its ability to influence NATO. The armed forces have been 
deteriorating for years, and the country badly needs Western loans 
to keep the tattered economy afloat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 05:36:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nazi Slaves Still Feel Victimized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- Eugeniusz Szobski can't forget toiling on  
the German assembly line, making car engines 12 hours a day, 
dressed in concentration camp stripes, then sleeping in filthy, 
lice-infested barracks. 
</P>
<P>
	His six months as a Nazi slave laborer at the Daimler-Benz  
factory near Mannheim ended in 1945 only because he caught typhus 
and then the war soon stopped. More than 700 of his 1,060 coworkers 
had died. 
</P>
<P>
	For compensation, Szobski got 1,100 zloty from the Polish-German  
Reconciliation Foundation in the early 1990s. That is about $280. 
</P>
<P>
	``One day of my work was worth a package of cigarettes,'' the  
75-year-old says bitterly. 
</P>
<P>
	He and other Polish survivors of German slave labor and  
concentration camps feel they are being victimized again, simply 
for being Poles. They point to survivors in Western countries who 
are being paid thousands of dollars by Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany says the situation is different because Poland's postwar  
communist government renounced compensation claims in 1953. 
</P>
<P>
	After communist rule fell in 1989, however, Poland's new  
democratic government pushed for compensation, and Germany paid 
$277 million, while stressing the money was humanitarian aid and 
not compensation. That is the money that provided the payment to 
Szobski and others. 
</P>
<P>
	Angry over the small payments, Szobski and 10 other aging Poles  
have taken their claims to a new arena: a class-action lawsuit in 
New Jersey seeking compensation from German companies doing 
business in America that benefitted from Nazi-era forced labor. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has been a segregation of victims after the war,'' said  
Jacek Turczynski, head of the reconciliation foundation, which is 
helping the plaintiffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want a global solution'' to the compensation issue, he  
added. ``We hope that thanks to filing the lawsuit in the United 
States, America will become a spokesman for all victims.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Germany has paid more than $57 billion to Nazi victims since  
World War II, including the money paid to Poland. Polish victims 
received less than 1 percent of the compensation even though Poles 
accounted for about a third of 7 million slave laborers, 
Turczynski's foundation says. 
</P>
<P>
	``Only because we are Polish, we are treated differently,''  
Szobski said. ``We have already experienced the Nazi theory of 
super-humans and sub-humans. Are we again sub-humans?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Holocaust victims in the United States launched a  
legal campaign against Swiss banks and German businesses that 
operate in America. The pressure forced the companies to address 
the claims, and Switzerland's two largest banks agreed in August to 
pay $1.25 billion to holders of dormant wartime accounts and their 
heirs. 
</P>
<P>
	A separate fund set up last year by German automaker Volkswagen  
has compensated at least 200 people so far, including a dozen 
Poles. 
</P>
<P>
	Twelve of Germany's largest companies, responding to more U.S.  
lawsuits, pledged recently to set up a similar fund to pay 
reparations to slave laborers, including those from eastern Europe. 
But few details about the fund -- how many victims will be eligible, 
how much they will receive -- have been settled. 
</P>
<P>
	The Polish survivors filed their own suit because they feared  
they might be excluded from a possible settlement between the 
German companies and victims living in the United States, or be 
offered less money. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as there were no lawsuits, German companies refused to  
talk,'' Turczynski said. ``Our lawsuit is intended to force German 
businesses to talk about our claims.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers and historians say Poland's 1953 declaration doesn't  
exclude compensation for individuals, so the Polish claimants are 
free to join in the U.S. court claims against German firms. 
</P>
<P>
	``Poles can file lawsuits in the United States as long as  
companies have assets here,'' said Allyn Z. Lite, the New Jersey 
lawyer representing the Poles. 
</P>
<P>
	Turczynski's foundation says the class-action lawsuit seeks at  
least $5,560 for each of the 450,000 surviving slave laborers 
registered with the group, for a total of $2.5 billion. That is 
about one-tenth the back wages owed Poles for their forced labor, 
the foundation says. 
</P>
<P>
	Jozef Wolan, one of the plaintiffs, was 16 when he was forced to  
work on a German farm in February 1942. 
</P>
<P>
	He received $380 in compensation for 38 months of work that  
included carrying 150-pound sacks of grain and unloading tons of 
sugar beets daily during harvest season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that somebody will notice us finally,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 13:25:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cancer Drug May Fight Heart Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The experimental drug that caused a sensation when  
it was found to wipe out cancer in mice by choking off the tumors' 
blood supply is also showing promise against heart disease. 
</P>
<P>
	The treatment involves the Harvard-developed drug endostatin,  
which has been shown to be remarkably potent against cancer but has 
not been tested yet on people. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the same team that discovered endostatin found that in  
mice, at least, the drug may also greatly slow the development of 
atherosclerosis, or hardening of the arteries. Atherosclerosis is a 
buildup of fatty deposits. 
</P>
<P>
	The research raises the possibility that a new category of  
drugs, the blood vessel inhibitors, may be useful weapons against 
both heart disease and cancer, the two most important diseases of 
the industrialized world. 
</P>
<P>
	A team led by Dr. Judah Folkman of Harvard Medical School and  
Children's Hospital in Boston reported the development in Tuesday's 
issue of the American Heart Association journal Circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	Folkman pioneered the study of angiogenesis, the growth of new  
blood vessels. Endostatin is a natural protein that blocks blood 
vessel formation. Without a blood supply, cancer in lab animals 
often stops growing and disappears. 
</P>
<P>
	Heart disease also involves unwanted tissue growth -- the  
accumulation of cholesterol, blood cells and smooth muscle cells in 
lumps known as plaque. Plaque growing in the heart arteries is the 
chief cause of heart attacks and angina pain. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts have long noticed that plaque often has its own network  
of tiny blood vessels called capillaries. 
</P>
<P>
	``By blocking them, perhaps we can alter the progression of the  
disease,'' said Dr. Karen Moulton, who conducted the experiment in 
Folkman's lab. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 16-week experiment involving 73 mice, the researchers  
tested endostatin on animals that were fed a high-cholesterol diet. 
They found that those on the drug averaged 85 percent less plaque 
buildup in their hearts' aortas than did untreated animals. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very exciting concept,'' said Dr. Stephen Epstein of  
Washington Hospital Center in Washington. ``If the data can be 
validated by other labs, it represents a whole new paradigm for 
strategies to prevent atherosclerosis and its complications.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Epstein acknowledged that the discovery also presents  
``a very important conundrum,'' because drugs that promote blood 
vessel growth, rather than block it, are already one of the hottest 
areas of heart disease research. 
</P>
<P>
	Epstein and others are testing the use of growth proteins that  
trigger the body to sprout new blood vessels. When injected into 
the heart, these proteins induce the growth of a new blood supply. 
This nourishes heart muscle that is starved by clogged arteries. 
</P>
<P>
	Some human testing suggests this treatment can relieve the  
effects of atherosclerosis. But Epstein said the latest work raises 
the possibility that it could also make the underlying disease 
worse by promoting the growth of plaque. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Dr. Jeffrey Isner of St. Elizabeth's Medical Center in  
Boston said his own animal experiments show no evidence that 
stimulating the growth of blood vessels will speed up 
atherosclerosis or do anything else bad. 
</P>
<P>
	Moulton speculated that both treatments could eventually find a  
place in controlling heart disease. Blood vessel inhibitors like 
endostatin might be given at a relatively early stage of disease, 
just as cholesterol-lowering statins are now used to keep blood 
vessels healthy. The blood vessel stimulators would be reserved for 
relieving arteries that are already badly clogged. 
</P>
<P>
	At EntreMed Inc. in Rockville, Md., which is developing  
endostatin, spokeswoman Mary P. Sundeed said the company is 
concentrating on the cancer uses of the drug and has no plans to 
test it against heart disease. 
</P>
<P>
	She said initial safety testing of endostatin in cancer patients  
should begin this summer at the University of Wisconsin and M.D. 
Anderson Cancer Center in Houston. 




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
