<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4:30 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Reiterates Kosovo Stance  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today reaffirmed his  
commitment to assist Kosovo refugees and vowed to continue the 
campaign against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic ``until we 
prevail.'' Clinton spoke to a group of private humanitarian relief 
leaders and federal officials at the White House. Meanwhile at the 
Pentagon, spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the U.S. military has for 
the first time obtained satellite images that ``indicate atrocities 
have taken place'' by Serb troops against ethnic Albanians. The 
images show ``armored personnel carriers and tanks appearing to 
herd groups of people into a smaller area,'' Bacon said, although 
there's no evidence about what happened to the people. 

</P>
<P>
	Cohen Warns Yugoslavia of Attacks  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen says  
Serb military and police forces are ``open and vulnerable'' to 
stepped-up NATO air assaults. Cohen warned the Serbs that NATO 
attacks against Yugoslavia will be greatly expanded in the coming 
days. ``We're going after his tanks, his armored units, his 
artillery, those forces on the ground that are carrying out this 
horrific ethnic cleansing. They are going to be targeted now and 
taken out,'' Cohen said. 

</P>
<P>
	Libya Delivers Pan Am Bomb Suspects  
</P>
<P>
	THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- Libya today handed over two  
suspects in the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am jet over Lockerbie, 
Scotland, triggering suspension of sanctions that isolated Libya 
from the West. The surrender of alleged former intelligence agents 
Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah means the two 
men can be tried in the Netherlands under Scottish law on charges 
of planting the suitcase bomb that blew up Pan Am Flight 103, 
killing 270 people. The United Nations had imposed sanctions on 
Libya in 1992 and 1993 for its refusal to turn over the suspects. 

</P>
<P>
	Suspect in Gay Attack Pleads Guilty  
</P>
<P>
	LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- A man pleaded guilty today in the slaying  
of gay college student Matthew Shepard, cutting short a trial that 
could have ended with the death penalty. Russell Henderson, 21, 
pleaded guilty to felony murder and kidnapping. He could get two 
life sentences. Authorities said Henderson and Aaron McKinney, 21, 
posed as homosexuals and lured Shepard out of a bar last October, 
kidnapped and pistol-whipped him and left him tied to a fence in 
the cold. The University of Wyoming student died five days later. 

</P>
<P>
	Defendants Have Right to Silence  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Criminal defendants who plead guilty have a  
constitutional right to remain silent at sentencing without judges 
holding it against them, the Supreme Court ruled today. Holding 
such defendants' silence against them would impose ``an 
impermissible burden on the exercise of the constitutional right 
against compelled self-incrimination,'' the court ruled 5-4 in a 
Pennsylvania drug case. 

</P>
<P>
	Cancer Drug May Fight Heart Disease  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The experimental drug that caused a sensation when  
it was found to wipe out cancer in mice is also showing promise 
against heart disease. The treatment involves the drug endostatin, 
which has been shown to be remarkably potent against cancer but has 
not been tested yet on people. The same Harvard Medical School and 
Children's Hospital researchers have found that in mice, at least, 
the drug may also greatly slow the development of atherosclerosis, 
or hardening of the arteries. 

</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com, Wal-Mart Settle Lawsuit  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Amazon.com and Wal-Mart Stores are settling a  
lawsuit charging that the online bookseller hired computer system 
managers away from Wal-Mart to steal the retailer's trade secrets. 
The suit also charged that Amazon.com targeted Wal-Mart's software 
vendors to learn more about the retailer's information systems. In 
the settlement, Amazon.com agreed to reassign some of the former 
Wal-Mart employees to jobs that don't mirror the positions they 
held at Wal-Mart. Amazon.com also said it would return Wal-Mart 
information brought by the former employees. No damages are to be 
paid. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 174.82, Ends Over 10,000  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology issues propelled the stock market  
higher today, lifting the Dow Jones industrial average above 
10,000: The Dow closed up 174.82 at 10,007.33. On the NYSE, gainers 
led losers 1,692-1,307. The rally also sent the Nasdaq into record 
territory, closing up 66.73 at 2,560.10. The previous high close 
was 2,510.09. 

</P>
<P>
	O's Opener Honors Cal Ripken Sr.  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The Baltimore Orioles opened their season today  
by remembering Cal Ripken Sr. Before the game against Tampa Bay, 
the Orioles unveiled a large, orange ``7'' (Ripken's number) in the 
third-base coaching box. In addition, the Orioles will wear a patch 
of the No. 7 on the right sleeves of their jerseys this season. 
Ripken, who died March 24 of lung cancer at age 63, served 36 years 
with the Orioles as a player, scout, coach and manager. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  

</P>
