<TEXT>
<P>
	Libyan Suspects Handed Over  
</P>
<P>
	THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- U.N. sanctions against Libya have  
been suspended after the North African nation handed over two 
suspects in the deadly bombing of a jetliner over Scotland. The 
sanctions prevented air travel to and from Libya, and isolated 
Libya from the West for the past seven years. Former Libyan 
intelligence agents Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa 
Fhimah are accused of planting a suitcase bomb that blew up Pan Am 
Flight 103 on Dec. 21, 1988, killing 270 people. They will be tried 
under Scottish law. 

</P>
<P>
	Cohen Warns Yugoslavia of Attacks  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen says  
Serb military and police forces are ``open and vulnerable'' to 
stepped-up NATO air assaults. Cohen warned the Serbs that NATO is 
about to unleash significant firepower, and said the air campaign 
against Yugoslavia will be expanded greatly once the go-ahead is 
given for Army combat helicopters and anti-personnel missile 
launchers. The United States has committed several Apache choppers 
that allow for attacks at close range. Cohen says the copters will 
individually target the Yugoslav troops and special police, the 
forces he says are responsible for what the ``ethnic cleansing'' 
campaign in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Countries To Take In Refugees  
</P>
<P>
	BLACE, Macedonia (AP) -- NATO officials say another 44,000 ethnic  
Albanians left Kosovo yesterday, with most of them heading to 
Albania. That brings to 360,000 the number of Kosovars who have 
been driven from the war-torn Serbian province the past two weeks. 
But some NATO countries will start taking in some of the refugees. 
Germany is ready to accept 40,000; the United States, 20,000; and 
Turkey, 20,000, NATO said. Defense Secretary William Cohen said the 
Kosovars could be temporarily housed at U.S. bases in Guam or Cuba. 

</P>
<P>
	Protests Held at Gay Death Trial  
</P>
<P>
	LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- Young people dressed as angels stood  
silently today outside the courthouse where one of the men accused 
of killing a gay student is on trial, trying to block from view a 
group of anti-gay demonstrators. Meanwhile, jury selection in the 
trial of Russell Henderson was delayed until tomorrow. Henderson 
and two others are charged with the beating death last October of 
University of Wyoming student Matthew Shepard. Shepard was brutally 
beaten, tied to a fence and left to die. 

</P>
<P>
	Egypt Drops Rape Law Called Failure  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has decreed  
an end to a law allowing rapists to go free if they marry their 
victims. Mubarak said the law ``encouraged the criminals to 
perpetrate their crime.'' Parents of rape victims have used the 
law, which dates to 1904, as a way to regain family honor. Rapists 
have used it to escape punishment. Opponents argued that the law 
was in victims' interest, because otherwise their marriage 
prospects were slim. 

</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com, Wal-Mart Settle Lawsuit  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Amazon.com and Wal-Mart Stores are settling a  
lawsuit charging that the online bookseller hired computer system 
managers away from Wal-Mart to steal the retailer's trade secrets. 
The suit charged that Amazon.com targeted the retailer's 
information systems, which include data on sales, inventory and 
consumer buying habits. Amazon.com agreed to reassign some of the 
former Wal-Mart employees to jobs that don't mirror the positions 
they held at Wal-Mart. Amazon.com also said it would return 
Wal-Mart information brought by the former employees. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Back Over 10,000  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks climbed higher today as investors reacted  
to signs in the government's employment report that the economy's 
fast growth rate may be moderating. Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow 
industrials were up 175.93 to 10,008.44. Advancing issues on the 
New York Stock Exchange led decliners 1,610-1,261. The Nasdaq was 
up 53.52 to 2,546.89. 

</P>
