<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China To Visit U.S for Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- On the eve of Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji's  
visit, U.S. and Chinese trade officials intensified efforts Monday 
to strike a deal granting China its long-sought membership in the 
World Trade Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	But the administration insisted any agreement would have to meet  
demands by U.S. manufacturers and farmers for access to China's 
huge market as a way of shrinking America's record $57 billion 
trade deficit with China, second only to Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Cassidy, America's top negotiator on Chinese trade  
issues, held day-long discussions over remaining disagreements with 
a delegation led by Long Yongtu, China's vice minister for trade. 
Some of the biggest sticking points include Chinese barriers to 
exports of American farm products, chemicals and operations by U.S. 
insurance companies. 
</P>
<P>
	China has made a number of concessions in recent weeks in hopes  
of finally overcoming U.S. objections to its membership in the 
Geneva-based organization that sets the rules for world trade. 
</P>
<P>
	But the trade talks are coming at a time of serious strains in  
U.S.-Chinese relations over the issues of human rights and charges 
that China stole U.S. nuclear secrets during the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu, the first Chinese premier to visit the United States in 15  
years, would like to capture a WTO agreement as the centerpiece of 
his trip, but the administration insisted Monday that it will not 
accept a bad package. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that rather than looking at a calendar, we're going  
to look at the details of a deal and we're not going to take 
anything but a good deal,'' presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart 
told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu was scheduled to arrive in Los Angeles on Tuesday for the  
start of a nine-day American trip that will include stops in 
Washington for meetings Thursday with Clinton as well as visits to 
Denver, Chicago, New York and Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with Wall Street Journal executives, distributed  
Monday, the Chinese premier accused President Clinton of caving in 
to Congress and changing the standards for China's entry into the 
WTO. 
</P>
<P>
	He told the newspaper that Chinese concessions had brought a WTO  
agreement within reach, but ``due to pressure from the U.S. 
Congress, the U.S. government has shown a change in attitude.'' He 
called Washington's new demands ``unreasonable'' and said China is 
not inclined to make further concessions. ``Make no mistake,'' he 
said. ``China is not begging for accession to the WTO.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Outside trade experts were split on whether the current strained  
state of U.S.-Chinese relations would put a WTO agreement out of 
reach. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Hufbauer, economist at the Institute for International  
Economics, a Washington think tank, said there were strong 
pressures within the administration to clinch a WTO agreement since 
Clinton's other trade initiatives are tied up in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``This may be the only thing that Clinton will be able to  
achieve on his trade agenda during the remainder of his time in 
office,'' Hufbauer said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Greg Mastel, an economist at the Economic Strategy  
Institute, said Congress won't go along with a WTO deal. ``A deal 
that was seen as a sell-out would be a big political problem for 
President Clinton,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mastel predicted that the best outcome China could expect would  
be a ``framework'' agreement -- a ``face saving move'' -- where both 
sides would spell out where agreements have been reached, points of 
differences still remaining and set a deadline for concluding the 
talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu's visit comes at a time when the United States is upset over  
a Communist Party-ordered crackdown on Chinese trying to form a 
democratic party and allegations of Chinese espionage at U.S. 
nuclear labs. For their part, the Chinese are upset with America's 
role in the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia, which the Chinese have 
condemned as a dangerous attack on international security. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Lockhart stressed that America's ``important relationship  
with China'' requires regular high-level discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockhart refused comment on a published report that the chief of  
China's military intelligence secretly directed $300,000 to 
Clinton's re-election campaign in 1996. He said the allegations 
were ``the subject of an on-going investigation at the Justice 
Department.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Times said that former Democratic fund-raiser  
Johnny Chung had given an account of the $300,000 payment to 
federal investigators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
