<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Pitchers Face Major Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan has had a hard time of it lately: recession,  
unemployment and sinking corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Now even Japanese pitchers in the major leagues are getting  
hammered. 
</P>
<P>
	Hideo Nomo has fallen from rookie stardom to a Chicago Cubs  
minor league team. Hideki Irabu was denigrated by New York Yankees 
owner and dropped from the five-man rotation last week after 
struggling in spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just can't be helped,'' said fishmonger Masao Nakagawa,  
standing over racks of dried squid in his Tokyo market stall. 
``There are good times, and then there are bad times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The demotions have disappointed Japanese fans who used to watch  
TV specials with delight when a few of their own made it to 
baseball's pinnacle. 
</P>
<P>
	``A cold season for Japanese big league pitchers,'' read a  
headline last week in the national Asahi newspaper. ``For Japanese 
pitchers, jumping to the majors is getting more remote.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among Japanese major leaguers, perhaps no one's star has fallen  
as far and as fast as Nomo's. 
</P>
<P>
	The right-hander broke into the big leagues in May 1995 with the  
Los Angeles Dodgers and became an overnight sensation. He won the 
National League Rookie of the Year award and led the league with 
236 strikeouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Then it all seemed to fall apart. The Dodgers traded him to the  
New York Mets last year. The Mets gave up on him after he went 0-2 
with a 7.62 ERA this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he's with Chicago's Triple-A Iowa farm team, getting just a  
handful of starts to prove himself before the Cubs decide whether 
to add him to their roster or let him go. 
</P>
<P>
	The reversal of fortune has knocked him the radar screens of  
many Japanese fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't talk much about Nomo these days,'' said Ryuichi  
Matsuda, an 18-year-old college student. 
</P>
<P>
	Irabu, meanwhile, made it to the big time after the Yankees won  
a bidding war in 1997 and signed him to a four-year, $12 million 
contract. The pitcher was 13-9 with a 4.06 ERA last year. 
</P>
<P>
	But Irabu has had a tough spring, going 0-2 with an 8.38 ERA.  
Yankees owner George Steinbrenner called him a ``fat ... toad'' 
last week, complaining about Irabu's weight (252 pounds) and lack 
of hustle. Irabu has been dropped temporarily from the starting 
rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Yankees broke camp in Florida, Irabu asked to remain  
behind ``to think about many things.'' He has since rejoined the 
club and apologized to his teammates for his absence. 
</P>
<P>
	There are a handful of other Japanese pitchers in the majors.  
Masato Yoshii is hanging on as the Mets' fifth starter after 
signing a $5 million, two-year contract in November. Shigetoshi 
Hasegawa is a reliever with the Anaheim Angels. 
</P>
<P>
	Some in Japan point to the American baseball system as a factor  
in their players' downfalls. 
</P>
<P>
	Hiromitsu Ochiai, a former player with the Yomiuri Giants,  
criticizes the way in which the Mets got rid of Nomo, saying a 
Japanese team would never release a player right before the opening 
of a season. 
</P>
<P>
	``The difference is that in Japan, we focus on how to cultivate  
a player,'' he wrote for the Weekly Asahi magazine. ``In America, 
they just try to pick the best among the players they have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kenichi Ida, a 26-year-old worker in a vegetable store in Tokyo,  
suggested that Japanese too small to compete with the bigger 
American players. 
</P>
<P>
	``Japanese body power is different from Americans,'' he said,  
gobbling down an early lunch of rice and seaweed flakes outside his 
store. ``So it's harder for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anyway, he said, baseball is not really on people's minds much  
anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're more interested here in soccer,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
