<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Four Shot To Death in Mich. Eatery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Hanna Akrawi became worried when a security  
company called to say the alarm at her family's restaurant hadn't 
been set when the eatery closed. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time Mrs. Akrawi entered the Prestige Barbecue on Sunday  
morning, her 12-year-old son, her husband, his brother and a cook 
were dead. Each had been shot several times in the head. 
</P>
<P>
	The restaurant appeared to have been ransacked and money from  
Saturday's sales was missing by the time the bodies were found, 
police homicide Inspector William Rice said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police identified the victims as restaurant owner Jamal Akrawi,  
49, his 12-year-old son Tommy, both of Oak Park; Akrawi's older 
brother, Abed Akrawi, who was visiting from Iraq; and cook Paul 
Scott, 19, a high school senior from Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said there were no signs of forced entry, and speculated  
that the killer or killers entered the restaurant about the time it 
closed at midnight Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rice told the Detroit Free Press that police questioned several  
people Sunday. ``We're looking at all the ex-employees,'' he said. 
``We're going through them as fast as we can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Nofar of Livonia, a cousin of Jamal Akrawi, said Jamal and  
Hanna Akrawi took turns working shifts at the restaurant, while 
Tommy sometimes worked the cash register. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the only way they could survive,'' he said. ``They're a  
very hardworking family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Scott, the youngest of nine siblings, started cooking at  
Prestige last summer and wanted to study culinary arts after 
graduation, his relatives said. 
</P>
<P>
	One brother, Michael Smith, lives less than 100 yards from the  
restaurant and watched Sunday as police wrapped yellow crime scene 
tape around the business. Soon after, an officer approached him 
with the news. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't want to believe it,'' Smith said. ``It's not the type  
of thing you talk about. I was hoping he was at home and not at 
work.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
