<DOCNO> APW19990405.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 01:53:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Longtime Rival Lawyers Square Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- Courtroom veterans Wyatt Skaggs and Cal  
Rerucha have faced each other many times, but never before with the 
national media looking on and a man's life at stake. 
</P>
<P>
	Skaggs is the defense attorney and Rerucha the prosecutor in the  
trial of Russell Henderson, who is charged with first-degree 
murder, kidnapping and aggravated robbery in the fatal beating Oct. 
6 of gay university student Matthew Shepard. 
</P>
<P>
	The violence of the crime -- Shepard died from massive skull  
fractures after he was tied to a fence and pistol-whipped -- and 
suspicion Shepard may have been targeted because he was gay have 
put the town and the lawyers in the spotlight. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both are good trial attorneys,'' said prosecutor Jon Forwood.  
``There's no mismatch there. Each can handle himself quite well in 
court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fiercely competitive, the two can also bring out the worst in  
each other. 
</P>
<P>
	In the case of an accused rapist, Rerucha became incensed after  
Skaggs told the jury his client was good-looking and ``could have 
many, many women if he wanted to. ... Is this a type of guy who 
would commit a rape?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rerucha responded that serial killer Ted Bundy was also  
good-looking, a remark noted by the Wyoming Supreme Court on appeal 
but not deemed egregious enough to overturn the conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was almost as though Wyatt had invited it,'' said Ted  
Lauer, professor of law at the University of Wyoming. ``The level 
of aggression and debate between the two was so intense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Wyatt can be one of the meanest people in the whole world in  
court. Out of court he can be brusque, sharp and short,'' said 
Lauer. ``He doesn't mince words with anybody. If he doesn't like 
you, he'll tell you so to your face.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both men are extremely private, refusing to hold news  
conferences and seldom offering interviews. Neither would comment 
to The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	In a rare public statement in December, Skaggs railed at  
Rerucha's decision to seek the death penalty against Henderson. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been other cases in this county that have been just  
as heinous or more heinous in which he has not requested the death 
penalty,'' he said. ``I think it's heavy-handed to say the least 
and somewhat politically motivated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lauer disagreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``Cal is an extremely conscientious person,'' he said. ``He  
doesn't do anything without agonizing over it. I'm sure he agonized 
over the decision to seek the death penalty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A sign outside Skaggs' office refers to him as ``country  
lawyer,'' but prosecutors know better. He has become the top 
criminal defense attorney in the state public defender's office and 
often is assigned the toughest cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Skaggs grew up the son of a flying instructor in Cody, a town on  
the outskirts of Yellowstone National Park. He told The Cody 
Enterprise last October that he was ``a bit of a rebel'' while 
growing up. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe that's one reason he so strongly defends each of his  
clients, no matter the charge. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every person, no matter how poor or reprehensible, deserves  
the best representation possible,'' he said. ``That's something 
that was drilled into me by my parents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rerucha, former paperboy and son of a Laramie railroad worker,  
enjoyed early political success. He was elected student body 
president at the University of Wyoming and after law school, 
alternated between private practice and work as deputy county 
attorney. In 1986, he ran for prosecutor and won. Albany County 
voters have re-elected him three times. 
</P>
<P>
	The Shepard case is not the first time he has drawn national  
attention. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1990, he charged a pregnant woman with child abuse because  
she allegedly consumed high quantities of alcohol. A judge 
dismissed the case because Rerucha could not show any damage had 
occurred to the unborn child. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, both lawyers will take part in a hearing called by 2nd  
District Judge Jeffrey A. Donnell. The meeting has pushed back jury 
selection to Tuesday and opening statements from Tuesday to 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Security remained tight at the courthouse, where visitors had to  
weave around police tape to the only open entrance and pass through 
a metal detector. Police have been planning for demonstrations for 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to anticipate as best we can both for what we  
know is going to occur and for what we can anticipate is going to 
occur,'' said Laramie Police Cmdr. Dale Stalder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 15:23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Reiterates Kosovo Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The American-led NATO air campaign against  
Yugoslavia will continue ``unceasing and unrelenting'' until 
President Slobodan Milosevic reverses course in Kosovo, President 
Clinton said Monday as the alliance reported a quickened pace of 
airstrikes and the arrival of more firepower. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our plan is to persist until we prevail,'' Clinton said at the  
White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Anticipating that Milosevic may soon declare his goals in Kosovo  
achieved and propose peace, the Clinton administration pointedly 
declared that it will not tolerate a Kosovo emptied of ethnic 
Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	``Milosevic may think he's finished'' at that point, Pentagon  
spokesman Kenneth Bacon said. ``We will not be finished.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Previewing a planned bolstering of NATO's airpower, Defense  
Secretary William Cohen said U.S. Army Apache attack helicopters 
would target Serb military and police forces that are now ``open 
and vulnerable'' in Kosovo. The helicopters probably will not be 
ready for action for more than a week, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going after his tanks, his armored units, his artillery,  
those forces on the ground that are carrying out this horrific 
ethnic cleansing,'' Cohen said in an Associated Press interview. 
``They are going to be targeted now and taken out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R.-Ill., dated  
Sunday, Clinton said the Apaches and supporting forces would 
operate from Albania. ``The mission does not include any planned 
deployment of ground troops'' into Kosovo, Clinton said. The 
duration of the mission ``will depend on the course of events,'' he 
wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	In his remarks Monday at the White House, Clinton said Milosevic  
faced a choice of ending the violence against ethnic Albanians in 
Kosovo or watching NATO systematically diminish the Yugoslav 
leader's ability to impose his will on Kosovo and stay in power. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know we are up against a dictator who has shown time and  
again that he would rather rule over rubble than not rule at all, 
someone who recognizes no limits on his behavior except those 
imposed by others,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Mr. Milosevic does not do what is necessary, NATO will  
continue an air campaign. It will be undiminished, unceasing and 
unrelenting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even as it worked out plans for expanding U.S. military  
involvement in Kosovo, the administration was scrambling on the 
humanitarian front. It flew more emergency relief supplies to 
Albania and worked on plans for accommodating 20,000 Kosovar 
refugees, probably at the Guantanamo Naval Station in Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen and other administration officials insisted that the  
decision to airlift refugees out of the Balkans was not meant to 
indicate NATO had given up its goal of reversing the forced exodus 
from Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a temporary arrangement designed to deal with an  
emergency problem; it's not designed to have permanent relocation 
of these refugees,'' said State Department spokesman James P. 
Rubin. He said the idea was to ``alleviate the bottleneck'' of 
hundreds of thousands of refugees in Albania and Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said Secretary of State Madeleine Albright had received a  
report on the plight of the ethnic Albanians inside Kosovo from 
David Sheffer, the U.S. ambassador-at-large for war crimes. Based 
on interviews he conducted with refugees, Sheffer concluded that 
Albanians are being driven from Kosovo not by NATO bombing but by a 
systematic expulsion by Serb military and police forces, Rubin 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheffer reported that Pristina, the Kosovar capital, is being  
expunged neighborhood by neighborhood with seemingly calculated 
efficiencies. He said Kosovars are shaken down for their cash, 
money and jewelry, and those who resist expulsion are killed by 
gunfire or by torching their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The use of Apache helicopters, subject to final approval by NATO  
political authorities and by President Clinton, would mark an 
important turning point in the allies' war in Yugoslavia. The 
higher-flying NATO jets used so far have been unable to make a dent 
in the Serb armed forces operating in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are now open and vulnerable to this kind of an attack,''  
Cohen said. ``The Apaches are a very capable aircraft that will go 
in low and start to target them individually. It has a good deal of 
firepower and is going to represent an enormous challenge to the 
forces in opposition. He's going to be paying a high penalty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Apaches, used heavily against Iraqi forces in the 1991 Gulf War,  
are armed with laser-guided anti-tank missiles. Their crews are 
trained to fly low to the ground, either day or night, and in most 
kinds of weather. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kosovo, the Apaches would face a considerable threat from a  
variety of Serb air defense weapons, including shoulder-fired guns 
and anti-aircraft artillery. To suppress that threat, the Army 
plans to deploy multiple launch rocket systems to Albania armed 
with long-range missiles that can hit air defenses. 
</P>
<P>
	As NATO presses ahead with its bombing under clearing skies in  
Yugoslavia, officials at U.S. European Command in Germany began 
assembling Task Force Hawk, which will have 24 Apache helicopters, 
plus a variety of support forces, including 26 UH-60 Blackhawk and 
CH-47 Chinook helicopters, for cargo lifting and medical 
evacuation. The Army force would involve about 2,600 soldiers, 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO officials were expected to give their formal OK to the use  
of Apaches, although the decision lay in Clinton's hands. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Cohen spokesman Kenneth Bacon said Sunday that the 24  
Apache attack helicopters offered to NATO could be in place in 
Albania in seven to 10 days, Army officials speaking privately said 
Monday it might take two weeks or longer to get the full contingent 
of about 2,600 soldiers in place. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Navy aircraft carrier USS Theodore Roosevelt and  
its battle group entered the Adriatic Sea on Monday. The carrier's 
contingent of F/A-18 Hornet and other strike aircraft are expected 
to begin flying missions on Tuesday. The battle group includes 
three ships and one submarine armed with Tomahawk cruise missiles, 
which have been a key weapon in NATO's air campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 09:44:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Holds Easter Egg Roll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Moms wearing pink bunny ears, toddlers bundled  
against a chilly breeze and dads toting movie cameras streamed to 
the White House today for the 121st annual Easter egg roll. 
</P>
<P>
	President and Mrs. Clinton greeted thousands of people gathered  
on the South Lawn, which was still damp from a morning drizzle. 
Sharing the stage with three adult-sized bunnies, the president 
asked the crowd to pray for troops and refugees in the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	Then the president blew a whistle to start the festivities.  
</P>
<P>
	``Are you ready?'' Clinton asked children waiting to begin  
rolling eggs. ``All right. On your mark, ready, set go!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Using white plastic spoons, the children propelled hard-boiled  
eggs along the lawn to a finish line. For their effort, they got a 
plastic egg filled with candy and other gifts. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House Easter egg roll has a century-old tradition. In  
the late 1870s, Congress scrapped its own Easter Monday event after 
deciding that the Capitol lawn should not be used as a children's 
playground, according to historian William Seale. The event was 
moved to the White House where it's been held every year except 
during World War I and World War II. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 02:23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clemens To Make N.Y. Yankees Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Roger Clemens against Gil Heredia. That's  
almost as much of a mismatch as, say, the New York Yankees against 
the Oakland Athletics. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens, the five-time Cy Young Award winner, makes his debut in  
a Yankees uniform tonight as the defending World Series champions 
open their season against Heredia, a journeyman with a 22-24 career 
record, and the lowly A's. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it will be very special -- especially since I'm with a  
new club and a new bunch of guys who are going to be behind me. 
I'll have to channel my emotions early and make them work for me,'' 
Clemens said. ``I'm not nervous, but I get excited about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heredia, who became the A's opening day starter only because  
staff ace Kenny Rogers is recovering from a stiff elbow, pitched 7 
2-3 scoreless innings in a win over the Yankees in New York last 
September and said he's trying to ignore the comparisons with 
Clemens -- who has 233 career victories. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really haven't even thought about Rogers Clemens vs.  
Heredia. I can't even put them in perspective,'' the A's 
right-hander said. ``I'm just taking it as far as me against the 
Yankees. Roger has nothing to do with my performance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens, who won his last 15 games in 1998 en route to his  
unanimous selection as Cy Young Award winner for the Toronto Blue 
Jays, was traded to the Yankees in mid-February for pitchers David 
Wells and Graeme Lloyd and second baseman Homer Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something when you're facing the best team in baseball  
and the best pitcher in baseball over the last 10 years,'' A's 
designated hitter Matt Stairs said. ``There will be a lot of 
adrenalin, we'll just be trying to keep our emotions down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because he'll be wearing the Yankees' road grays, he won't start  
in the famed pinstripes until Saturday at home against Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees interim manager Don Zimmer, taking over while Joe Torre  
recovers from prostate cancer surgery, said he doesn't expect 
Clemens to be affected by the attention he'll receive in his first 
start in a Yankees uniform. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a five-time Cy Young winner, so it's just another day at  
work for him. And that's the way he works every day, anyhow,'' 
Zimmer said. ``You go in the clubhouse and you've got to look in 
nine places to find him. But wherever he's at, he'll be working and 
doing something. There aren't too many pitchers who can keep up 
with the conditioning that Roger Clemens goes through every day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees are coming off a tumultuous spring that included the  
Clemens trade, Torre's diagnosis with prostate cancer and Darryl 
Strawberry's battle to come back from cancer surgery late last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Another twist was added in recent days when owner George  
Steinbrenner called Hideki Irabu a ``fat ... toad'' and decided to 
leave the pitcher behind when the team broke training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	But after Zimmer penciled in Ramiro Mendoza instead of Irabu for  
the start Wednesday at Oakland in the Yankees' third game of the 
season, Steinbrenner announced he was hoping Irabu would start that 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm the manager, I try to do what's right for the ballclub. My  
mind is not going to be changed by anybody,'' Zimmer replied 
Saturday night in Los Angeles. ``George Steinbrenner has been good 
to me, but, to me, you can't sit back here and be a little wimp.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irabu rejoined the Yankees on Sunday and apologized for his  
absence. Zimmer, meanwhile, reiterated that Mendoza would start 
Wednesday and that Irabu would be in the bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I talked to the boss (Steinbrenner) this morning, and he said  
he didn't mandate that anyone start,'' general manager Brian 
Cashman said. ``This isn't as big as it's been made. There was 
certainly a bump in the road the last few days, there's no 
question. We've dealt with bigger things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It has been a much quieter spring for the Athletics, who  
finished last in the AL West the past two seasons and likely will 
end up there again this year. They look forward to the challenge of 
starting their season against a team that won a record 125 games 
last season and added a future Hall of Famer as its No. 1 starter. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know they're the best team in baseball, and we can find out  
where we measure up real quickly,'' A's manager Art Howe said. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakland first baseman Jason Giambi knows tonight's game will  
take on even greater importance because of Clemens' debut with the 
Yankees, and just hopes the A's are catching the defending 
champions at a good time. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the best time to face them,'' he said, ``before they  
get rolling.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
