<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 14:15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rules on Shellfish Harvesting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) -- In a big victory for Washington state's  
Indian tribes, the U.S. Supreme Court on Monday left intact a 
ruling affirming their right to gather shellfish from privately 
owned beaches. 
</P>
<P>
	The court rejected without comment an appeal of a lower-court  
ruling that said the 17 tribes' shellfish-gathering rights are 
guaranteed under 19th-century treaties. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once again, the Supreme Court has made it clear that the  
tribes' treaty-reserved rights to natural resources in western 
Washington are as valid today as the day the treaties were 
signed,'' said Billy Frank Jr., an elder in the Nisqually Tribe. 
</P>
<P>
	State officials, shellfish growers and private property owners  
had challenged the lower-court decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Barbara Lindsay, a spokeswoman for some of the thousands of  
property owners affected, said: ``We're just stunned that this 
could happen in America, that our property rights and our privacy 
rights could be trampled.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Commercial shellfish growers contend the ruling could threaten  
their livelihoods because the Indians will be able to gather 
naturally occurring shellfish even from cultivated areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Tribal leaders said Monday's court action does not mean Indians  
will be indiscriminately tramping private beaches to dig clams, 
mussels and other shellfish. Among other things, tribal members 
will be permitted to harvest on private property only five days a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a long process before you can go on a beach and  
harvest,'' said Doug Williams, a spokesman for the Northwest Indian 
Fisheries Commission. ``There must be a biological assessment of 
the area, sampling and testing, and a written notice. In fact, as 
far as I know, there has been only one harvest off of a private 
landowner's beach'' since the 1994 ruling on tribal shellfish 
rights by a federal judge in Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Ms. Lindsay said, in the end ``we will have people on our  
beaches, invading our privacy'' to dig for shellfish. 
</P>
<P>
	``When people bought these properties, they had no idea there  
were treaty rights to shellfish,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under treaties signed in 1855, the tribes gave up most of their  
land in then-Washington Territory in exchange for reservations, 
money and the right to continue fishing in traditional fishing 
grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	A series of court rulings during the 1970s defined what areas  
are traditional Indian fishing grounds, and affirmed the tribes' 
right to take up to half of the salmon and other fish. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, U.S. District Edward Rafeedie said shellfish are  
covered, too. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 21:13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A New Era of Stock Pricing / Commentary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *AP Business Analyst    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In this, the ninth year of economic expansion,  
the stock market's ``.com'' mania seems only to intensify, 
propelling some Internet and technology shares into the 
stratosphere. 
</P>
<P>
	The mania is based in the belief that Internet and some  
technology stocks can't be measured the old-fashioned way, that is, 
on the basis of earnings. Get with it, reader; this is a new era. 
</P>
<P>
	In the new era, profits don't count as they once did. In fact,  
in notable instances they seem not to count at all. Amazon.com's 
price rose tenfold last year in the total absence of profits. 
</P>
<P>
	What does count is the willingness, even eagerness, of buyers to  
put a higher price on corporate shares, especially if they have a 
.com in their names or Internet positions for their companies. 
</P>
<P>
	This is new-era pricing, and it has more to do with price  
momentum and expectations than with such measurements as earnings 
growth, dividends and maturity of management. 
</P>
<P>
	Analyst Michael Flament calculates that between 1945 and 1982,  
stocks produced a total return of 9.6 percent a year, thanks to a 
4.7 percent dividend income rise and 7.5 percent earnings growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Add those two factors together and you come to 12.2 percent, but  
from that you must subtract a 2.6 percent decline in price-earnings 
ratios to produce the net of 9.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Compare that with the annual rates of growth since then. From  
1982 to 1999, the total return from stocks has been 20.4 percent a 
year, or more than twice that of the 1945-1982 period. 
</P>
<P>
	New-era pricing produced that result. While both dividend income  
and earnings growth accounted for only 3.8 percent and 6.3 percent, 
respectively, price-earnings ratios soared 10.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Since P-E ratios indicate the number of times earnings that  
investors are willing to pay for a corporate share, it suggests 
that investors believe as never before in the future of stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	In such behavior, some critics see a corollary.  
</P>
<P>
	Commenting on market conditions, analyst Charles Allmon recalls  
a passage from ``Security Analysis -- Principles and Techniques,'' 
a stock valuation classic written by Benjamin Graham. 
</P>
<P>
	Allmon refers to it in an article for Better Investing, a  
monthly magazine of the National Association of Investment Clubs, 
but it may have pertinence for others. 
</P>
<P>
	Describing the mood of the 1920s, Graham wrote that ``making  
money in the stock market was now the easiest thing in the world. 
It was only necessary to buy 'good' stocks, regardless of price, 
and then let nature take her upward course.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The results of such a doctrine, said Graham, ``could not fail to  
be tragic. Countless people asked themselves, 'Why work for a 
living when a fortune can be made in Wall Street without 
working?''' 
</P>
<P>
	The answer came in the crash of 1929. ``Human nature never  
changes,'' said Allmon. Graham might have agreed. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 01:53:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stock Prices Close Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's main stock index closed higher today after  
the central bank announced a rise in corporate sentiment, but sharp 
early gains were wiped out by profit-taking. The dollar gained 
against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average climbed 44.59  
points, or 0.27 percent, to finish the day at 16,334.78 points. On 
Friday, the average closed down 37.37 points, or 0.23 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.36 yen in late afternoon trading, up 0.70  
yen from late Friday in Tokyo and also above its late New York 
level of 120.55 yen on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In its closely-watched quarterly ``tankan'' survey, the Bank of  
Japan reported business sentiment at large manufacturers improved 
moderately from the previous tankan, prompting hope that the 
economy has bottomed out. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei average was up more than 300 points at one point in  
morning trading after the release of the survey, but share prices 
fell back in the afternoon as traders pocketed profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the moderate upswing in corporate confidence cheered the  
market, and investors are eager to buy on any significant dips, 
analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The data confirms the economy has begun to bottom and that its  
outlook is expected to improve,'' said Masatoshi Sato, manager of 
the investment information group at Kankaku Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The tankan survey measures the percentage of firms seeing  
business conditions improve minus the percentage seeing conditions 
worsen. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentiment at small- and medium-sized manufacturers also  
improved. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen's deterioration against the dollar boosted the shares of  
export-oriented companies, products of which are made cheaper 
abroad by a weaker Japanese currency, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section closed up 3.00 points, or 0.23 percent, to 1,307.17 
points. The TOPIX rose 3.73 points, or 0.29 percent, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 558.7 million shares changed hands on the First  
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, down from 614.58 million 
shares Friday. Advancing issues outnumbered retreaters 801 to 433, 
while 95 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	On the foreign exchange market, the dollar gained on buying by  
overseas funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the release of the central bank survey had little  
effect on currency trading as the results were largely within 
expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	The greenback was also lifted by dollar-supportive comments from  
Japanese Vice Finance Minister for International Affairs Eisuke 
Sakakibara, who reiterated today that the country's foreign 
exchange policy hasn't changed. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar traded as low as 120.43 yen and as high as 121.75 yen  
in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 130.61 yen, up from  
130.32 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.740 percent from Friday's finish of 1.730 percent, 
driving its price down to 100.51 yen from 100.60 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 14:25:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends At Record 10,007.33 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology issues propelled the stock market  
sharply higher today, lifting the Dow Jones industrial average back 
above 10,000, as investors stopped worrying about interest rates 
and looked forward to strong first-quarter earnings reports. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue chip index closed up 174.82 at 10,007.33, just  
squeezing past the Dow's previous closing high of 10,006.78, set 
March 29. Monday's session was just the second time that the Dow 
has finished above 10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq composite index and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index  
also set new records. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq rose 66.69 to 2,560.06, passing its previous high  
close of 2,510.09, reached Feb. 1. The S&AMP;P 500 rose 27.40 to 
1,321.12, exceeding its closing high of 1,316.55 set March 18. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a herd instinct out there, as everyone wants to buy the  
winners,'' said David Orr, chief economist at First Union Capital 
Markets in Charlotte, N.C. ``This is not economics; it's 
psychological.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were buoyed by Friday's Labor Department report that  
just 46,000 new jobs were created in February, the smallest 
increase in three years. The report calmed investor fears that the 
economy was growing too fast and that the Federal Reserve might 
raise interest rates to slow it down. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts said the rally exceeded their expectations from the  
jobs report. Monday was the first chance the market, which was 
closed for Good Friday, had to react to the numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is nothing wrong with the economy, but is the economy  
that good? The answer is probably no,'' Orr said. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks once again set the tone for trading.  
</P>
<P>
	Among Dow stocks, IBM was up 6 5/8 to 183 5/8 and Hewlett-Packard rose  
3 9/16 to 71 7/16. America Online rose 16 3/4 to 166 3/4 on the New York 
Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Nasdaq, Yahoo! shot up 39 5/16 to 219 1/16 as traders  
anticipated a strong earnings report from the Internet company on 
Wednesday. Computer maker Dell was up 2 13/16 at 44, Sun 
Microsystems gained 3 3/4 at 129 15/16, and Microsoft was up 2 1/4 at 94 
15/164. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online declined to comment Monday on a published report  
that revived rumors AOL, the No. 1 Internet services company, was 
in talks to buy CBS. The takeover talk was the subject of a report 
Monday in the online edition of the San Jose Mercury News. AOL was 
up 16 15/16 at 166 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Online trading companies also traded higher after a Credit  
Suisse First Boston analyst issued positive comments about the 
sector. E-Trade Group rose 11 3/4 to 72 5/8 Charles Schwab rose 9 1/8 to 
103 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Blue chip stocks also rose amid optimism about first-quarter  
earnings reports that will be released starting this week. That 
included oil companies -- Exxon was up 2 1/16 to 72 3/16 and Chevron 
rose 3 13/16 to 90 5/8. 
</P>
<P>
	``Expectations are very solid for the larger companies,'' said  
Richard Cripps, chief market strategist for Legg Mason of 
Baltimore. ``Microsoft, GE and these types of companies will show 
robust double-digit growth in sales and earnings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Online bookseller Amazon.com rose 15 1/2 to 186 1/2 and retailer  
Wal-Mart gained 2 1/8 to 95 3/8. The two companies settled a suit brought 
by Wal-Mart charging that Amazon hired computer system managers 
away from Wal-Mart to steal the retailer's trade secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the  
NYSE with 1,689 up, 1,321 down and 558 unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 694.4 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs. 701.1  
million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 9.64 to 614.63, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 9.94 to 721.24 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 3.55 to 402.29.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 05:41:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
