<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> India's Government Nears Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- A restive party in India's ruling  
coalition pushed the government a step closer to possible collapse 
Monday, declaring that it would withdraw from the Cabinet. 
</P>
<P>
	Jayaram Jayalalitha, head of a party known by its Tamil acronym  
AIADMK, announced after a meeting of party leaders that the two 
government ministers from her party would resign Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The powerful south India politician said she would travel to New  
Delhi next week to explore the possibilities of forming a new 
government, Press Trust of India quoted her as saying in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Jayalalitha has hinted in the past that she would support a  
no-confidence vote against Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee's 
wobbly coalition when parliament convenes April 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Vajpayee's one-year-old coalition is made up of 19 parties  
holding 276 seats in the 545-member lower house of parliament. A 
defection by Jayalalitha's 18 deputies could topple the government, 
but Vajpayee is banking on her enemies to cross over to the 
government and offset the loss. 
</P>
<P>
	Vajpayee has rejected Jayalalitha's demands that Defense  
Minister George Fernandes be dismissed or investigated for firing 
India's naval commander, Admiral Vishnu Bhagwat, in December. He 
has also refused her demands to reinstate Bhagwat. 
</P>
<P>
	The showdown over Fernandes is the latest dispute between the  
prime minister and Jayalalitha, the most fractious member of his 
coalition. In the past, he has placated her on several issues, 
including transferring officials probing corruption charges against 
her. 
</P>
<P>
	Jayalalitha, head of the All India Anna Dravida Munnetra  
Kazhgam, embarrassed the prime minister by meeting Congress Party 
leader Sonia Gandhi in New Delhi last week in a flirtation with 
Vajpayee's chief opposition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
