<TEXT>
<P>
	Dow Ends At Record 10,007.33  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology issues propelled the stock market  
sharply higher today, lifting the Dow Jones industrial average back 
above 10,000, as investors relaxed about interest rates and looked 
forward to strong first-quarter earnings reports. It closed up 
174.82 at 10,007.33. That was just above the Dow's previous closing 
high of 10,006.78, set last Monday. The rally also sent the Nasdaq 
composite index and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index into record 
territory. The Nasdaq rose 58.55 to 2,551.92, passing its previous 
high close of 2,510.09, reached Feb. 1. 

</P>
<P>
	Tech Stocks Lead the Way  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks once again set the tone for  
trading today. Among Dow stocks, IBM was up 6 15/16 to 183 15/16 
and Hewlett-Packard rose 3 9/16 to 71 7/16. On the Nasdaq, Yahoo! 
shot up 39 5/16 to 219 1/16 as traders anticipated a strong 
earnings report from the Internet company on Wednesday. Computer 
maker Dell was up 2 13/16 at 44, Sun Microsystems gained 3 3/4 at 129 
15/16, and Microsoft was up 2 1/4 at 94 15/164. 

</P>
<P>
	Online, Blue Chip Stocks Help Rise  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP -- Online trading companies traded higher today  
after a Credit Suisse First Boston analyst issued positive comments 
about the sector. E-Trade Group rose 11 5/8 to 72 1/2 and Charles Schwab 
rose 9 1/8 to 103 3/8. Blue chip stocks also rose amid optimism related 
to first-quarter earnings reports that will be released starting 
this week. That included oil companies -- Exxon was up 2 3/16 to 72 
5/16 and Chevron rose 3 7/8 to 90 11/16. 

