<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stock Market Higher; Dow Up 170.62 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology issues propelled the stock market  
higher Monday, lifting the Dow Jones industrial average above 
10,000, as investors relaxed about interest rates and looked 
forward to robust first-quarter earnings reports. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow was up 170.62 at 10,002.62,  
trading just below its record high close of 10,006.78, set last 
Monday. The markets were closed on Good Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The rally also sent the Nasdaq composite index and the Standard  
&AMP; Poor's 500 index into record territory. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq was up 56.87 at 2,550.24, leaping above its high  
close of 2,510.09 reached Feb. 1. The S&AMP;P 500 rose 24.14 to 
1,317.86, slightly exceeding its closing high of 1,316.55 reached 
March 18. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a herd instinct out there, as everyone wants to buy the  
winners,'' said David Orr, chief economist at First Union Capital 
Markets in Charlotte, N.C. ``This is not economics; it's 
psychological.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were buoyed by Friday's Labor Department report that  
just 46,000 new jobs were created in February, the smallest 
increase in three years. The report calmed investor fears that the 
economy was growing too fast and that the Federal Reserve might 
raise interest rates to slow it down. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts said today's market surge exceeded their  
expectations from the jobs report. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is nothing wrong with the economy, but is the economy  
that good? The answer is probably no,'' Orr said. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks once again set the tone for trading.  
</P>
<P>
	Among Dow stocks, IBM was up 6 to 183 and Hewlett-Packard rose  
3 1/4 to 71 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! shot up 34 to 213 3/4 as traders anticipated a strong  
earnings report from the Internet company on Wednesday. Computer 
maker Dell was up 2 9/16 at 43 3/4, Sun Microsystems gained 3 29/32 at 
130 3/32, and Microsoft was up 2 19/64 at 94 63/64. 
</P>
<P>
	Online trading companies also traded higher after a Credit  
Suisse First Boston analyst issued positive comments about the 
sector. E-Trade Group rose 8 13/16 to 69 11/16 Charles Schwab rose 
6 1/2 to 100 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Blue chip stocks also rose amid optimism related to  
first-quarter earnings reports that will be released starting this 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Expectations are very solid for the larger companies,'' said  
Richard Cripps, chief market strategist for Legg Mason of 
Baltimore. ``Microsoft, GE and these types of companies will show 
robust double digit growth in sales and earnings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 558.6 million shares, 
down from Thursday's 565.2 million. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
