<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Delivers 148 Planes in 1st Q </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing delivered 148 commercial jets in the first  
three months of 1999 on its way towards a goal of a record 620 
deliveries this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the company delivered a record 550 jetliners.  
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the deliveries should keep Boeing's profits on  
target as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``These numbers show Boeing has really done a whale of a job,''  
said Paul Nisbet, an analyst at JSA Research in Newport, R.I. 
``They are very much on track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company will release its first-quarter earnings report April  
21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 05:58:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> E-Mail Flood Inconvenient for Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government wants to hear from you. Just  
don't send a lot of e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest demonstration of computer technology surpassing  
Washington's ability to cope with it, the U.S. Forest Service 
scrambled to adopt new rules about how taxpayers can send 
electronic messages to all its employees. 
</P>
<P>
	The government says it moved to prevent what could become a  
deluge of unwanted constituent e-mail, which can be sent with a 
single mouse-click to thousands of bureaucrats more easily and more 
quickly these days than a single letter can be hand-delivered by 
the Postal Service. 
</P>
<P>
	But the modern convenience of e-mail for citizens is proving  
inconvenient for the government, which is struggling to balance its 
obligations to listen to the nation's populace against its desire 
to get its work done. 
</P>
<P>
	The Forest Service changed its rules earlier this year after  
Andy Stahl of the activist Forest Service Employees for 
Environmental Ethics discovered a method to send e-mail messages to 
27,000 agency employees, a sort of high-tech handbilling. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, about 40 groups and individuals, sympathetic to forest  
industries, caught wind of the stunt by Stahl, a former agency 
employee. They asked for e-mail addresses for all 34,000 employees 
so they, too, could send messages -- an estimated 1.3 million 
e-mails in total. 
</P>
<P>
	``Would you please send me the e-mail list for Montana Forest  
Service employees?'' asked a writer in Montana. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand the U.S. Forest Service e-mail system is  
available,'' another wrote from Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Fearing the agency's computers might crash under the strain,  
Forest Service Chief Mike Dombeck decided to become a human filter 
for all the digital discourse. ``It could potentially grind it to a 
halt,'' said spokesman George Lennon. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agency's new policy, anyone who wants to get a message  
to all Forest Service employees will send it to Dombeck. If he 
decides the message is appropriate -- and he promises to be 
extremely lenient -- he will then post it on the agency's internal 
Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	The Forest Service's dilemma isn't unique. Congress, too, is  
looking at ways to restrict the flow of constituent e-mail. The 
home page for the House of Representatives offers a ``write your 
representative'' tool, but citizens can write only to a single 
congressman, not all at once. 
</P>
<P>
	During the impeachment debate, e-mails flooded Capitol Hill and  
strained computer systems. And in 1996, the Federal Communications 
Commission received 200,000 messages in less than a week when 
consumers mistakenly believed the agency might propose an Internet 
tax. 
</P>
<P>
	That barrage shut down the agency's e-mail system and public  
affairs computers. The FCC has since beefed up the system to 
prevent it from happening again. 
</P>
<P>
	Some experts said the Forest Service handled its dilemma wisely.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're paying our taxes and funding these agencies to get work  
done,'' said Ray Everett-Church of the Coalition Against 
Unsolicited Commercial E-mail. ``If they're listening to these 
diatribes, they're not going to be doing the people's business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paul McMasters, a First Amendment specialist at the Freedom  
Forum, a journalism research foundation, said the agency wasn't 
obligated to hand over its employee e-mail list. 
</P>
<P>
	``The potential for mischief is obviously great,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	McMasters said mass-mailing agency employees probably isn't  
worthwhile, anyway, because most key decisions are made by a few 
people at the top. 
</P>
<P>
	Stahl, the environmentalist, said he plans no more mass e-mails  
himself. But he supports anyone else who wants to send bulk 
messages. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's called democracy,'' he said. ``Communication should be  
free and open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And if all that freedom and openness wears thin?  
</P>
<P>
	``That's why you have a delete key.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 19:23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vikings, George Agree To Terms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- The Minnesota Vikings, who were led  
to the NFC championship game last season by Randall Cunningham, are 
taking a chance on another quarterback with something to prove. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings announced Monday they have reached a contract  
agreement with Jeff George to serve as Cunningham's backup, giving 
George a chance to mend his reputation as a talented but 
temperamental passer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our sense of it was simply that when a player's in free agency  
it's a good time for reflection,'' Leigh Steinberg, George's agent, 
said Monday night. ``I try to focus a player on what values and 
priorities are good for them. ... In every way Minnesota was at the 
top of the list, except short-term economics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	George's one-year contract reportedly is worth $400,000 plus  
incentives, a mammoth slide from the $5 million-a-year deal he had 
as Oakland's starter the last two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Signing Jeff George is a big plus for our Viking program,''  
coach Dennis Green said. ``Jeff is a very talented quarterback with 
a competitive mentality. He has proved that he has the physical 
tools and the right mental makeup to be successful in the NFL.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings felt compelled to find a strong backup for  
Cunningham after they traded Brad Johnson to Washington in 
February. Johnson was the Vikings starter until injuries sidelined 
him for much of last season, giving Cunningham the chance to step 
in and lead the team's high-powered offense, which scored an 
NFL-record 541 points in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Cunningham had the best year of his career and, despite his age  
-- 36 -- the Vikings opted to keep him instead of Johnson, who said 
he wanted to start or be traded. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings will be George's fourth team. Indianapolis selected  
him as the top pick in the 1990 draft. He also played for Atlanta 
and Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	George led the AFC in passing with the Raiders in 1997, throwing  
for 3,917 yards with 29 TDs and nine interceptions. But he was 
injured part of last season and did not play well, and the Raiders 
opted out of his hefty contract during the offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, George got into a sideline shouting match with Atlanta  
coach June Jones on national television. That prompted the Falcons 
to release him. 
</P>
<P>
	Steinberg said his client should benefit from playing for a team  
with a chance to win the Super Bowl, rather than teams with little 
or no chance of making the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	George has played on only two winning teams during his eight  
seasons, finishing 9-7 with the Colts in 1992 and 9-7 with the 
Falcons in 1995, losing a first-round playoff game at Green Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	``Indianapolis and Atlanta were rough situations,'' Steinberg  
said. ``Oakland was just a matter of where he played very well in 
1997 and got hurt in 1998. ... The only problem has been fitting 
into those two organizations (Indianapolis and Atlanta).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cunningham signed as a backup two years ago after a one-year  
retirement. At the time, he was considered by some to be damaged 
goods. 
</P>
<P>
	``So many people have looked at Jeff like he's a bad guy or  
something, but they did the same thing to me two years ago,'' 
Cunningham said. ``So I know those things can sometimes be false. 
I'm sure it's not true what's been said of him.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 10:48:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NATO Countries To Take In Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLACE, Macedonia (AP) -- Covered in grime, four aid workers  
grunted as they struggled up a steep muddy slope, carrying a 
blanket. In it lay the limp form of a gaunt, bearded man in a 
traditional Albanian hat. 
</P>
<P>
	The four set down their burden in a makeshift hospital tent next  
to a pile of mud-soaked garbage and quickly turned back toward the 
squalid, sprawling refugee camp below. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's horrible down there,'' one of the workers said as he  
hurried down the hillside on the Macedonia-Yugoslav border, where 
tens of thousands of refugees from the war in Kosovo were waiting 
Sunday to make their way onward. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to the burgeoning humanitarian crisis, NATO nations  
prepared to begin taking in large numbers of refugees while 
stressing it was only a temporary measure until they could return 
to homes in Kosovo. Germany is ready to accept 40,000; the United 
States, 20,000; and Turkey, 20,000, NATO said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	On the border camp's outskirts, a long line of people stood  
listlessly, waiting to be chosen for the next bus going to an 
accommodation or transit center. Occasionally someone would 
collapse into the mud. Behind them, wisps of smoke wafted over a 
sea of shelters made from plastic sheeting or blankets. 
</P>
<P>
	With no latrines in the camp, the muddy earth underfoot was  
mixed with feces. Some refugees washed themselves in a freezing 
river. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is like nothing I have ever experienced,'' said one woman  
who identified herself only as Lora. Tears in her eyes, she 
strained to look for the rest of her family in the crowd below. 
</P>
<P>
	Buses were moving refugees out of the camp at a rate of 300 an  
hour, or about 5,000 a day, the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees 
said. Macedonian officials hoped to get an airlift under way today 
to ferry the refugees out of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Police and army troops banned the media from entering the camp  
or coming into direct contact with the refugees in recent days, but 
visitors found thousands of people sitting in the dirt, many 
holding plastic bags or huddling with coats over their heads. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, after days of waiting, aid was beginning to  
arrive at the camp. Local Red Cross workers, assisted by UNHCR, 
were distributing boxes of cookies and cartons of juice. Blankets 
and plastic sheeting were also being supplied. 
</P>
<P>
	``The situation has always been bad, but at least we are feeding  
them,'' said UNHCR spokesman Joe Hegenour. 
</P>
<P>
	Macedonia, a former Yugoslav republic, agreed to let refugees  
pass over its border in return for a promise that nearly all would 
go elsewhere. More than 120,000 have arrived so far. 
</P>
<P>
	Montenegro, the smaller of the two republics that make up  
Yugoslavia, has taken in another 35,000 Kosovars fleeing Serb 
atrocities. Albania is coping with an influx of about 226,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Fearing political and ethnic instability as a result of the  
refugees' arrival, Macedonia has said it can take in no more than 
20,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Some questioned whether NATO might be exacerbating the problem  
by providing temporary shelter outside the region, saying such a 
course of action played into the hands of Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should not disperse people all over,'' European Union  
Humanitarian Aid Commissioner Emma Bonino said Sunday. ``We should 
not cooperate in any way with ethnic cleansing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO stressed it remained the alliance's aim for refugees to  
return eventually to Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 10:48:07 </DATE_TIME>
