<DOCNO> APW19990405.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 14:05:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Back Pain Forces Ripken Out of Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Cal Ripken was removed from the Baltimore  
Orioles' game against Tampa Bay on Monday with stiffness in his 
lower back. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken voluntarily ended his record consecutive games streak at  
2,632 last September, so his removal for a pinch-hitter in the 
third inning Monday didn't have the possible repercussion it might 
have had a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Orioles third baseman has been a model of durability  
since his rookie season in 1982, when he began his remarkable 
streak. He played in pain for at least a portion of the 17-year 
run, although he almost had to sit down in 1997 because of lower 
back pain. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken gave no indication of experiencing any back problems this  
spring. He hit .200 but missed a huge chunk of the exhibition 
schedule to be with his ailing father, who died March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken appeared to run hard after putting down a sacrifice bunt  
in the second inning Monday. But when it came to take his next trip 
to the plate, he was replaced by Willis Otanez. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 00:51:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mo. Prepares for Weapon Proposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Using pulpits and pickup trucks, activists in a  
statewide battle over the legalization of concealed guns campaigned 
hard in the final days before Missouri's voters decide its fate. 
</P>
<P>
	The pulpits Sunday included New Northside Baptist Church, a  
spiritual cornerstone in a mostly black St. Louis neighborhood that 
is occasionally rocked by gunfire and violent death. 
</P>
<P>
	``The myth that concealed weapons reduce crime is nonsense,''  
declared the Rev. William J. Ellis, who has led the church for more 
than a quarter of a century. 
</P>
<P>
	He urged his worshippers to reject Proposition B on Tuesday  
because ``that way, we won't have to get a metal detector for those 
entering the church house.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The message was the same in a coordinated appeal to  
congregations -- with pastors criticizing Proposition B as 
loophole-ridden, unsafe and too risky for children. 
</P>
<P>
	If approved, anyone 21 or older may apply for a permit to carry  
a concealed firearm for a fee starting at $80. Twelve hours of 
training would be required. 
</P>
<P>
	Known alcohol or drug abuser and people with felony or  
misdemeanor firearms convictions or dishonorable military 
discharges would be ineligible for the permits. 
</P>
<P>
	Many worshippers at Easter ceremonies were quietly reverent but  
unswayed in their support for concealed guns. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve McCauley, who lives in an older section of St. Louis known  
as Dutchtown, said his 90-year-old neighbor ``is afraid of her 
shadow and won't let anybody in but the postman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So when his pastor at St. Anthony of Padua Catholic Church  
``asked us to consider voting against it'' during Sunday's sermon, 
McCauley quietly kept his support for Proposition B to himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he drove his pickup truck to the headquarters of  
Missourians Against Crime -- the leading support group for 
Proposition B and recipient of more than $3 million in 
contributions from the National Rifle Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a supporter because of crime. It's the right to protect  
yourself. I want everyone to have that choice, and I don't even own 
a gun or have any plans to seek a license if conceal-carry is 
approved. But we need this right,'' McCauley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of Proposition B, while enjoying a roughly 4-1 lead  
in fund raising on the strength of the NRA donations, nonetheless 
were apprehensive that their side of the story wasn't being told. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Jeffery, 40, insisted that his state-by-state research  
showed Proposition B's background checks and other provisions to be 
among the strongest of states with concealed guns laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``The history of this in other states shows that people act  
safely, responsibly and peaceably when conceal-carry is 
implemented,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Proposition B campaign may intensify today, as actor and NRA  
leader Charlton Heston appears in Springfield to rally support for 
the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the mayors of St. Louis, Kansas City and Columbia  
were linking up with Proposition B foes for campaign-ending news 
conferences in those cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides planned to congregate outside Busch Stadium to  
distribute literature to St. Louis Cardinals fans; the baseball 
club is officially on the record against Proposition B, amid 
concerns about hidden guns making sports turn deadly. 
</P>
<P>
	Back at New Northside Baptist Church, Jacqueline Gary, a  
worshipper with daughters ages 2 and 13, still had serious doubts 
about Proposition B. She plans to vote ``no.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``My older daughter is transferring from St. Louis County  
schools to the city schools, and I am honestly terrified about what 
will happen if this passes,'' said Mrs. Gary, 35. 
</P>
<P>
	She reached down to smooth 2-year-old daughter Teniah's pink  
Easter dress as the wide-eyed child grinned at arriving 
churchgoers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is frightening when I think about my babies' safety,'' Mrs.  
Gary said. ``I do not believe in guns. But I might have to get one 
just to defend myself from the nuts if this passes.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 15:15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> La. Town Wracked by Deadly Twister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BENTON, La. (AP) -- The muddy stack of possessions was sadly  
small -- a few wet snapshots, a crumpled blouse, a box of Christmas 
ornaments -- all the mementos James Dyal was able to find amid the 
crushed metal and wood where his mother died. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not much of anything left,'' Dyal said Monday as he  
rummaged through the debris left by a tornado that smashed Betty 
Dyal's trailer, killing her. ``I'd like to find some more pictures, 
some of her things that we could keep, but it's soaked and 
scattered all over the place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dyal, 60, was retired and lived alone in a trailer park.  
Her body was found lying near her Ford Fairmont, which was thrown 
into the middle of the mobile home lot, its roof crushed. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the six deaths in Saturday night's tornado occurred in  
the 66 trailers smashed by the storm at Hay Meadow Trailer Park. 
Block after block, the crushed wreckage was stacked in haphazard 
piles, blown into dangling power lines, draped over cars and 
trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	Eighteen people remained hospitalized Monday; eight were in  
critical condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to the misery, 4 to 6 inches of rain fell Sunday night,  
further soaking the remnants worth salvaging. 
</P>
<P>
	Families were allowed back into the park on Monday to pick  
through the rubble despite new tornado warnings and dark skies 
threatening more severe thunderstorms. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got a few clothes and a little paperwork we needed,'' said  
Joan Delise, 34, who worked with her right arm in a sling. She 
dislocated a shoulder and was badly bruised when the tornado 
shattered her trailer. ``But most of it's too buried to get to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The National Guard brought in front loaders, bulldozers,  
backhoes, dump trucks and troops to help with the cleanup. 
</P>
<P>
	Sticky red mud sucked at workers' shoes. Grassy areas became  
mini-marshes. Glass, nails, splinters of wood, jagged fencing and 
razor-like pieces of metal made moving through the maze of wreckage 
dangerous. 
</P>
<P>
	``I keep longing for my house,'' said Mildred Pryor, 46, as she  
stood atop the wreckage of her trailer. ``I'm just homesick. I want 
somewhere where I can sit and relax, but I know that won't happen 
for a while.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the Twin Point area where the other three deaths occurred,  
residents continued to pick through their broken trailers and 
houses. Workers also began removing broken trees downed by the 
storm. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no water, no lights, no gas,'' said Linda Jones, who  
was helping a friend recover the few things left at her smashed 
trailer. ``Not that there's anything to live in if there was. This 
is exactly what misery looks like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lynette Holyfield found little to take from her wrecked trailer  
at Hay Meadow. But her fiance, Scott Steudebaker, cheered her up 
when he found a 4-inch square pillow that Ms. Holyfield had 
cross-stitched for his Valentine's gift. Embroidered on it were the 
words ``I Love You'' and their names. 
</P>
<P>
	``He found it about five houses down,'' Ms. Holyfield said.  
``Now we're going to use it for a ring pillow at our wedding next 
month. Everyone says I shouldn't even wash the mud off it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 05:48:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Lawmakers Mull Kosovo Ground Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The debate is growing over whether the Clinton  
administration can continue to foreclose the use of ground troops 
in Kosovo with the issue likely to dominate Congress when lawmakers 
return from their spring recess. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers from both parties said Sunday that President Clinton  
no longer should foreclose out of hand use of ground troops as a 
military option in Kosovo, but most emphasized that Congress should 
give its approval before troops actually are deployed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The diplomacy won't start until our president stops saying no  
ground troops,'' Sen. Dick Lugar, R-Ind., a senior member of the 
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, said on ABC's ``This Week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``To say no ground troops is a mistake'' Sen. Joseph Biden of  
Delaware, the committee's top Democrat, agreed on CNN's ``Late 
Edition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, administration officials said there are no plans to send  
ground forces into Kosovo, although the Pentagon announced Sunday 
it is sending 24 Apache helicopter gunships to neighboring Albania 
for use against Serbian troops in Kosovo. About 2,000 U.S. soldiers 
also will be sent to Albania to support the helicopters. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not believe an invasion force ... is in the national  
interest,'' Sandy Berger, the White House national security 
adviser, said on CBS' ``Face the Nation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But a growing number of lawmakers of both parties are arguing  
categorically ruling out ground troops only plays into the hands of 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and keeps him from the 
negotiating table. 
</P>
<P>
	By ruling out such an option ``you immediately convince  
Milosevic that we're not really serious, that we're not ready to 
stay the course,'' Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va., said on ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to hold open the option of using ground forces,'' Sen.  
Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., concurred on CBS. He said the attitude 
in Congress on ground troops has changed with the air war showing 
no early sign of capitulation by Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last week, there was no support for American or NATO ground  
forces. Next week, I think there may be because we understand more 
what's on the line here,'' Lieberman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The House returns from its Easter recess Tuesday, while the  
Senate is away until next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Democrats and Republicans said the use of ground troops  
should be debated in Congress and no troops should be committed in 
Kosovo without congressional approval. ``The Constitution requires 
Congress to make that decision,'' Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., said 
on ``Fox News Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a Vietnam War fighter pilot and  
POW, said it is time for Congress to ``become more engaged'' and 
debate a vote on the use of U.S. ground troops. ``We certainly have 
to make preparations for it,'' he told CBS. ``You never take any 
option off the table. ... It may well take ground forces to win,'' 
Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., agreed on NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., said if ground forces are needed  
Clinton must make the case clearly on Capitol Hill. ``If he does 
... the Congress and the American people will follow,'' Shelby said 
on CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	But other lawmakers rejected consideration of ground troops in  
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The air war should be intensified, Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo.,  
told CNN, but he added he couldn't ``conceive of a situation where 
we ... ought to be using ground troops.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., said on NBC that if invading troops  
are needed, ``those countries that are our allies that have 
strategic interests, let them take over the ground war.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 05:48:26 </DATE_TIME>
