<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McGwire Causes ESPN Confusion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In an effort to show Mark McGwire's first game  
today, ESPN teased fans in New York by mistakenly showing a few 
innings of the marquee Dodgers-Diamondbacks game. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York area was supposed to see the Atlanta-Philadelphia  
game, but because of a communications mixup, fans got to see the 
first few innings of the Randy Johnson-Kevin Brown matchup. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe there was a mixup partially caused by the fact that  
we have a third network today,'' said ESPN spokeswoman Diane Lamb. 
``If we didn't add the network, New York viewers wouldn't be able 
to see the St. Louis game because the Yankees were a part of our 
tripleheader.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The third feed was put in place to allow fans in New York, the  
Bay Area, Los Angeles and Arizona to see McGwire. ESPN usually has 
one alternate feed for those areas unable to watch their home teams 
because of local broadcast rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees were involved in the third game of ESPN's  
tripleheader, playing at Oakland, so fans in the Bay Area and New 
York had to be on one of the alternate feeds. 
</P>
<P>
	The third feed was slated to start with the Braves-Phillies,  
then the Cardinals-Brewers and conclude with the White Sox-Mariners 
game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 17:12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Whitewater Figure Hale Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Whitewater figure David Hale was  
sentenced to 21 days in prison Monday for lying to state regulators 
about the solvency of his insurance company. With time off for good 
behavior, he could serve less than four days. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge David Bogard followed the jury's sentencing recommendation  
and turned down requests to let Hale serve his time in home 
detention. Hale's wife, Sue, had pleaded for mercy, recounting 
Hale's heart problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale was released on $10,000 bond while he appeals.  
</P>
<P>
	Hale pleaded guilty in the Whitewater case to two felonies and  
served 21 months of a 28-month sentence. He was a key witness 
against then-Gov. Jim Guy Tucker and James and Susan McDougal at 
their 1996 fraud trial. All three were convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale was convicted last month of making a false statement to  
regulators about the health of a burial insurance company he owned. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, Hale was directed to cover a $38,757 shortfall on the  
company books, but prosecutors say he ran a scam that temporarily 
addressed the problem. Hale claimed that regulators failed to 
recognize a legitimate business deal that netted the insurance 
company $150,000 in stock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
