<DOCNO> APW19990405.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 18:11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tugboat Co. Fined for Sea Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) -- A tugboat company agreed Monday to pay  
$600,000 to settle charges stemming from an accident that damaged 
sea grass and coral off the Florida Keys and left a scar 13 miles 
long. 
</P>
<P>
	Coastal Marine Towing, which has since gone out of business,  
reached the settlement just before a federal civil trial began. The 
settlement leaves Great Lakes Dredge and Dock Co. as the remaining 
defendant. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought we were doing the right thing for everyone  
concerned,'' Coastal attorney Allan Kelley said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. and state officials say an important part of the ecosystem  
of the Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary died in 1993 when 
four tugboats hauling dredging equipment passed through. One boat 
ran aground, tearing up the bottom. A pipe being towed by another 
boat came loose and dragged along the bottom for 13 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	Jon Mueller, an environmental attorney for the Justice  
Department, said the flotilla of four boats was a joint effort of 
Coastal and Great Lakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Great Lakes attorney John Keller said in his opening statement  
that Coastal Marine owned the boats that caused the damage while 
Great Lakes owned the other two boats. ``We didn't do it,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government is seeking about $1 million from Great  
Lakes. 
</P>
<P>
	The sea grass beds are nurseries for many species of fish,  
including snapper, grouper and grunts. The area where the boat ran 
aground, about 45 miles east of Key West, still has not recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	The marine sanctuary was created in 1990 to protect 2,800 square  
nautical miles of water heavily used by fishermen and boaters. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, treasure hunter Mel Fisher's company and his son were  
fined nearly $590,000 and ordered to hand over treasure from a 
sunken Spanish galleon for damaging sea grass in the Keys. That 
case was the first violation of the Florida Keys sanctuary to go to 
trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
