<DOCNO> APW19990405.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 09:25:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rejects Jailhouse Talk Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today refused to review a  
South Carolina judge's order that barred pretrial reporting on a 
secretly recorded conversation between a murder defendant and his 
lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices, without comment, turned away a Columbia, S.C.,  
newspaper's arguments that the judge's 1997 ``prior restraint'' on 
publication was unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	The South Carolina Supreme Court upheld the judge's order last  
year, ruling by a 4-1 vote that it had been necessary and ``as 
narrowly tailored, both in scope and duration, as was possible 
under the circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	B.J. Quattlebaum was facing trial, and a possible death penalty  
if convicted, for a murder committed during an armed robbery when 
in 1995 he and his lawyer talked about his case in a room at the 
Lexington County Sheriff's Department. They did not know their 
conversation was being videotaped. 
</P>
<P>
	When Quattlebaum's lawyers later learned that a copy of that  
tape had been leaked to Columbia television station WIS-TV, they 
sought a court order barring its dissemination. 
</P>
<P>
	State Judge Thomas Cooper ordered the station and all other news  
organizations, including The State newspaper, to refrain from 
reporting what the tape disclosed until jurors for Quattlebaum's 
trial had been selected and sequestered. 
</P>
<P>
	Quattlebaum subsequently was convicted and sentenced to death.  
He remains on South Carolina's death row. Although the judge's 
order long ago lost its legal force, the substance of Quattlebaum's 
secretly recorded discussion with his lawyer never has been made 
public. 
</P>
<P>
	A deputy sheriff has been indicted and charged with illegally  
taping what should have been a confidential conversation. The 
deputy, awaiting trial, has been suspended without pay. 
</P>
<P>
	In upholding the prior restraint on publication in Quattlebaum's  
case, the state Supreme Court said, ``It is difficult to conceive 
of a situation in which the rights of a defendant to a fair trial 
were more at jeopardy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state court's lone dissenter, Justice Jean Toal, said a less  
intrusive alternative might have preserved fair-trial rights. She 
noted a 1976 ruling in which the nation's highest court required 
that all possible alternatives be considered before courts bar the 
news media from publishing information they have. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for The State-Record Co.,  
which publishes The State, said there was no ``factual support'' 
for the 1995 prior restraint. The appeal also argued that the 
order's short duration made it no less a violation of the 
Constitution's free-press guarantees. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is The State-Record vs. Quattlebaum, 98-1035.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 19:05:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Case Dismissed Against Reno Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A judge dismissed a deportation case against  
a Palestinian accused of plotting to kill Attorney General Janet 
Reno, saying secret evidence against him was not convincing. 
</P>
<P>
	Hany Mahmoud Kiareldeen remained in federal custody Monday,  
however, after the Immigration and Naturalization Service obtained 
an emergency stay. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, U.S. Immigration Judge Daniel Meisner ordered  
Kiareldeen released on $1,500 bail. He also granted Kiareldeen 
conditional permanent residency, meaning he can remain in the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Meisner wrote that the evidence does not support the  
government's claim that Kiareldeen ``has engaged in terrorist 
activity'' or ``that there exists a reason to believe he is likely 
to do so in the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The stay was granted Friday by the U.S. Board of Immigration  
Appeals, which will consider his case. No date was immediately set 
for a hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiareldeen was arrested by the INS in March 1998 and accused of  
overstaying his student visa, which was the only formal charge 
against him. He has maintained his innocence. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiareldeen has lived in New Jersey since he left the Gaza Strip  
in 1990. He managed an electronics store in Passaic and lived in 
Bloomfield with his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	Summaries of secret FBI evidence given to the judge said  
Kiareldeen plotted to kill Reno because of her role in prosecuting 
the terrorists responsible for the 1993 World Trade Center bombing, 
that he was a suspected member of an unnamed terrorist 
organization, and that he made a threat against Reno. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI never brought any charges against him.  
</P>
<P>
	Kiareldeen lawyers blamed the allegations on a ``disgruntled''  
ex-wife, Amal Mohamed. She testified against Kiareldeen last year, 
but refused to say whether she was the FBI source. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
