<DOCNO> APW19990405.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 15:15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Galarraga Tosses First Pitch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Andres Galarraga, sitting out the season while  
being treated for back cancer, threw out the ceremonial first pitch 
before the Atlanta Braves' opener Monday against the Philadelphia 
Phillies. 
</P>
<P>
	Galarraga performed the ceremony from his home in West Palm  
Beach, Fla. Surrounded by two of his three daughters, Katherine and 
Andria, Galarraga tossed the ball toward a camera that was 
broadcasting live to the center-field video board at Turner Field 
in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Eddie Perez, one of Galarraga's closest friends, crouched behind  
the plate, a ball already in his glove. After Galarraga threw, 
Perez emerged got up and displayed the ball to the cheering crowd 
as if it had traveled across two states. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am so excited and so sorry I cannot be there today,''  
Galarraga told the crowd in Atlanta. ``I wish the best luck for all 
the players, the Atlanta Braves, and thank all the fans for all the 
support you gave me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Galarraga was diagnosed with cancer shortly before the start of  
spring training. He will undergo six months of chemotherapy and 
radiation, and doctors are hopeful he will be able to return for 
the 2000 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, Galarraga was the Braves' top hitter with a .305  
average, 44 homers and 121 RBIs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
