<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 23:31:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mixed Results for Baseball's Stars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	How baseball's big stars did Monday on opening day:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Mark McGwire. Hit home run No. 1, renewing his bid to make  
even more history. Coming off his record-breaking season of 70, he 
connected in the fifth inning for his 458th career homer in St. 
Louis' 10-8 loss to Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Ken Griffey Jr. Hit his seventh opening-day home run, one  
behind Frank Robinson's record, in an 8-2 loss to Chicago. The 
Seattle star did it at the Kingdome, soon after career homer king 
Hank Aaron threw out the first ball. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Roger Clemens. Made his debut for the World Series champion  
New York Yankees, staying in the game after an early rain delay at 
Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Albert Belle. Hit a three-run homer and an RBI single in his  
Baltimore debut, a 10-7 win over Tampa Bay. The crowd of 46,733 at 
Camden Yards gave him a standing ovation, and the surly slugger 
responded with a curtain call. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Cal Ripken. Forced to leave the Orioles' game in the third  
inning because of a stiff lower back and was listed as day-to-day. 
Last year, he voluntarily ended his record streak of 2,632 
consecutive games. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Kevin Brown. Baseball's first $100 million man allowed three  
home runs in his Dodgers debut, but Los Angeles beat Arizona 8-6 in 
11 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Randy Johnson. The Big Unit struck out nine in his first game  
since signing a $52.4 million contract with Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Raul Mondesi. The top performance of the day -- hit a tying,  
three-run homer with two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning, 
then hit a two-run homer in the 11th that lifted Los Angeles over 
Arizona 8-6. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Wade Boggs. Got two hits for Tampa Bay, moving him within 76  
of the 3,000 milestone. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Barry Bonds. Set an NL record with his 290th career  
intentional walk, breaking Hank Aaron's record in San Francisco's 
11-8 victory over Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Juan Gonzalez. Broke up Brian Moehler's no-hit bid by singling  
with one out in the seventh inning as Detroit defeated Texas 11-5. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Pedro Martinez. Struck out nine and was the winning pitcher as  
Boston beat Kansas City 5-3. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Tom Glavine. The NL Cy Young winner took the loss as Curt  
Schilling and the Philadelphia Phillies beat Atlanta 7-4. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Alex Fernandez. Pitching for the first time since wrecking his  
shoulder in the 1997 NL championship series, he led Florida over 
the New York Mets 6-2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 17:12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  United States 1, England 0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANO, Nigeria (AP) -- Dan Califf, a defender from the University  
of Maryland, scored in the 11th minute today to give the United 
States a 1-0 win over England in the Americans' opener at the FIFA 
World Youth Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Catliff scored off a pass from Francisco Gomez, and goalkeeper  
Tim Howard made the goal stand up with several big saves. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're smart enough to know that this win will not guarantee us  
an easy way in the tournament,'' Califf said. ``We'll have fun with 
this tonight and start thinking about Japan tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is tied for the Group E lead with Cameroon,  
which beat Japan 2-1 Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The early goal obviously did a lot for us today,'' U.S. coach  
Sigi Schmid said. ``We played with confidence and I feel we showed 
the fans that we weren't afraid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Califf received a yellow card in the 68th minute as did  
England's Ashley Cole and Greg Lincoln. 
</P>
<P>
	The top two teams in the six groups advance to the second round  
along with the four best third-place teams. The tournament is for 
players under 20 years of age. 
</P>
</TEXT>
