<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 05:15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> E-Mail Flood Inconvenient for Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government wants to hear from you. Just  
don't send a lot of e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest demonstration of computer technology surpassing  
Washington's ability to cope with it, the U.S. Forest Service 
scrambled to adopt new rules about how taxpayers can send 
electronic messages to all its employees. 
</P>
<P>
	The government says it moved to prevent what could become a  
deluge of unwanted constituent e-mail, which can be sent with a 
single mouse-click to thousands of bureaucrats more easily and more 
quickly these days than a single letter can be hand-delivered by 
the Postal Service. 
</P>
<P>
	But the modern convenience of e-mail for citizens is proving  
inconvenient for the government, which is struggling to balance its 
obligations to listen to the nation's populace against its desire 
to get its work done. 
</P>
<P>
	The Forest Service changed its rules earlier this year after  
Andy Stahl of the activist Forest Service Employees for 
Environmental Ethics discovered a method to send e-mail messages to 
27,000 agency employees, a sort of high-tech handbilling. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, about 40 groups and individuals, sympathetic to forest  
industries, caught wind of the stunt by Stahl, a former agency 
employee. They asked for e-mail addresses for all 34,000 employees 
so they, too, could send messages -- an estimated 1.3 million 
e-mails in total. 
</P>
<P>
	``Would you please send me the e-mail list for Montana Forest  
Service employees?'' asked a writer in Montana. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand the U.S. Forest Service e-mail system is  
available,'' another wrote from Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Fearing the agency's computers might crash under the strain,  
Forest Service Chief Mike Dombeck decided to become a human filter 
for all the digital discourse. ``It could potentially grind it to a 
halt,'' said spokesman George Lennon. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agency's new policy, anyone who wants to get a message  
to all Forest Service employees will send it to Dombeck. If he 
decides the message is appropriate -- and he promises to be 
extremely lenient -- he will then post it on the agency's internal 
Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	The Forest Service's dilemma isn't unique. Congress, too, is  
looking at ways to restrict the flow of constituent e-mail. The 
home page for the House of Representatives offers a ``write your 
representative'' tool, but citizens can write only to a single 
congressman, not all at once. 
</P>
<P>
	During the impeachment debate, e-mails flooded Capitol Hill and  
strained computer systems. And in 1996, the Federal Communications 
Commission received 200,000 messages in less than a week when 
consumers mistakenly believed the agency might propose an Internet 
tax. 
</P>
<P>
	That barrage shut down the agency's e-mail system and public  
affairs computers. The FCC has since beefed up the system to 
prevent it from happening again. 
</P>
<P>
	Some experts said the Forest Service handled its dilemma wisely.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're paying our taxes and funding these agencies to get work  
done,'' said Ray Everett-Church of the Coalition Against 
Unsolicited Commercial E-mail. ``If they're listening to these 
diatribes, they're not going to be doing the people's business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paul McMasters, a First Amendment specialist at the Freedom  
Forum, a journalism research foundation, said the agency wasn't 
obligated to hand over its employee e-mail list. 
</P>
<P>
	``The potential for mischief is obviously great,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	McMasters said mass-mailing agency employees probably isn't  
worthwhile, anyway, because most key decisions are made by a few 
people at the top. 
</P>
<P>
	Stahl, the environmentalist, said he plans no more mass e-mails  
himself. But he supports anyone else who wants to send bulk 
messages. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's called democracy,'' he said. ``Communication should be  
free and open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And if all that freedom and openness wears thin?  
</P>
<P>
	``That's why you have a delete key.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 12:15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Students Do Income Taxes for Fun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- As the government's April 15th tax deadline  
looms, Yinel Lora is in great demand. Though just 21 and still in 
college, she has a talent sought by millions of Americans: She can 
do taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody wants to catch me before somebody else does,'' Ms.  
Lora says between clients. 
</P>
<P>
	The Baruch College accounting major is one of 72,000 people  
nationwide -- mostly students and retirees -- who give their time 
each year to the Volunteer Income Tax Assistance program. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Internal Revenue Service offers free help at local  
offices around the country, IRS employees say the volunteers 
provide an invaluable service by taking their calculators and tax 
guides to the places where people go -- to nearly 5,000 schools, 
malls and community centers. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS sponsors the program in conjunction with colleges and  
other organizations that set up the help sites. Participating 
schools range from tiny Jacksonville State University in 
Jacksonville, Ala., to the University of California at Los Angeles 
and New York University. 
</P>
<P>
	The students who participate get practical accounting  
experience, and the taxpayers, regardless of income, get their 
returns done for free. 
</P>
<P>
	What the students don't do, however, is strategize.  
</P>
<P>
	There's no talk of tax shelters or capital gains minimization.  
If anything gets tricky, the professors step in, and if it's too 
tricky for them, they refer people to professionals. 
</P>
<P>
	And if you get audited, forget it. The program's volunteers  
can't help. 
</P>
<P>
	Professor Richard Hendler, who served as a volunteer tax  
preparer in the 1980s and now oversees the volunteers at NYU, said 
he's never seen anyone get audited because the returns his students 
work on are pretty straightforward. 
</P>
<P>
	Taxpayer Rita Ritchie was pleased with the free help, and even  
more pleased when she learned she owed no taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're wonderful here. They're wonderful people,'' Ms.  
Ritchie said of the students at the Baruch program, adding that at 
her age -- she's in her 70s -- she's already paid enough taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	And while it may make some nervous to show their finances to a  
blue-jeaned, clunky-shoed college student, Ms. Ritchie said she was 
confident in her tax helper, Andrea White, noting that the 
23-year-old checked everything twice. 
</P>
<P>
	To qualify as volunteers, the students must take an IRS seminar.  
Then they must pass an exam asking them to prepare tax returns 
based for hypothetical clients and answer questions such as the 
following: 
</P>
<P>
	``Mark's uncle, Howard, has no income and lived with Mark all  
year in Tampa. Mark provided all of Howard's support. Howard is a 
U.S. citizen and single. Can Mark claim his Uncle Howard as a 
dependent?'' (Answer: Yes he can.) 
</P>
<P>
	Hendler, the NYU professor, said the program gives him ``a warm  
feeling'' -- words not typically associated with taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	People come to his students hesitant and anxious, toting their  
shoe boxes and shopping bags of receipts. The volunteers send them 
away reassured and sometimes awaiting a refund, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	No one seemed very concerned about the volunteers getting sued.  
</P>
<P>
	``Do I worry about it? No. Should I? I guess so,'' said Hendler.  
</P>
<P>
	Ms. White, the Baruch volunteer, downplayed the risk because,  
``It's the IRS that really sponsors this program, that's how I look 
at it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her clients seem happy. Asked if she would return with her  
returns next year, Ms. Ritchie said, ``If I'm living, I'll come 
back.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
