<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Offer May Stop Rental Co. Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) -- United Rentals Inc., the largest  
equipment rental company in North America, is making an unsolicited 
$553 million offer for Rental Service Corp. -- a move that would 
stop a pending merger between Rental Service and NationsRent Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	If United Rentals' offer succeeds, the combined company would  
have annual revenue of about $3 billion, 700 branches and a rental 
fleet of more than 400,000 pieces of construction, industrial and 
landscaping equipment and tools. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the offer announced Monday, the Greenwich-based United  
Rentals would pay $22.75 a share for all of Rental Service's 
outstanding stock, a 28 percent premium over its 30-day average 
closing price. 
</P>
<P>
	United filed papers Monday in the Delaware Chancery Court  
seeking an injunction to stop the merger. The papers said the 
lawsuit was a ``challenge to a proposed merger based on an alleged 
breach of fiduciary duty.'' The lawsuit itself was not available 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Rental Service soared $5, or 29 percent, to close at  
$22.25 in trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The offer, good through April 30, is conditioned on getting a  
majority of the shares and the termination of the pending merger 
between Rental Service and NationsRent. 
</P>
<P>
	Rental Service is based in Scottsdale, Ariz., while NationsRent  
is based in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, Rental Service announced a planned merger with  
NationsRent in which each NationsRent share would be exchanged for 
0.355 shares of Rental Service. Investors spurned the deal, 
however, sending shares in both companies plummeting. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger was to be completed around mid-May. If the Rental  
Service board agrees to the offer from United Rentals, it could 
result in a breakup fee of $40 million. 
</P>
<P>
	NationsRent said Monday that it remains committed to the merger.  
</P>
<P>
	On the NYSE, United Rentals' stock fell 93 3/4 cents to close at  
$27.81 3/4, while NationsRent stock slipped 43 3/4 cents to close at 
$5.93 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	United Rentals operates in 470 locations in the U.S. and Canada,  
most of them in major metropolitan areas. Rental Service operates 
in about 245 locations, mostly in medium- and smaller-sized 
markets, making it the third-largest rental company in North 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	Founded in September 1997, United Rentals has become North  
America's biggest equipment-rental concern by aggressively buying 
out the small operators who dominate the business. It has acquired 
107 companies, including 24 of the largest 100 companies in the 
industry. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
