<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Corn, Soybeans Retreat / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        CHICAGO (AP) -- Corn and soybean futures retreated Monday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade amid nagging concerns about strong harvests 
in South America. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat futures advanced after shrugged off initial weakness  
tied to excellent crop conditions in winter wheat growing areas. 
</P>
<P>
        Corn and soybean prices fell back amid expectations that demand  
for U.S. exports, already at the lowest levels in years, will be hurt 
by the harvest of bumper crops in Argentina and Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
        Futures prices also are under pressure from projections American  
farmers this spring will plant record acreage to soybeans and large 
tracts to corn, boosting inventories already at the highest level in 
more than a decade. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat for July delivery rose 2 1/2 cents to $2.88 3/4 a bushel;  
May corn fell 3 1/4 cents to $2.18 3/4 a bushel; May oats fell 3 1/2 
cents to $1.11 a bushel; May soybeans fell 1 1/4 cents to $4.82 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
        Meat and livestock futures rose strongly on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, with pork rising on higher cash market prices and beef boosted 
by fewer slaughter-ready cattle. 
</P>
<P>
        June live cattle rose 0.55 cent to 67.65 cents a pound; May  
feeder cattle rose 1.10 cents to 74 cents a pound; June lean hogs rose 
1.15 cents to 54.10 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose 0.60 cent 
to 52.30 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
