<HEADLINE> Main Tokyo Index Down at Midday / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was higher against the yen Tuesday  
morning after a rally to record levels on Wall Street. The Tokyo 
Stock Exchange's main index fell moderately. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.59 yen in morning trading, up 0.23 yen  
from late Monday in Tokyo but below its level of 121.83 yen in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average lost 117.38 points, or 0.72 percent, to  
end the morning session at 16,217.40. On Monday, the average 
finished up 44.59 points, or 0.27 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar held its strength after the Dow  
Jones industrial average moved back above 10,000 points. The Dow 
rose 174.82 points to close Monday at 10,007.33, exceeding the 
closing high of 10,006.33 recorded March 29. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's strength also derived from the continuing turmoil  
in Yugoslavia, where NATO forces intensified their bombing campaign 
against Serbian targets around the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. currency is often seen as a safe haven for investors  
during times of international crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 130.32 yen, down  
from 130.61 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices started slightly higher  
following the strong showing on Wall Street, but moved into 
negative territory in quiet trading as the weak yen led traders to 
take profits. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 14.16 points, or 1.08 percent, to 1,293.01. 
The TOPIX closed up 3.00 points, or 0.23 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.745  
percent from Monday's finish of 1.740 percent, driving its price 
down to 100.47 yen from 100.51 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
