<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Studios Counter 'Star Wars' Prequel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Fighting the Force with romance, two films  
with female appeal -- ``Notting Hill'' starring Julia Roberts and 
Hugh Grant and ``The Love Letter'' with Kate Capshaw and Tom 
Selleck -- will open close to the May 19 release date of ``Star 
Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace,'' studio officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The high-stakes scheduling decisions spoke to the power -- and  
possibilities -- that rival studios see in ``The Phantom Menace,'' 
one of the most highly anticipated films in recent years and one 
that many say has the potential to follow only ``Titanic'' in box 
office gross. 
</P>
<P>
	Most studios are steering their movies far clear of the ``Star  
Wars'' prequel. But others had second thoughts, particularly after 
last year's experience with ``Godzilla.'' Some studios regretted 
not putting films against the big lizard movie when it didn't live 
up to high expectations over Memorial Day weekend, then plummeted 
the following week. 
</P>
<P>
	With this history and other factors in mind, Universal Studios  
said Monday it had moved ``Notting Hill'' from June 18 to May 28 -- 
Memorial Day weekend-- putting the movie in competition with the 
second week of ``The Phantom Menace,'' which is being distributed 
by 20th Century Fox. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought: Why not pick the film that is the perfect  
counter-programming,'' said Universal distribution head Nikki 
Rocco. ``Hopefully there's two audiences: kids who want to see 
'Star Wars' and mom and dad who'll be in the mood for a little 
romance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Notting Hill'' is the story of a travel bookstore owner  
(Grant) whose life turns upside down when a movie star (Roberts) 
walks into the store. Grant is reunited with the screenwriter and 
producer of his hit, ``Four Weddings and a Funeral.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, DreamWorks is sticking to its previously announced  
decision to open ``The Love Letter'' on May 21, just two days after 
``The Phantom Menace'' debuts on a Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The film tells of an unsigned love letter that intrigues people  
in a small New England town, as they wonder who it could have been 
from. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the time we put it on May 21, there were really not any  
movies being released at that time that we thought would take up 
all of our targeted audiences, which are females,'' said DreamWorks 
distribution chief James Tharp. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, DreamWorks is facing unexpected competition from ``Notting  
Hill,'' but Tharp said, ``We're locked in to that day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other studios, however, have decided to give the Jedi plenty of  
room to operate. Warner Bros. is among those that won't have a 
single movie out in May, launching its summer slate with the 
Independence Day weekend release ``Wild, Wild West'' starring Will 
Smith. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
