<HEADLINE> Griffey Hits Home Run in Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Ken Griffey Jr. homered in his second at-bat of  
the season Monday night, connecting after career home run king Hank 
Aaron threw out the ceremonial first pitch at the Kingdome. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey, who led the American League with 56 homers last season,  
hit a 401-foot drive over the right-center field wall in the third 
inning. The Seattle star homered off James Baldwin of the Chicago 
White Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	After crossing home plate, Griffey gestured to Aaron in the  
Mariners' broadcasting booth. The shot gave the Mariners a 2-1 
lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey hit his seventh opening-day home run, tying the record  
shared by Babe Ruth, Willie Mays, Eddie Mathews and Carl 
Yastrzemski. Frank Robinson leads the all-time list with eight. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey, 29, starting his 11th major league season, hit his  
351st career homer. He is given the best chance among active 
players at catching Aaron's mark of 755 set in 23 seasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
