<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Castle Harlan Fund Gets AMR Svcs. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- One of Castle Harlan Inc.'s investment  
funds has bought AMR Services, a subsidiary of AMR Corporation. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has been renamed Worldwide Flight Services Inc., the  
New York-based Castle Harlan said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition was made by Castle Harlan Partners III, a $630  
million limited partnership for private equity investments. Terms 
were not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has been one of the world's largest providers of  
ground services for more than 200 airlines at some 65 major 
airports around the world. It reported revenues in 1998 of about 
$230 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter A. Pappas, who has worked for AMR Corporation, the parent  
company of American Airlines, for 20 years, will continue to act as 
Worldwide Flight Service's CEO and president. 
</P>
<P>
	AMR announced last year that it would sell some of its  
subsidiaries to concentrate on its core airline business. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
