<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mariners Offers Griffey $100M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Ken Griffey Jr. has been offered several contract  
alternatives worth at least $105 million, The Seattle Times 
reported Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey said he had not yet responded formally to the team's  
multiple offers, all of which reach the level of Kevin Brown's 
record $105 million, seven-year deal with the Los Angeles Dodgers, 
the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just to get it done? I don't think so, not with two years on  
my present contract,'' he was quoted as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking before Monday night's season opener against Chicago,  
Griffey refused to confirm the offers. His agent, Brian Goldberg, 
said last month that the Mariners had begun talks on a possible 
extension. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm tired of all the questions about my contract. If I'm not  
worried about it, I don't think anyone else should be,'' Griffey 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey has two seasons left in a $34 million, four-year  
contract, one that made him baseball's highest-paid player when he 
agreed to the extension in January 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle also wants to work out an extension with All-Star  
shortstop Alex Rodriguez, who has two seasons left in a $10.6 
million five-year deal and will be eligible for free agency at the 
unusually young age of 25. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why don't we just let myself and Alex play baseball?'' Griffey  
said. ``It's 1999. Let's worry about what happens on the field. All 
I want to do is play baseball and not think about contracts. You 
guys are not going to be able to figure me out because there's 
nothing to figure out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey downplayed the dollar figure while talking to The Times,  
saying: ``It ain't about money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both Griffey and Rodriguez are concerned whether the Mariners  
will spend enough to win. He's been in Seattle for 10 years and 
still hasn't reached the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	``And I'm not getting any younger,'' he said. ``The one thing  
you can't buy in this game is that ring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he worries about what the team will do about other key  
players, including Jay Buhner, Edgar Martinez, Dan Wilson, David 
Segui, Jamie Moyer. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of them are up at the end of this year. If they all go  
unsigned, I hope the Mariners don't expect Alex and I to play with 
six, seven guys we don't even know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he would object if the Mariners tried to trade star  
Rodriguez at the end of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone believes I will be the one to stay, that I will be  
easier to sign than Alex. That is not necessarily true,'' Griffey 
said. ``They have six or seven other guys to sign before they deal 
with us, and there isn't one of them (who) wouldn't defer money to 
help us win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey said winning is the most important thing to him.  
</P>
<P>
	``I want this to be the Mariners' year for so many reasons,'' he  
said. ``But we need that good start. If we go 1-9, all the 
questions are going to be fired at me and Alex. Regardless of 
anything, I'll be the last one they get rid of.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
