<DOCNO> APW19990405.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 15:25:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shipbuilder Faces Safety Fines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Federal safety regulators today cited  
Avondale Industries Inc., a major U.S. Navy shipbuilder, for 
hundreds of workplace safety violations, the most serious involving 
inadequate protection to keep workers from taking potentially 
deadly falls. 
</P>
<P>
	The 437 violations alleged by the U.S. Occupational Safety and  
Health Administration carry $537,000 in proposed fines. 
</P>
<P>
	The action came after complaints from the Metal Trades Council  
of the AFL-CIO, which has been engaged in a bitter fight with the 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	``This continued willful disregard for their employees' safety  
is unacceptable,'' said Charles N. Jeffress, the assistant 
secretary of labor for OSHA. 
</P>
<P>
	An attorney for Avondale said the company was the victim of a  
biased investigation and expected to prove that during an appeal. 
The company has 15 days to contest the citations. 
</P>
<P>
	The violations were alleged in 60 citations issued by OSHA  
following a six-month investigation at Avondale's yard, one of 
Louisiana's largest employers with about 6,000 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The most serious allegations involved willful violations of  
federal standards in providing workers adequate protection from 
falling, including having improper scaffolding and guard rails and 
not having manholes and other small openings properly covered. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeffress said that of the seven deaths at Avondale since 1990,  
three of them were caused by falls. He said that OSHA inspectors 
had pointed out the problems in previous examinations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would not take this type of action if we did not consider  
this violations serious to the health and safety of employees,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Avondale officials said they expected a large number  
of citations to be issued, along with a large fine, but said the 
investigation by OSHA was biased and some of its workers had 
created violations through sabotage. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very unusual for a company to accuse its own employees of  
sabotage,'' Jeffress said. ``It's very unusual for a company to 
question the integrity and professionalism of our investigators.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation was conducted by a team of OSHA inspectors  
from around the country with expertise in shipyards, Jeffress said. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of 256 instances of alleged fall-protection violations  
were contained in four citations issued by OSHA. Fifty-five other 
citations covered 207 violations involved such items as stairs, 
ladders, respirators, sanitation welding and protective equipment 
for workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Another citation was issued for a sewerage problem at the yard,  
OSHA said. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale attorney Horace A. ``Topper'' Thompson said he expected  
all of the citations to be tossed out by an administrative law 
judge. He said OSHA's team leader on the inspection ``had the same 
agenda'' as the union. 
</P>
<P>
	For the past six years, Avondale has refused to recognize a  
collective bargaining election held in 1993 by the Metal Trades 
Council. The results of that election, which favored the union, are 
being challenged in federal court by the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale has a proposed merger pending with Newport News  
Shipbuilding. The Pentagon and the Justice Department have not 
objected to the merger. 
</P>
<P>
	However, General Dynamics Corp. has made a $1.36 billion offer  
to buy Newport News, a deal that analysts say could scuttle the 
Avondale merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson said both the Navy and Newport News had been kept  
apprised about the investigation, as well as the company's 
allegations about the propriety of the inspection. OSHA also was 
informed by letter about the company's concerns a month ago, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Monday on the Nasdaq Stock Market, shares of Avondale  
fell 18 3/4 cents to $29.81 1/4. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 22:51:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft To Offer Privacy Tools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hoping to jump-start a promising new privacy  
technology, Microsoft and a prominent Internet group will offer a 
free digital tool kit that one day will allow consumers to restrict 
what personal information Web sites collect about them. 
</P>
<P>
	These new tools, to be announced today, initially will help  
Internet companies write electronic privacy promises that can 
automatically be evaluated by a Web browser or other software using 
a nascent technology called the platform for privacy preferences, 
or P3P. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers today must manually find a company's privacy statement  
online, if one exists, and read through legalese to determine what 
information a Web site might be harvesting, such as their name, 
e-mail address or even favorite authors or clothing sizes. 
</P>
<P>
	Using the new technology, a customer's Internet browser could  
electronically interpret a company's promises, issuing a warning 
only if it can't find a statement or if the Web site wants more 
information than a consumer is willing to disclose. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite support from the world's largest software company,  
hurdles remain and widespread adoption is months, if not years, 
away. 
</P>
<P>
	The technology is mired in a patent dispute and also almost  
certainly will require tens of millions of people on the Internet 
to install new browser software. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's new tools, for example, are based partly on a  
relatively new computer code called extensible markup language, or 
XML, that even the most current versions of some browsers don't yet 
fully support. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft and the San Francisco-based Electronic Frontier  
Foundation planned to make their announcement today at the opening 
of an important privacy conference in Washington. They will propose 
changes in a key specification controlled by the World Wide Web 
Consortium, an Internet standards group, which would allow online 
merchants to use their new digital tools. 
</P>
<P>
	``The technology they're announcing probably isn't the final  
answer, but it's a real positive step,'' said Rick White, former 
co-chairman of the Congressional Internet Caucus who now practices 
technology law in Washington state. ``I'm not certain that 
technology will solve all the problems -- there are some gaps you 
might have to fix in a legislative way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both Congress and the Clinton administration have threatened the  
industry with tough new privacy laws unless companies adequately 
regulate themselves over ways they collect customer information 
across the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The European Union already has passed laws that prohibit the  
transfer of personal information about its citizens without their 
consent to any outside country. The White House is negotiating to 
see how those laws might affect U.S. businesses on the Internet, 
where international borders are blurred. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is going to get a lot of the system up to speed  
quickly,'' predicted Tara Lemmey, executive director of the 
Electronic Frontier Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement is the industry's answer to what it describes  
as a frustrating chicken-and-egg problem -- how to encourage 
Internet consumers to use the new privacy technology until Web 
sites begin to offer electronic promises that can be understood by 
the technology. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we're trying to do here is build a foundation,'' said  
Saul Klein, a group program manager at Microsoft. ``We're not 
saying that we think this is the answer to self-regulation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One serious problem for the technology is a legal battle with  
Seattle-based Intermind Corp., which earlier this year won a patent 
important to P3P. The company has said it is willing to license the 
technology for a reasonable price. 
</P>
<P>
	``Good software patents are expensive, and we were way ahead of  
the curve,'' said Drummond Reed, the company's chief technology 
officer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Web consortium said the group is ``looking seriously ... at  
the validity and applicability of this patent.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 19:32:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                             *John Bibb    	
</P>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- John Bibb, retired sports editor for The  
Tennessean, who once was nominated for Pulitzer Prize and covered 
36 straight Masters golf tournaments, died Sunday of cancer. He was 
72. 
</P>
<P>
	Bibb, a member of the Tennessee Sports Hall of Fame and a  
two-time president of the Golf Writers Association of America, 
worked for The Tennessean from 1942 until his retirement in 1993. 
He was sports editor for the last 23 years. 
</P>
<P>
	He was nominated for a Pulitzer in 1980 for a series of columns  
calling for a U.S. boycott of the 1980 Olympic Games in Moscow. 
</P>
<P>
	Bibb covered numerous U.S. Opens and PGA Championships, the  
British Open and Ryder Cup matches. He covered his first Masters in 
1949. 
</P>
<P>
	Bibb later crossed over into radio. He was a sports commentator  
on WSM's ``Waking Crew'' program and later joined the 
``Roundtable'' program, where he offered views on politics and 
other topics. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife of nearly 50 years, Betty Jean; a son  
and a granddaughter. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Gary Blonston    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gary Blonston, chief of the Knight Ridder  
Washington news bureau and a veteran journalist, died Sunday of 
cancer. He was 56. 
</P>
<P>
	During a career that spanned nearly 36 years, Blonston served as  
a reporter, editor and writing coach. He worked at The Miami 
Herald, The Detroit Free Press and the San Jose Mercury News before 
coming to Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Jonathan Wolman, former Washington bureau chief of The  
Associated Press and now the AP's managing editor, said of 
Blonston: ``He ran one of the best bureaus in town, constantly 
juggling between hard news coverage and the sort of perspective 
pieces that newspapers need from Washington. He had a refined sense 
of irony, just what you need to make sense of it all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blonston was a principal writer on two Pulitzer Prize-winning  
projects. One was during his time at the Free Press, when he came 
under gunfire while covering Detroit's 1967 riots. Blonston also 
worked on the Mercury News' reporting of the 1989 Loma Prieta 
earthquake in the San Francisco Bay area. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1968, Blonston found himself in the middle of rioting  
protesters and police officers outside the Democratic National 
Convention in Chicago. Coughing from tear gas, he dictated his 
story to an editor on deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Blonston also freelanced for newspapers and magazines, on topics  
ranging from politics to prehistoric art. During a 1967 strike at 
the Free Press -- when Blonston was working at Chrysler Corp. -- he 
wrote a book on the history of the Plymouth. In 1996, he published 
``William Morris,'' a book about a famed glass blower. 
</P>
<P>
	Blonston began his newspaper career with The Miami Herald in  
1964, moving to the Free Press two years later. 
</P>
<P>
	He moved to San Jose in 1987, then to Knight Ridder's Washington  
bureau. He became bureau chief in August 1995, supervising a staff 
of 60 reporters and editors. 
</P>
<P>
	Blonston is survived by his wife, Susan Goldberg, a deputy  
managing editor at USA Today, two children from a previous marriage 
and a sister. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Corwin Dwight Denney    	
</P>
<P>
	PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) -- Corwin Dwight Denney, an aerospace  
engineer who began by personally flight-testing his own products, 
died April 1 of pneumonia, following a battle with cancer. He was 
77. 
</P>
<P>
	He began manufacturing aerospace components and flight-test  
equipment in 1947 when he founded American Helicopter Co., forming 
the core of what would become his Fortune 500 company, Automation 
Industries Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Denney served as the lone test pilot for the company, before  
several veterans joined the business at the end of World War II and 
it became known as Mid-Continent Manufacturing. 
</P>
<P>
	The company was soon commissioned by the federal government to  
create complex aircraft structures and nondestructive test 
materials. That funding enabled Denney to merge the business with 
tiny Pasadena-based Automation Instruments in 1952 to form 
Automation Industries Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	While still at the helm of that company, he branched off into  
oil drilling in 1962, forming the independent San Antonio-based 
Venus Oil Co. He later invested in the Beverly Wilshire Hotel in 
Beverly Hills, helping to restore it to profitability before 
selling his share in 1985 for $33 million. 
</P>
<P>
	But he is perhaps best known for orchestrating a score of  
mergers during his three decades as president, chairman of the 
board and chief executive officer of Automation Industries, which 
he sold to General Cable in 1978 for $106 million. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Giulio Einaudi    	
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Giulio Einaudi, an Italian publisher, died Monday of  
a heart attack, the ANSA news agency said. He was 87. 
</P>
<P>
	A medical doctor, Einaudi founded the liberal publishing firm  
that bears his name in 1933 and made it into an important force in 
Italy's intellectual life. 
</P>
<P>
	Einaudi wrote books on literature, history, philosophy, art and  
science. He was also a collector of rare books and prints. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Deil Gustafson    	
</P>
<P>
	CANNON FALLS, Minn. (AP) -- Deil Gustafson, a former owner of  
Summit Banks in the Twin Cities and the Tropicana Hotel and Casino, 
a Las Vegas complex with a history of ties to organized crime, died 
Friday. He was 67. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of death was not available.  
</P>
<P>
	The former businessman and real estate magnate spent 40 months  
in federal prison in the mid-1980s after being convicted of 
participating in a financial scam involving the Tropicana and his 
banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Gustafson sold the Tropicana in 1979, but was under  
investigation as recently as the mid-1990s for allegedly trying to 
hide millions of dollars in proceeds from the sale of the casino. 
He pleaded guilty to bankruptcy fraud in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	He was also deputy director of the late Hubert Humphrey's 1960  
presidential campaign. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Peter Pellegrino    	
</P>
<P>
	NEWTOWN, Pa. (AP) -- Peter Pellegrino, a pilot and ballooning  
enthusiast who trained military air traffic controllers during 
World War II, died March 26 at age 82. 
</P>
<P>
	He played a key role in creating an early national ballooning  
organization, the Balloon Federation of America. Today, the group 
is made up of 100 local clubs with more than 4,000 individual 
members. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Ambroise Roux    	
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Ambroise Roux, an influential business leader who  
was a close adviser to the late President Georges Pompidou, died 
Sunday of a heart attack, the daily Le Monde reported. He was 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Roux was the chief executive officer of one of France's largest  
companies, the Compagnie Generale d'Electricite, for 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting in 1963, Roux wielded considerable power in French  
business and political circles as head of CGE, an industrial group 
now known as Alcatel. 
</P>
<P>
	Roux was close to a number of French politicians, most notably  
Pompidou, whom he advised during a time of enormous growth in 
France's industrial sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Roux worked for a series of government ministries during the  
1950s and then moved to private business, where he fought for lower 
corporate taxes and greater independence for France's corporate 
sector. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Early Wynn    	
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Hall of Fame baseball pitcher Early Wynn, a  
300-game winner and one of the fiercest competitors of his time, 
died Sunday from complications related to a stroke. He was 79. 
</P>
<P>
	Wynn pitched from 1939 to 1963, winning 20 games or more for the  
Cleveland Indians four times and once for the Chicago White Sox in 
the 1950s. 
</P>
<P>
	He was 23-11 in 1954, when the Indians won the American League  
pennant with 111 wins in a 154-game season. In 1959, he won the Cy 
Young Award for the pennant-winning White Sox, posting a 22-10 
record at age 39. 
</P>
<P>
	He was also a good hitter, with 17 career home runs and a  
batting average one season of .319. Managers would use him as a 
pinch hitter. 
</P>
<P>
	Wynn returned to the Indians at age 43, and won his 300th game  
on July 13, 1963. 
</P>
<P>
	After he retired, Wynn was a pitching coach for the Indians and  
Minnesota Twins. He was inducted into the Hall of Fame in 1972. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
