<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China OKs Four Foreign Insurers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China granted licenses to four foreign insurance  
companies on Monday after saying earlier it would open its tightly 
controlled insurance market to competition from abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	The license issues to the U.S., Canadian and British firms come  
on the eve of Premier Zhu Rongji's departure for a 14-day visit to 
the United States and Canada. He hopes to win a deal in Washington 
on China's entry to the World Trade Organization, and insurance and 
other financial services are a sticking point in the protracted 
negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's newcomers are the Chubb Group of Insurance Cos. and  
John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co., both of the U.S., Sun Life 
Assurance Co. of Canada and Britain's Prudential Corp. They join 
nine other insurers doing business in China. 
</P>
<P>
	Granting the licenses will help to ``further restructure China's  
insurance mechanism and to open wider China's insurance market,'' 
the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	China requires all foreign life insurance companies to find  
Chinese partners before they can sell insurance in the country. 
Foreign companies aren't allowed to hold a controlling stake and 
life insurance companies are may only sell individual life 
insurance plans. 
</P>
<P>
	China also limits foreign insurance sales to only two cities -  
Shanghai and Guangzhou. But industry executives say insurance 
regulators are prepared to soon open up to 10 more cities for 
foreign insurers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
