<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> High Court Clarifies Case Transfers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today clarified the deadline  
for transferring cases from state court to federal court, saying 
the 30-day clock begins to run when someone is formally served and 
receives a copy of a lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-3 ruling allows an Illinois company to have a  
breach-of-contract lawsuit against it moved from an Alabama state 
court to a federal court. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the company was faxed a copy of the lawsuit two  
weeks before it was formally served, the 30-day clock did not begin 
to run until formal service was completed, the justices said. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law gives defendants 30 days after receiving a lawsuit  
``through service or otherwise'' to transfer it to federal court 
when the parties are from different states. 
</P>
<P>
	Writing for the court, Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg said  
defendants' time to transfer a case to federal court begins when 
they receive formal service and a copy of the lawsuit, or when they 
receive a copy of the complaint sometime after being formally 
served, ``but not by mere receipt of the complaint unattended by 
any formal service.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That ``assures defendants adequate time to decide whether to  
remove an action to federal court,'' Ginsburg wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Murphy Bros. of East Moline, Ill., was sued in Alabama state  
court Jan. 26, 1996, by Michetti Pipe Stringing, based in Nisku, 
Alberta, Canada. Michetti accused Murphy of breaking a contract and 
fraud involving a construction project in Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	Michetti faxed a copy of the lawsuit to Murphy's vice president  
the following Jan. 29. Murphy was formally served with the lawsuit 
by certified mail Feb. 12. 
</P>
<P>
	On the following March 13, Murphy had the case transferred to  
federal court on grounds the companies were from different states. 
It made the request within 30 days after receiving formal service, 
but 44 days after getting the faxed copy of the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Michetti asked a federal judge to return the case to state  
court, saying Murphy waited too long after receiving the lawsuit by 
fax. The judge refused, saying the time limit did not begin to run 
until the case was served by certified mail. 
</P>
<P>
	The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals disagreed and sent the  
case back to state court. The clock begins running when someone 
receives a copy of a lawsuit ``by any means,'' the court said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court disagreed. Ginsburg's ruling was joined by  
Justices John Paul Stevens, Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony M. 
Kennedy, David H. Souter and Stephen G. Breyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia  
and Clarence Thomas dissented. Writing for the three, Rehnquist 
said the ``plain language'' of the law required the 30-day clock to 
begin running when the lawsuit was faxed to Murphy. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Murphy Bros. vs. Michetti Pipe Stringing, 97-1909.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 13:55:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Capitol Hill Quiet for Another Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress began the second week of its Easter  
recess Monday, leaving for next week any debate on the U.S. role in 
the growing turmoil in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	While some members of the armed services and intelligence  
committees were in Washington to keep abreast of developments in 
the crisis, neither the House nor Senate were in session or will 
hold hearings this week. 
</P>
<P>
	A schedule drawn up at the beginning of the year had the House  
back in session this week, but new Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., 
revised that to give House members the same two weeks off that the 
Senate is enjoying. The Easter break is commonly used to work in 
home districts or take fact-finding trips around the country or 
abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	Kosovo is expected to be a major topic when they return next  
Tuesday: Appropriators must make quick decisions about the cost of 
the military mission and whether to pay for it through emergency 
spending or by increasing the fiscal year 2000 defense budget. The 
House and Senate have an April 15 deadline for coming up with a 
plan for the 2000 budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
