<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 00:22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Blasts Serb Targets  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO blasted at Serb targets Monday  
that reportedly included an air force building, army barracks and 
the capital's airport, while the allies planned an airlift of 
ethnic Albanian refugees flooding out of Kosovo province. Amid a 
heavy new wave of airstrikes late Sunday and early Monday across 
Serbia, the United States signaled an escalation of firepower to 
halt Serb attacks on Kosovo's Albanian majority. Washington agreed 
to send 24 Apache helicopter gunships, 2,000 troops and a missile 
launching system to Albania to give NATO the ability to directly 
attack Serb troops and tanks in Kosovo, a province of Serbia, 
Yugoslavia's dominant republic. NATO leaders meeting Monday must 
approve use of the weapons. 

</P>
<P>
	Can Antibiotic Stop Heart Attacks?  
</P>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Researchers hope to find out if taking an  
antibiotic will spare heart patients from future heart attacks, 
bypass surgery or even death. In a federally funded study based on 
growing evidence a common bacterial infection may trigger heart 
attacks and worsen, perhaps even cause, atherosclerosis -- narrowing 
of the arteries from plaque deposits. Given that known risk factors 
for heart disease such as smoking, high cholesterol and high blood 
pressure can't account for many cases, doctors increasingly suspect 
infectious agents may be partly to blame for some of the 1.75 
million heart attacks, bypass surgeries and artery-clearing 
angioplasties in this country each year. 

</P>
<P>
	Va. Workers Strike Newport News  
</P>
<P>
	NEWPORT NEWS, Va. (AP) -- Thousands of workers went on strike at  
Newport News Shipbuilding at midnight Sunday. ``We haven't heard a 
word'' from shipyard management, Arnold Outlaw, president of Local 
8888 of the United Steelworkers of America, said before the final 
hour. The union, which represents many of the yard's 9,200 hourly 
workers, had said it would strike over what it says are 
insufficient raises in a proposed new contract. In the new 
contract, the union wants an across-the-board hourly pay increase 
of $3.95 over three years. 

</P>
<P>
	Extradition of Libyans Expected  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Arab and African dignitaries began arriving  
in Libya Sunday to witness the handover of two suspects in the 1988 
Pan Am bombing. The convergence of officials followed reports that 
the chief U.N. legal counsel, Hans Corell, had left for Europe on 
Friday on his way to Libya to arrange the handover. Lamen Khalifa 
Fhimah, 42 and Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi, 46, are to be tried 
under Scottish law in the Netherlands. The bombing killed 270 
people, mostly Americans and Britons 

</P>
<P>
	Salvation for Ruined Mormon Church  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A top Mormon official said Sunday that the  
church will rebuild the historic Nauvoo Temple in Illinois which 
was destroyed by arson and a tornado after the Mormons went West. 
The temple was dedicated in 1846 after most of the embattled 
Mormons had left for the Salt Lake Valley. It was destroyed in an 
arson fire two years later. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Companies See Profits Drop  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- According to Fortune magazine's annual listing  
of the largest U.S. public companies, profits at the Fortune 500 
companies declined for the first time in seven years in 1998. U.S. 
companies suffered the effects of the economic crisis in Asia, 
Russia and Latin America, as profits for the 500 fell 1.8 percent 
last year, compared to 7.8 percent earnings growth in 1997. GM 
topped the list for the 11th year straight, taking in $161.3 
billion in 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock Prices Up  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stock prices rose Monday. The Nikkei  
gained 44.59 points to close at 16,334.78. 

</P>
<P>
	Heat 90, Wizards 79  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Miami Heat survived a fourth-quarter  
drought to end their worst losing streak in three years, with 
Alonzo Mourning scoring 24 points and grabbing 17 rebounds Sunday 
in a 90-79 victory over the Washington Wizards. Tim Hardaway added 
20 points and eight assists for the Heat, whose four-game skid was 
their worst since April 1996. Juwan Howard led the Wizards with 20 
points. 

</P>
<P>
	Hawks 85, Hornets 83  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Mookie Blaylock scored seven points late in the  
fourth quarter and Grant Long hit a baseline jumper with 2.6 
seconds left Sunday, carrying the Atlanta Hawks to an 85-83 victory 
over the Charlotte Hornets. Alan Henderson led the Hawks with 18 
points and reserve Tyrone Corbin added 15. Jones led Charlotte with 
16 points and Derrick Coleman had 18 rebounds and 14 points. Chucky 
Brown and Elden Campbell scored 14 points each. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  

</P>
