<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Example of How 'Marriage Tax' Works </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An example of how the federal tax code  
penalizes married couples who earn comparable salaries. 

</P>
<P>
	A machinist and a school teacher each earn $31,500 a year, or  
$63,000 combined. 
</P>
<P>
	If single, they can each take a standard deduction and a  
personal exemption totaling $6,950, leaving them with a taxable 
income of $24,550 apiece, subject to a 15 percent tax. 
</P>
<P>
	These typical singles would each pay $3,682 in tax, or $7,364  
combined. 
</P>
<P>
	But if the same machinist and teacher marry, they are subject to  
different tax rates and deductions. 
</P>
<P>
	They can only take $12,500 for the personal exemption and  
standard deduction, leaving them with $50,500 that is partly 
subject to a 28 percent tax rate. 
</P>
<P>
	That means the married pair pays $8,635 in tax -- a ``penalty''  
of $1,271. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
