<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Up, Coffee Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude and its products advanced Monday on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange after U.N. officials said American airstrikes 
on Iraqi targets last week may have damaged a pipeline delivering 
oil. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, coffee futures fell sharply, while beef and  
pork futures rose sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude edged closer to their highest levels in a year after oil  
experts for the United Nations, which is overseeing the sale of 
Iraqi oil for humanitarian purposes, reported there was a drop in 
flow from the Bazarkan oil fields. 
</P>
<P>
	Iraq previously had said missile attacks from British and  
American planes in the southern no-fly zone of that country had 
damaged a pipeline control center, although the Clinton 
administration denied any pipeline damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Iraq reported the pipeline operating as of Saturday, but experts  
said it was operating Monday at least 45 percent below normal 
capacity. 
</P>
<P>
	A slowdown in shipments from Iraq would come at a time when  
other OPEC members are moving to reduce daily output in a bid to 
push prices per barrel above $17. Such a sustained rally would put 
prices at their highest in more than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude and unleaded gasoline prices have risen at the fastest  
rate since the Gulf War on those moves. Refinery problems on the 
West Coast have also contributed to the increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Light, sweet crude for May delivery rose 31 cents from trading  
Thursday to $16.95 barrel; May unleaded gasoline rose .88 cent to 
53.98 cents a gallon; May heating oil rose .62 cent to 44.02 cents 
a gallon; May natural gas fell .008 cent to $2.030 for each 1,000 
cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee futures tumbled more than 2 percent on the Board of Trade  
of the City of New York as fresh supplies from producers continued 
to arrive at a time when consumption levels generally decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee prices had rebounded recently as roasters took advantage  
of prices at their lowest in nearly three years to replenish 
inventories, but those gains now have led to diminished buying even 
as new supplies of stored Latin American crops roll in. 
</P>
<P>
	May arabica coffee fell 2.75 cents to $1.073 a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Beef and pork futures moved strongly higher on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange amid expectations the Clinton administration 
soon will begin buying meat and livestock for donation to Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has pledged 150,000 tons of beef and 50,000 tons  
of pork to aid cash-strapped Russia in a move that also was meant 
to help producers slash large surpluses that grew over the winter. 
</P>
<P>
	But Chuck Levitt, an analyst at Alaron Trading Corp., noted the  
purchase now will come at a time when supplies are tightest. Demand 
typically rises sharply around this time of year as Americans begin 
the outdoor grilling season. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .55 cent to 67.65 cents a pound; May  
feeder cattle rose 1.10 cents to 74 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
rose 1.15 cents to 54.10 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose .60 
cent to 52.30 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
