<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Salon Magazine Undergoes Makeover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The online magazine Salon, an Internet  
pioneer, is undergoing a makeover, obtaining the desirable domain 
address of www.salon.com from a beauty salon owner. 
</P>
<P>
	The new address is one of several changes being announced today  
by Salon, which is published by Salon Internet Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	David Talbot, Salon's editor and founder, said the magazine  
plans an expansion into breaking news. It will also be introducing 
two new sections, focusing on health and people. Obituaries and a 
daily gossip column are being added. The magazine has hired 20 
employees and is opening an office in Washington, D.C., with two 
staff reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Talbot said the domain name is key to revitalizing the  
publication. 
</P>
<P>
	Salon magazine had been residing at three Internet addresses --  
www.salon1999.com, www.salonmagazine.com and www.salon.net -- since 
its November 1995 debut. 
</P>
<P>
	But many potential readers expected to find the magazine at  
www.salon.com. Instead, they found themselves at a Web site owned 
by Roy Frederickson, who owns two beauty salons in Austin, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Talbot finally persuaded Frederickson to sell his domain name  
for a promise of stock, an undisclosed sum of cash and the 
salon.net domain. On Salon magazine's new home page, there is a 
link to Frederickson's page. 
</P>
<P>
	Talbot is counting not only on the new address but on a national  
advertising campaign, a newly designed site and a larger staff to 
help attract visitors to the publication. With the old address, 
Salon had been attracting 1.2 million visitors a month, according 
to Talbot. 
</P>
<P>
	The San Francisco-based magazine posted revenue of $3.5 million  
in its fiscal year ended April 1, derived largely from advertising. 
Talbot said Salon was not yet profitable. 
</P>
<P>
	Salon attracted controversy last September when it reported that  
Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the chairman of the House Judiciary 
Committee who would lead the impeachment effort against President 
Clinton, had once been involved in an extramarital affair. 
</P>
<P>
	Jonathan Broder, the magazine's Washington bureau chief,  
resigned over the magazine's decision to reveal the affair. He said 
at the time that ``there was no public issue involved'' in Hyde's 
conduct. Many news organizations knew of allegations about an 
affair dating to Hyde's career before Congress, but decided against 
a story. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
