<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sosa Set to Start Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Sammy Sosa is starting where he left off last  
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago Cubs star hit his final 1998 home run against the  
Houston Astros' Jose Lima in the Astrodome last Sept. 25, giving 
him a 66-65 lead over Mark McGwire in the race for the home record. 
McGwire then hit five in his final three games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year I was ready, but I think in 1999 I am more ready  
because a lot of people are expecting me and Mark to come back and 
do the same way and I'm really ready to see this through,'' Sosa 
said today as the Cubs and Astros prepared for Tuesday night's 
game, the final season opener in the Astrodome. 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa looks muscled up this spring and hit a major league-high 12  
homers, three more than McGwire and Seattle's Russ Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	``My last home run was here last year and tomorrow we start  
again,'' Sosa said, ``but last year is over and I want to start 
again, and have a great year. I have to say that he's ready and I'm 
ready.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For another record?  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to say it's not going to happen,'' Sosa said.  
``It could happen or it could not. Right now, we're just trying to 
get ready for the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa will face Astros ace Shane Reynolds (19-8, 3.51 ERA last  
season). Steve Trachsel (15-8, 4.46) will start for the Cubs, 
shaken during spring training with the season-ending injury to 
Kerry Wood. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sosa seems pretty hot right now,'' Astros manager Larry  
Dierker said. ``That's the way we left him in September. I'm not 
sure if there's ever a good time to face him but I'm satisfied to 
be facing the Cubs and Brewers this homestand. It gives us a 
preview as far as what we're up against.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Sosa added some weight during the offseason, Cubs manager  
Jim Riggleman thinks it may help. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it was by design,'' Riggleman said. ``He maintained  
his strength last year. He felt in previous years he lost weight 
during the season. Last year he maintained it and felt that was the 
formula for success.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Sosa hit for average, he trailed McGwire 24-9 in the home  
run, before hitting 20 in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa led just twice -- 48-47 on Aug. 19 and on Sept. 25, when  
Lima surrendered No. 66 to his countryman. Sosa won't get a shot at 
Lima (16-8, 3.70) until Thursday night. Sosa hit four homers 
against the Astros last season, including three off Lima. 
</P>
<P>
	``You look at lineups these days, and the top two guys are the  
McGwires and Sosas coming off last year,'' Reynolds said. ``But 
there are guys all over on every team that you have to watch. With 
these guys, you've got to take them more serious but other guys can 
get you too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lima allowed 34 homers in all, the fourth-highest total in the  
NL. After he gave up Nos. 50 and 51 at Wrigley Field on Aug. 23, 
there was a published report questioning whether Lima grooved a 
pitch for the Cubs star. Both players denied the allegation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll try not to let him hit any more home runs off me; then  
they can't say I grooved it for him,'' Lima said. ``I hope I can 
strike him out three times Thursday and then everyone will have to 
keep his mouth shut.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
