<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson vs. Brown in Opener Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Coming your way today: the Big Unit and his  
blazing fastball against the sidewinding Georgian and his nasty 
slider. 
</P>
<P>
	Opening day at Dodger Stadium features Randy Johnson of the  
Arizona Diamondbacks against Kevin Brown of the Los Angeles 
Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	A dream matchup, for sure.  
</P>
<P>
	Runs will no doubt be at a premium, just as they were last fall  
when Johnson and Brown squared off in the opener of the NL division 
series between the Houston Astros and San Diego Padres. 
</P>
<P>
	The final score? 2-1, Padres.  
</P>
<P>
	``Imagine that,'' Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley said with a  
smile. 
</P>
<P>
	Thanks to some big bucks, Johnson and Brown have changed teams  
since their last meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Brown vs. the Unit; opening day,'' Hundley said. ``It's going  
to be fun. If I was going to go to an opening day, ours is the one 
I'd go to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The game has been a sellout for weeks, and much anticipated  
since Johnson signed a $52.4 million, four-year contract with the 
Diamondbacks on Nov. 30, and Brown became baseball's richest player 
when he signed a $105 million, seven-year deal with the Dodgers 12 
days later. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's good for baseball, to have two of the most dominant  
pitchers in the game throw against each other on opening day,'' Los 
Angeles second baseman Eric Young said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never faced him before,'' Dodgers shortstop Mark  
Grudzielanek said of Johnson. ``The biggest thing I think is you 
can't be overwhelmed by him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's easier said than done when the time comes to face the  
6-foot-10 left-hander. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown might not be 6-10, but facing him is no walk in the park,  
either. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no question he's one of the best pitchers in the  
league,'' Grudzielanek said. ``He's tough, he's not making that 
kind of money for nothing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grudzielanek was speaking about Johnson; he just as easily could  
have been talking about Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	While Johnson has been baseball's dominant left-hander in the  
1990s, mostly with the Seattle Mariners, Brown has been one of the 
toughest right-handers, especially the last three years, when he's 
gone 51-26 with a major league-best 2.33 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, who helped the Florida Marlins and Padres reach the World  
Series in the last two years, was 18-7 with a 2.38 ERA in 1998 and 
could become the first pitcher to appear in three consecutive World 
Series with three different teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, that's his goal for this year.  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 10-1 with a 1.28 ERA after the Astros acquired him from  
Seattle last July 31, said he still feels honored to pitch on 
opening day, and expects a playoff-type environment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been in that atmosphere, whether it's been in the  
playoffs or the All-Star games,'' he said. ``I have a job to do and 
I don't get caught up in all of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As far as facing Brown is concerned, Johnson said, ``I've faced  
him once before and just thought it was a very well-pitched game by 
both of us, and I'm imagining it's going to be the same thing on 
opening day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown downplayed the duel.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not pitching against him, although I'll face him at least  
a couple times,'' Brown said. ``I've got to get those other guys 
out. My job's still the same. 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks are hoping for significant improvement in just  
their second year of existence, while the retooled Dodgers are 
favored to win the NL West. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm real excited,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said.  
``We've had a great spring. Now, we've got to prove that we're a 
good club.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
