<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cards Put Lankford, Howard on DL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Opening day wasn't a thrill for St. Louis  
Cardinals players Ray Lankford and David Howard, who were placed on 
15-day disabled list today. 
</P>
<P>
	Lankford, who hit .293 with 31 homers and 105 RBIs last year,  
has been slow to recover from knee surgery performed in November 
and played only two games as a designated hitter this spring. 
Howard had won the second base job until he pulled a groin muscle 
in his final spring at-bat Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've wanted to start forever and finally was told I was going  
to,'' Howard said. ``Then to do it in the last inning of the last 
spring game, it's really disappointing. I wish I wouldn't have run 
as hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Infielders Placido Polanco and Luis Ordaz, who had been optioned  
to Triple-A Memphis on Saturday, were recalled. They didn't 
actually left the team because the moves had been anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never expect to start a season without problems,'' said  
manager Tony La Russa, who began last year without three starting 
pitchers. ``Right now, even though we've taken a hit or two or 
three, we still have the depth that we can play through it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie J.D. Drew, whose best position is center field, will  
replace Lankford in center for the first week or so. Polanco 
started the opener at second base. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard hit .262 with surprising power this spring -- four homers  
and 10 RBIs in 61 at-bats. He has only 10 homers in 593 career 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	But he's been fragile during his career. This is his eighth  
stint on the disabled list in nine seasons. Last year Howard was on 
the DL twice with a sprained left shoulder and played in only 46 
games, batting .245 with two homers and 12 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	The news wasn't all bad Monday. Shortstop Edgar Renteria, who  
didn't play in a major league spring game due to a bone bruise in 
his right knee, started and batted leadoff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
