<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers' Lindros Still in Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Doctors won't know until midweek when  
hospitalized Flyers captain Eric Lindros can return to 
Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	And it will take several more days to determine if his collapsed  
lung mends fast enough to let him skate in the playoffs that start 
in less than three weeks, Flyers team physician Dr. Gary Dorshimer 
said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorshimer said those answers depend on what happens after  
doctors at Nashville's Baptist Hospital discontinue the suction in 
a tube in Lindros' chest to determine if the lung can remain 
inflated without the assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	Still in pain from the injury, Lindros had hoped to return for  
the playoffs, refusing to ``rule anything out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though there was speculation Lindros was injured when hit during  
the Flyers' 2-1 win Thursday night at Nashville, he said he felt 
pain but didn't think it was serious. ``I went out and had a 
cheeseburger and fries,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Later Thursday and early Friday, Dorshimer said Lindros  
experienced ``a progressive feeling of weakness, tiredness and 
shortness of breath and then eventually lightheadedness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the lightheadedness, a Flyers spokesman disputed a USA  
Today report Monday that Lindros had collapsed in his Nashville 
hotel room. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it is a matter of semantics. I don't think he  
collapsed, but he was taken by ambulance'' to the hospital, team 
spokesman Joe Klueg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros felt chest pains Friday. Roommate Keith Jones told The  
Philadelphia Inquirer that Lindros was ``a hurtin' pup'' by the 
time Jones called Flyers trainer John Worley, who called the 
ambulance. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorshimer said Lindros did not appear to have a broken rib or  
punctured lung, but apparently broke a blood vessel. Blood seeping 
into his chest cavity caused his right lung to collapse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
