<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fujitsu, Hitachi Plan Super-Thin TVs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Fujitsu Ltd. and Hitachi Ltd. will set up a joint  
venture company to make plasma display panels for super-thin 
televisions, a media report said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The venture will make a 50-inch thin television targeted at the  
consumer market from next year, the Nihon Keizai newspaper reported 
in its evening edition. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies will share the cost of building a plant to  
produce the high-resolution displays, which would employ around 800 
workers -- with about 700 of them coming from Fujitsu, the paper 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fujitsu, one of Japan's biggest electronics companies, was the  
first in the world to begin making plasma displays in 1996 and now 
manufactures about 10,000 panels a month at a plant in northern 
Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Hitachi was planning to get into the business on its own later  
this year but the companies decided to join together to reduce 
costs, the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fujitsu's existing plasma TV operations will become a wholly  
owned subsidiary of the new company. 
</P>
<P>
	Hitachi and Fujitsu spokesmen confirmed they would make a joint  
announcement regarding plasma display panels on Tuesday but refused 
to provide further details. 
</P>
<P>
	High prices for plasma TVs -- 42-50 inch models cost between 1  
million ($8,300) and 2.5 million ($20,800) -- have kept them out of 
reach of most consumers so far. The thin televisions are currently 
used mostly for advertising in airports, railway stations and 
department stores. 
</P>
<P>
	The new joint-venture company aims to sell the 50-inch model to  
ordinary consumers for about 500,000 yen ($4,150), the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The global market for plasma displays is expected to grow from  
some 70 billion yen ($583 million) in the fiscal year ended in 
March to more than 1 trillion ($8.3 billion) by fiscal year 2005, 
according to Nomura Research Institute Ltd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
