<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Finds Stainless Steel Is Dumped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration moved a step closer  
to slapping punitive tariffs on Japan, Spain and four other 
countries Monday with a ruling that they illegally price some 
stainless steel in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Shipments of stainless round wire from those countries would be  
subject to tariffs of as much as 36 percent if an independent 
fact-finding agency determines that their pricing practices have 
injured or could injure U.S. producers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department ruling represents the latest in a string  
of victories for the U.S. steel industry, which has yet to lose a 
key ruling in trade complaints filed to combat low-priced imports. 
</P>
<P>
	Those successes paradoxically have made it more difficult for  
domestic producers to put foreign steel products under quotas or 
stronger sanctions to fend off imports blamed for thousands of 
layoffs and bankruptcies at three U.S. companies. Administration 
officials cite the favorable rulings as evidence the normal 
administrative process works. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten U.S. manufacturers sought tariffs a year ago, accusing  
Canada, India, Japan, South Korea, Spain and Taiwan of dumping 
round wire in the U.S. market at prices below production costs or 
home-market prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Stainless steel round wire, used to produce springs, wire rope  
and fasteners in construction and other applications, represents a 
small portion of the overall steel industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, Monday's dumping determination by the Commerce  
Department adds to relief the U.S. steel industry could get in 
response to the import surge. 
</P>
<P>
	A crucial decision covering the most common steel product,  
hot-rolled carbon steel, is due this month. The Commerce Department 
already has found evidence of dumping by Japan, Russia and Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan and Brazil face steel tariffs in the hot-rolled case,  
while Russia has agreed to curb exports instead of similar tariffs. 
A U.S. comment period for implementing the Russian agreement closed 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. International Trade Commission is to rule by mid-May on  
whether round wire dumping has or could hurt the U.S. industry. 
That's the last step before tariffs are imposed. 
</P>
<P>
	Tariffs proposed by the Commerce Department ranged from 3  
percent for stainless round wire from South Korea to 36 percent for 
the product from Spain's main producer. Japanese round wire could 
be subject to tariffs of up to 30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Stainless steel round wire is a $300 million-a-year domestic  
industry, and imports add another $100 million, industry officials 
said. Shipments from the six countries under Commerce Department 
scrutiny account for one-third of all imports. 
</P>
<P>
	The government already has imposed tariffs on stainless wire  
rod, the precursor to round wire, and has found six countries 
guilty of dumping stainless plates in coils, which could lead to 
more tariffs if injury is proven. Other complaints are pending. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases acted on Monday were filed by ACS Industries Inc. of  
Woonsocket, R.I.; Al Tech Specialty Steel Corp. of Dunkirk, N.Y.; 
Branford Wire &AMP; Manufacturing Co. of Mountain Home, N.C.; Carpenter 
Technology Corp. of Reading, Pa.; Handy &AMP; Herman Specialty Wire 
Group of Cockeysville, Md; Industrial Alloys Inc. of Pomona, Calif; 
Loos &AMP; Co. Inc. of Pomfret, Conn.; Sandvik Steel Co. of Clarks 
Summit, Pa.; Sumiden Wire Products Corp. of Stockton, Calif.; and 
Techalloy Co. Inc. of Mahwah, N.J. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 16:14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wizards Fire Coach Bickerstaff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Under Bernie Bickerstaff, the Washington  
Wizards became a tentative, underachieving team that froze in the 
fourth quarter. A team lacking the needed hustle for coming up with 
the big rebound or loose ball. 
</P>
<P>
	In danger of missing the playoffs for the 10th time in 11 years  
and struggling at 13-19, the Wizards fired Bickerstaff on Monday 
and replaced him on an interim basis with assistant Jim Brovelli. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very difficult. It was something I didn't want to do  
today, but I felt I had to,'' said general manager Wes Unseld, 
whose friendship with Bickerstaff dates to the 1970s, when Unseld 
played in Washington and Bickerstaff was an assistant coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way we were going, philosophically maybe, my thinking was  
different. It just wasn't happening, and it didn't seem to change. 
With 18 games left and a chance to still be in this thing, I 
decided to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unseld said he would start contacting coaching candidates  
immediately, although he did not rule out Brovelli as a long-term 
solution. Brovelli, 57, was 1-1 in his NBA head coaching debut 
earlier this season when Bickerstaff was out with the flu. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes it harder because it's Bernie,'' said Brovelli, who  
wouldn't comment directly on whether he's interested in keeping the 
job. ``He gave me the first opportunity to coach in the league. I'm 
going to miss him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Wizards, who lost 90-79 to Miami on Sunday, are in fifth  
place in the Atlantic Division and not in playoff contention. They 
have one of the best backcourts in the league in Mitch Richmond and 
Rod Strickland and a top forward in Juwan Howard, but lack a 
quality center. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wizards' real nemesis, however, has been the fourth quarter.  
They have held the lead in 20 of their 31 games after three 
quarters, but they have lost nine of those. 
</P>
<P>
	``What it boiled down to more than anything was I did not think  
we were a loose and relaxed basketball team,'' guard Tim Legler 
said. ``The atmosphere was very tense, and lot of guys were playing 
very defensive, rather than being aggressive and offensive on the 
court. ... I think that's indicative of what's happened this year 
when we've had close games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bickerstaff sometimes left players baffled with his novel player  
rotations. Several times this season he would play a starter for 
five minutes, then bench him for the rest of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things like that tend to confuse you a little bit,'' said  
swingman Calbert Cheaney, whose playing time has varied greatly 
since losing his starting job early in the season. ``Hopefully, we 
can get back to a little more consistency in terms of how players 
are going to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the losses mounted, Bickerstaff admitted he wasn't able to  
get his players to produce the intangibles for a fourth-quarter 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a missing ingredient,'' Bickerstaff said after  
Sunday's game. ``And the ingredient is you have to look yourself 
and say, `Do we have the innate ability to do those things?' To me, 
it doesn't take skill, it takes an awareness of what needs to be 
done in terms of, `There's a rebound, a loose ball, I have to get 
it.''' 
</P>
<P>
	But Bickerstaff also said his team simply wasn't as talented as  
teams such as Miami, something that didn't sit well with his 
players or Unseld. 
</P>
<P>
	``The personnel we have should be in the playoffs,'' Unseld  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brovelli said the Wizards' problem was ``more of mental thing.''  
</P>
<P>
	``We just have to get to a confidence level where we know in the  
fourth quarter that we can change and hopefully finish it out,'' 
Brovelli said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bickerstaff's dismissal is the NBA's fourth coaching change this  
season, following Del Harris (Lakers), Dave Cowens (Charlotte) and 
John Calipari (New Jersey). 
</P>
<P>
	Bickerstaff was in his 10th season as an NBA coach. His record  
was 338-348, including 77-71 with the Wizards. He began his 
coaching career in Washington in 1973, serving as an assistant 
until 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	Bickerstaff's best showing as a coach was in 1987, when he led  
Seattle to the Western Conference finals, one of three postseason 
appearances with the SuperSonics. 
</P>
<P>
	He was lured from his job as general manager of the Denver  
Nuggets and hired by the Wizards after the All-Star break during 
the 1996-97 season, leading Washington to its first postseason 
appearance since 1988. The Wizards were 42-40 last season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
