<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mueller Breaks Toe in First At-Bat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- San Francisco third baseman Bill Mueller broke  
his big left toe when he was hit by a pitch in his first at-bat of 
the season today. 
</P>
<P>
	Mueller couldn't get out of the way of Brett Tomko's breaking  
pitch in the first inning of the Giants' opener against the 
Cincinnati Reds. Tomko's fourth pitch to Mueller hit him squarely 
on the back foot, causing him to drop to the ground in pain. 
</P>
<P>
	After a couple of minutes, he got up and hobbled to first base.  
When Barry Bonds pulled the next pitch foul, Mueller took two steps 
toward second base and collapsed. 
</P>
<P>
	He was helped off the field and X-rays revealed the fracture.  
There was no immediate indication how long Mueller would be out. 
</P>
<P>
	Charlie Hayes replaced Mueller at third.  
</P>
<P>
	Mueller, 28, started 126 games at third last season, his third  
with the Giants. He hit .294 with nine homers and 59 RBIs last 
season, both career highs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
