<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Va. Workers Strike Newport News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWPORT NEWS, Va. (AP) -- Work continued today at Newport News  
Shipbuilding despite the first strike in 20 years against the only 
shipyard that builds and refuels the Navy's nuclear-powered 
aircraft carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of Local 8888 of the United Steelworkers struck in a  
dispute over wages and benefits when their contract expired at 
midnight Sunday. The union represents 9,200 hourly workers out of 
the yard's total 17,400 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're being very productive. It's quiet and orderly,''  
shipyard spokeswoman Jerri Fuller Dickseski said Monday. She said a 
number of employees reported for work, although she declined to be 
specific. 
</P>
<P>
	Local president Arnold Outlaw said he did not know exactly how  
many workers were on strike but ``I don't think there's very many 
(union) members in the shipyard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Union members picketed outside the shipyard's gates, shouting  
``Scab!'' as cars carrying nonstriking workers drove past at 
midafternoon. About a dozen police officers stood nearby. 
</P>
<P>
	No negotiating sessions had been held since union members voted  
Thursday to reject what the shipyard called its final offer, and 
Ms. Dickseski said none were scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	The union demanded an across-the-board hourly pay increase of  
$3.95 over three years. The current top rate for a mechanic is 
$14.53. 
</P>
<P>
	The shipyard offered wage increases over three years that it  
said would boost the average worker's pay $2.49 an hour, with 
automatic promotions based on experience and skills. 
</P>
<P>
	The last strike at the yard, in 1979, lasted three months.  
</P>
<P>
	The shipyard builds the Navy's Nimitz-class nuclear-powered  
aircraft carriers and repairs and refuels them. Ms. Dickseski said 
the strike had no effect on the shipyard's contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	The yard currently is building the aircraft carrier Ronald  
Reagan, refueling the carrier USS Nimitz and doing some maintenance 
work on the carrier USS Harry S. Truman. The yard also is working 
on the USS Norwall, a submarine scheduled to be deactivated. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Newport News fell 75 cents to $30.25 in trading on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
