<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Monday on the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq Stock Market, 
and American Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	
</P>
<P>
	Rental Service, up 5 at 22 1/4  
</P>
<P>
	The Scottsdale, Ariz.-based rental company was the target of a  
$1.36 billion unsolicited takeover bid by United Rentals, the 
largest equipment rental company in North America. United wants to 
buy Rental Service for $22.75 a share, a 32 percent premium over 
Rental Service's closing price of $17.25 on Thursday. 

</P>
<P>
	Pediatrix, down 9 1/2 at 17 1/8  
</P>
<P>
	The Fort Lauderdale, Fla.-based physician management company  
expects first-quarter earnings to fall short of Wall Street 
estimates because of higher-than-normal accounting and legal 
expenses. The company expects earnings to fall between 1 and 4 
cents below expectations. 

</P>
<P>
	Compaq, unchanged at 31 9/16  
</P>
<P>
	The Palo Alto, Calif.-based computer maker completed its  
acquisition of Zip2 Corp., which hosts and maintains consumer Web 
sites for media companies. Compaq said Zip2 will be a unit of its 
AltaVista unit and provide local news content on AltaVista's portal 
Web site. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
	National Research, down 1 1/16 at 2 9/16  
</P>
<P>
	The Lincoln, Neb. health care performance measurement firm said  
it expects delays in converting to a new, automated production 
system will significantly hurt revenue for the first quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	Mosaix, up 2 3/8 at 10 3/4  
</P>
<P>
	The Redmond, Wash. based-operator of computerized call center  
systems agreed to be acquired by Lucent Technologies in a stock 
swap valued at about $145 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Mapics, down, down 2 3/4 at 4 9/16  
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta-based software provider expects second-quarter  
earnings to fall short of Wall Street expectations. Analysts were 
expecting 18 cents a share, according to First Cal Corp. The 
company said it would be below the 16 cents a share it earned in 
the second quarter of 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	Aspen, down 3 5/16 at 9 15/16  
</P>
<P>
	The Cambridge, Mass.-based maker of chemical engineering  
software said it expects to post a significant loss for the third 
quarter. Analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. had predicted 
earnings of 18 cents a share for the quarter. The company said 
economic difficulties in the refining sector and a broad industry 
restructuring will result in lower-than-expected revenues. 

</P>
