<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 05:54:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Libyan Pair Will Go on Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Two years ago, Lamen Khalifa Fhimah squarely  
faced a television camera, pulled out the Muslim holy book, the 
Koran, and swore his innocence. 
</P>
<P>
	Fhimah, 42, will almost certainly renew that pious oath when he  
and co-accused Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi, 46, go on trial before 
a Scottish court in the Netherlands on charges of blowing up the 
Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	``I declare I was not part of the issue,'' Fhimah said in  
December 1996 during a rare public appearance he and al-Megrahi 
made on an Arabic television talk show. 
</P>
<P>
	Fhimah went on to say that his mother had died from the stress  
caused by the charges against him. 
</P>
<P>
	Al-Megrahi, a father of four, was equally emphatic in his  
denials. He told television viewers that when he learned of the 
charges against him, he hid it from his wife because she was ill at 
the time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We, my children and my family, are still suffering because of  
this,'' said al-Megrahi. 
</P>
<P>
	On Dec. 21, 1988, at Malta's Luqa airport, the two men allegedly  
planted a Samsonite hardback suitcase containing a bomb aboard an 
Air Malta flight to Frankfurt. The suitcase was routed as 
unaccompanied baggage from Frankfurt to London and onto the New 
York-bound Flight 103. 
</P>
<P>
	Nestled in the forward hold of the jetliner, it exploded over  
Scotland. A Scottish warrant says the bombing was the culmination 
of three years of plotting by al-Megrahi and Fhimah. All 259 
passengers and 11 people on the ground in Lockerbie were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. indictment says the two men built the bomb with plastic  
explosives supplied by the Libyan secret service, the Jamahirya 
Security Organization, which the United States accuses of 
international terrorism. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department says al-Megrahi is well-connected to the  
Libyan regime of Moammar Gadhafi and says he was head of security 
at Libyan Arab Airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Fhimah was manager of the Libya Arab Airlines office in Malta,  
and reportedly had access to Air Malta luggage tags. 
</P>
<P>
	In Malta, the explosives were allegedly kept at the Libyan  
airline office, a Libyan cultural center, and at Fhimah's home. 
</P>
<P>
	On Dec. 7, 1988, al-Megrahi traveled from Libya to Malta, where  
he purchased clothing the bomb was wrapped in, according to the 
indictment and the Scottish warrant. 
</P>
<P>
	Al-Megrahi returned to Libya but again went to Malta on or about  
Dec. 20, the indictment says. It says he returned to Libya on Dec. 
21 and hadn't left the country until being handed over for trial. 
</P>
<P>
	The special trial in the Netherlands by Scottish judges was part  
of a deal negotiated with Gadhafi in return for turning the men 
over. 
</P>
<P>
	Fhimah has acknowledged he worked for the Libyan Arab Airlines  
in Malta but says he left his job three months before the bombing 
and returned to Libya. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am neither an intelligence man nor a politician. I am simply  
a decent employee. Consequently, I want to defend myself and my 
reputation,'' he had said in a Radio Monte Carlo interview in 1991. 
``This is against my principles and the values with which I was 
raised and which do not permit me to kill an innocent soul.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
