<HEADLINE> Interest Rates Mixed in T-Bill Sale / T-Bills  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interest rates on short-term Treasury  
securities were mixed in Monday's auction as yields on three-month 
bills dipped to the lowest level since October. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury Department sold $6.5 billion in three-month bills  
at a discount rate of 4.265 percent, down from 4.380 percent last 
week. An additional $7.5 billion was sold in six-month bills at a 
rate of 4.345 percent, up slightly from 4.340 percent last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-month rate was the lowest since Oct. 26, when the  
bills sold for 4.070 percent. The six-month rate was the highest 
since March 22, when the rate was 4.420. 
</P>
<P>
	The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors  
-- 4.383 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling 
for $9,892.20 and 4.517 percent for a six-month bill selling for 
$9,780.30. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday the  
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index 
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 4.72 
percent last week from 4.75 percent the previous week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
