<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Hits Targets in Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO struck fuel depots, bridges and  
army barracks throughout Yugoslavia today, and said it was taking 
particular aim at Serbian ground forces accused of terrorizing 
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. President Clinton promised an 
``undiminished, unceasing and unrelenting'' air campaign, saying it 
would no longer be enough for Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic 
to just stop the killing. Milosevic defiantly promised to rebuild 
the bomb-damaged structures, denouncing NATO ``aggressors'' and 
``criminals.'' Serb media have been reporting some civilian 
casualties in the NATO raids. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Seeks Donations for Kosovo Aid  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Appealing directly to Americans to help the  
victims of Slobodan Milosevic's ``expulsion policy,'' President 
Clinton announced a toll-free 1-800 telephone number that people 
can call to donate money for ethnic Albanians expelled from Kosovo. 
The number -- 1-800-USAID-RELIEF -- was up and running this 
afternoon. He said the United States has put $150 million so far 
into humanitarian relief. The first shipments of 500,000 specially 
prepared meals for Kosovar refugees were en route to Italy, to be 
funneled into Albania. Another 600,000 meals were going to 
Macedonia, and tents, sleeping bags and blankets were being shipped 
to both countries from Travis Air Force Base in California and U.S. 
bases in Germany. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow, Nasdaq End at New Highs  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology issues led Wall Street to a new  
closing high today with the Dow industrials soaring 174.82 at 
10,007.33. The Dow's previous closing high was 10,006.78. On the 
NYSE, gainers led losers 1,689-1,321. The Nasdaq rose 58.55 to 
2,551.92, passing its previous high close of 2,510.09. IBM was up 
6 5/8 to 183 5/8, Hewlett-Packard rose 3 9/16 to 71 7/16 and Yahoo! shot 
up 39 5/16 to 219 1/16. America Online rose 16 15/16 to 166 15/16, 
but the company declined to comment on a published report that 
revived rumors that AOL was in talks to buy CBS. 

</P>
<P>
	Libya Delivers Pan Am Bomb Suspects  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands (AP) -- The United Nations suspended  
sanctions against Libya after Moammar Gadhafi surrendered two 
suspected Libyan intelligence agents for trial in the deadly 1988 
bombing of a Pan Am jet. The handover ended seven years of 
punishing sanctions against Libya and began what could be a lengthy 
trial process in the Netherlands. The two Libyans were being held 
tonight, awaiting arraignment under Scottish law on charges of 
planting the suitcase bomb that blew up Flight 103 over Lockerbie, 
Scotland, killing 270 people. 

</P>
<P>
	Guilty Plea in Gay Attack  
</P>
<P>
	LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- One of two young men charged in the slaying  
of gay college student Matthew Shepard pleaded guilty today and was 
sentenced to two consecutive life terms in prison. Russell 
Henderson, 21, pleaded guilty to felony murder and kidnapping, 
avoiding the possibility of the death penalty. Authorities said 
Henderson and Aaron McKinney, 21, posed as homosexuals and lured 
Shepard out of a bar last October, kidnapped and pistol-whipped him 
and left him tied to a fence. He died five days later. 

</P>
<P>
	China To Visit U.S for Trade Talks  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- On the eve of Premier Zhu Rongji's visit, U.S.  
and Chinese trade officials intensified efforts to strike a deal 
granting China its long-sought membership in the World Trade 
Organization. But the Clinton administration insisted any agreement 
would have to meet demands by U.S. manufacturers and farmers for 
access to China's huge market as a way of shrinking America's 
record $57 billion trade deficit with China. Some of the biggest 
sticking points include Chinese barriers to exports of American 
farm products, chemicals and operations by U.S. insurance 
companies. 

</P>
<P>
	Cancer Drug May Fight Heart Disease  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The experimental drug that caused a sensation when  
it was found to wipe out cancer in mice is also showing promise 
against heart disease. The same Harvard Medical School and 
Children's Hospital researchers who did the cancer study found that 
in mice, at least, the drug endostatin may also greatly slow the 
development of atherosclerosis, or hardening of the arteries. 
Endostatin has not been tested yet on people. 

</P>
<P>
	Giants Defeat Reds 11-8  
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Charlie Hayes hit a three-run homer in the  
eighth inning that provided the final turning point in today's wild 
San Francisco-Cincinnati opener that ended with an 11-8 Giants 
victory. The Reds overcame a four-run deficit with homers by Mike 
Cameron, Mark Sweeney and Sean Casey, pulling ahead 8-6 with a 
six-run sixth inning. But the Giants quieted the crowd of 55,112 
with a pair of homers -- by Ellis Burks and Hayes -- that pulled it 
out. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  

</P>
</TEXT>
