<DOCNO> APW19990405.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 08:45:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> High Court Decides for Prosecutors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prosecutors cannot be sued for having lawyers  
searched and interfering with their ability to advise a client 
appearing before a grand jury, the Supreme Court said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The court ruled unanimously that such action by California  
prosecutors in the Menendez brothers' murder case did not violate a 
lawyer's constitutional right to practice his profession. 
</P>
<P>
	The search of the lawyer was only a ``brief interruption,''  
Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist wrote for the court. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hold that the Fourteenth Amendment right to practice one's  
calling is not violated by the execution of a search warrant, 
whether calculated to annoy or even to prevent consultation with a 
grand jury witness,'' Rehnquist wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal appeals court had ruled that lawyer Paul L. Gabbert  
could sue two Los Angeles County prosecutors who handled the second 
murder trial of Lyle and Erik Menendez in the killings of their 
parents. 
</P>
<P>
	Gabbert represented Traci Baker, a defense witness in the  
brothers' first trial, in which two juries were unable to reach a 
verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors David Conn and Carol Najera believed that Baker, a  
former girlfriend of Lyle Menendez, had received a letter from him 
instructing her to testify falsely. Baker was served with a 
subpoena in March 1994 requiring her to testify before a grand jury 
and produce any letters from Lyle Menendez. 
</P>
<P>
	When Baker and Gabbert arrived at the courthouse, Conn got a  
warrant to search Gabbert. Because the lawyer was being searched 
while Baker was called to testify, he was not available to confer 
with her when she asked to speak to her lawyer outside the grand 
jury room. 
</P>
<P>
	Gabbert sued Conn and Najera, saying they violated his  
constitutional right to practice his profession. A federal judge 
ruled for the prosecutors based on qualified immunity. Qualified 
immunity protects government officials from civil rights lawsuits 
so long as they did not violate someone's clearly established 
rights. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated Gabbert's  
lawsuit, saying the prosecutors were not protected by qualified 
immunity. The prosecutors' actions were not reasonable because they 
were intended to keep Gabbert from consulting with Baker during her 
grand jury appearance, the appeals court said. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutors' appeal to the Supreme Court said they should  
not have to face lawsuits over an incident that did not harm the 
lawyer's overall ability to do his job. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the Supreme Court ruled for the prosecutors.  
</P>
<P>
	Rehnquist noted that grand jury witnesses have no constitutional  
right to have a lawyer present in the grand jury room, and added 
that the court need not decide whether there is a right to have a 
lawyer present outside the grand jury room for consultation. 
Gabbert is not entitled to raise that issue on his own, the chief 
justice said. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Conn vs. Gabbert, 97-1802.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0173 </DOCNO>
