<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shrinks Provide Service at Hotels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- You're in your room at a tony Nob Hill  
hotel, alone on a business trip. Maybe that big deal you flew 3,000 
miles for didn't go off just right. Feeling vulnerable? Confused? 
Depressed? Help can come as quickly as room service. 
</P>
<P>
	Meet Charmian Anderson, a soft-spoken psychologist who, for $2 a  
minute, will do her best to ease your worries and soothe your ego. 
</P>
<P>
	On-call hotel therapists are a dream come true for travelers who  
have never sought out counseling or Woody Allen types skittish 
about leaving behind the securities of home, Ms. Anderson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody knows, it's private. They can talk as long as they  
want,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, only two guests have taken the plunge. But Ms. Anderson  
is convinced her line of work will soon be as common as on-call 
hotel doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can just see that with the pace we live and the technology,  
it begs for this rapid response to serve people. All businesses are 
trying to respond with quality. Whether it's me or someone else, 
it's going to occur.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One client was a traveling investment banker who panicked when  
he learned he had only weeks to raise millions of dollars to save a 
failing company. Another hotel guest was forced to decide on the 
spot whether to take a job that would mean moving back in with her 
parents. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pressure was happening, it was there and they needed to  
deal with it right now,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Anderson has hung her shingle at the 20-room Nob Hill  
Lambourne, which tailors itself to the ``healthy executive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There are no bedtime chocolates here, but guests can loosen up  
with one of 14 on-call massage therapists, or help themselves to 
vitamin packs left on their pillows. Breakfast includes blue-green 
algae shakes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously there's a need'' for an on-call therapist to round  
out the psychological component, said Charlie Robles, the hotel's 
general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``So many people are traveling now. They're away from home or  
telecommuting. They don't have their mentor with them or even a 
boss to say, 'how do you handle this,' and that's what they're 
using her for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chekitan Dev, a marketing professor at Cornell's School of Hotel  
Administration, said on-call hotel therapy is ``an idea whose time 
has come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The business traveler, which is the major lifeblood of hotels  
in major cities, is probably more stressed out than any time in the 
past,'' Dev said. ``Their question is, 'What can you do for me that 
can make me feel better than when I arrived?' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Hotel founder Chip Conley got the idea to sign Ms. Anderson on  
after a guest requested a coach to help prepare for an interview 
and there was no one working there to do it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm still in need of therapy. I thought the rest of the world  
was too,'' Conley laughed. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea hasn't exactly taken off in the year since Ms.  
Anderson, who has a busy psychotherapy practice of her own, agreed 
to consult with the guests by phone or in their hotel rooms. The 
hotel changed her title from ``corporate psychologist'' to 
``corporate coach'' to minimize the stigma. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Ms. Anderson sees a need.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know the messes involved in traveling. I know what it's like  
to be in business and have pressures,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
