<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Zimmer Fights Injury To Coach Yanks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- The memory of a weekend tiff with owner  
George Steinbrenner already has started to fade. But nothing has 
been able to erase the debilitating pain New York Yankees interim 
manager Don Zimmer feels every day. 
</P>
<P>
	After more than five decades in baseball, Zimmer should be at  
home recovering from arthroscopic surgery on his right knee. 
Instead, he's managing the defending champions as they open their 
season at Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer is doing it only because of his friendship with Joe  
Torre, who turned the team over to his bench coach while recovering 
from prostate cancer surgery. Torre is not expected back until May 
or June. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it wasn't for Joe, I wouldn't have done it. I would've  
said, `Leave me as bench coach,''' Zimmer said. ``First of all, I 
wasn't capable of getting out of bed at the time. And I'm crippled 
over it now. I did it for Joe. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Joe went down, Joe wanted me to take the club,'' Zimmer  
added. ``So I'll do the best I can, and the players will do the 
best they can, until Joe gets back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pain in his leg is so bad Zimmer moves only with great  
effort. He uses a bat as a cane, yet still has trouble standing for 
long at the batting cage. Throughout spring training, he let coach 
Chris Chambliss bring the lineup card to home plate. 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer spent Monday afternoon at the team hotel ``with one leg  
up on two pillows -- that's really the only relief I get.'' Then he 
headed to the ballpark, knowing he'd be unable to go to the mound 
to remove a pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he'll leave that task to pitching coach Mel  
Stottlemyre. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm embarrassed of hobbling out in the middle of the baseball  
diamond,'' Zimmer said. ``And going out and arguing with an umpire, 
it's going to be rough. If something happens at second base, it may 
take me so long to get there I'll forget what it was about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer's stint as interim manager got a lot messier this past  
weekend when he got caught in the middle of Steinbrenner's battle 
with pitcher Hideki Irabu. It ended with the interim manager 
challenging the permanent owner to fire him. 
</P>
<P>
	The situation began last Thursday when Steinbrenner, infuriated  
that Irabu had failed to cover first base during a spring training 
game, called the pitcher a ``fat ... toad'' and decided to leave 
him behind when the team broke training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	But after Zimmer penciled in Ramiro Mendoza instead of Irabu for  
the start Wednesday at Oakland in the Yankees' third game of the 
season, Steinbrenner announced he was hoping Irabu would start that 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer shot back that he was the manager, and would not be told  
by anyone how to run the club on the field. When Irabu rejoined the 
club Sunday and apologized to the manager and teammates, Zimmer 
reiterated Mendoza would start Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Steinbrenner told The New York Times that he would  
abide by Zimmer's decision on Wednesday's starter. 
</P>
<P>
	``(It) is the call of the manager. Period. Exclamation. I've  
given him the players and it's his job from that point on, whether 
it's Torre or Zimmer,'' Steinbrenner said. 
</P>
<P>
	The owner then summed up the weekend misunderstanding with  
Zimmer by adding, ``I think in the heat of the moment, Zim just 
lost control. I chalk it up as zero.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With that crisis apparently calmed, Zimmer now can focus on the  
difficult task of playing caretaker to a team that -- even with 
five-time Cy Young Award winner Roger Clemens added to the roster -- 
will be hard pressed to match its record 125 wins of last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``The hardest thing to do in sports is to win when everyone  
expects you to,'' Zimmer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Probably nobody ever will improve on 125 wins and 50 losses.  
You'll probably never see it again. You read in the paper and you 
listen to somebody on a sports show and they say, `Well, the 
Yankees are a cinch.' But there's no such thing. We're all going in 
even on Monday. Hopefully, we can win an Eastern Division 
championship, but it won't be easy.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
