<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 15:45:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amazon.com, Wal-Mart Settle Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Amazon.com will reassign employees it lured away  
from Wal-Mart Stores and return computer system information to 
settle a lawsuit charging that the online bookseller tried to steal 
trade secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart sued last fall, alleging that Amazon.com hired its  
computer system managers and on-site consultants to learn more 
about the department store chain's information systems, which 
include data on sales, inventory and consumer buying habits. 
</P>
<P>
	That type of information would likely prove very useful to  
Amazon.com, which has been angling to become the Wal-Mart of the 
Internet through acquisitions that will expand the range of 
products it sells. 
</P>
<P>
	In the settlement filed Monday, Amazon.com agreed to reassign  
some of the former Wal-Mart employees to jobs that don't mirror the 
positions they held at Wal-Mart. Amazon.com also agreed to return 
information, brought over by former employees, related to 
Wal-Mart's database of customer and product information. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com already has returned ``thousands of Wal-Mart  
confidential documents,'' said Wal-Mart spokeswoman Betsy 
Reithemeyer. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no admission of wrongdoing by Amazon.com, which also  
agreed not to actively recruit any Wal-Mart employees for a year. 
</P>
<P>
	No damages are to be paid.  
</P>
<P>
	Amazom.com, which maintains it didn't steal trade secrets,  
settled the case to avoid costly and prolonged litigation, 
spokesman Bill Curry said. 
</P>
<P>
	While Wal-Mart, the nation's largest retailer, doesn't sell a  
lot of products online, it views Amazon.com as a threat to its book 
sales at stores. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the suggestion that Amazon.com is gunning to become  
Wal-Mart's online equivalent may not have gone over so well, said 
Tim Bajarin, president of Creative Strategies Research 
International, a consulting firm based in San Jose, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wal-Mart hasn't spelled out their strategy,'' Bajarin said,  
``but it's very clear if someone is going to be a Wal-Mart of 
cyberspace, they wanted to be it. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides tracking raw sales, profit margin and inventory data,  
Wal-Mart's system also documents what products consumers tend to 
buy together. 
</P>
<P>
	A database that extensive could help Amazon.com know which  
products and services would be most attractive to different 
customers, facilitating the online retailer's plan to expand into 
other areas. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 18:11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Blasts Yugoslav Targets  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Keeping up airstrikes, NATO blasted  
fuel depots, bridges and army barracks throughout Yugoslavia today. 
Allied air power also struck at Serb ground forces accused of 
pushing ethnic Albanians out of Kosovo. Conditions remained dire at 
a makeshift refugee camp at Blace, Macedonia, on the border with 
Kosovo, where thousands were living in shelters of plastic and 
blankets. NATO said relief flights carrying 200 tons of food and 
other emergency supplies were on the way. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Reaffirms Kosovo Stance  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today said NATO's military  
campaign against Yugoslavia will be ``unceasing and unrelenting'' 
until President Slobodan Milosevic backs down on Kosovo. ``Our plan 
is to persist until we prevail,'' Clinton said. Defense Secretary 
William Cohen said U.S. Army Apache attack helicopters would target 
Serb military and police forces that are now ``open and 
vulnerable'' in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Libya Turns Over Pan Am Suspects  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands (AP) -- The United Nations suspended  
sanctions against Libya today after Moammar Gadhafi surrendered two 
suspected Libyan intelligence agents for trial in the lethal 1988 
bombing of a Pan Am jet. The handover began what could be a lengthy 
trial process in the Netherlands. ``Now, at last, the road to 
justice has begun,'' President Clinton said in a statement. The two 
Libyans were being held at this former U.S. airbase, awaiting 
arraignment under Scottish law on charges of planting the suitcase 
bomb that blew up Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, killing 270 
people, including 189 Americans. 

</P>
<P>
	'Junior' Gotti Pleads Guilty  
</P>
<P>
	WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- John A. ``Junior'' Gotti, the son and  
alleged successor of America's best-known Mafioso, pleaded guilty 
today to racketeering, bribery, extortion and other charges in 
exchange for a prison term of up to seven years. The plea was 
entered the day before jury selection was to begin in his federal 
trial. If convicted, he could have been sentenced to 20 years in 
prison and fined millions of dollars. Gotti was charged with taking 
part in a criminal enterprise known as the Gambino family, and 
extortion, robbery, loansharking, gambling and bribery. 

</P>
<P>
	Gay Attack Sentence Is Life  
</P>
<P>
	LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- One of two men charged in the killing of  
Matthew Shepard pleaded guilty to murder, admitting he tied the gay 
college student to a fence and left him for dead. Russell Henderson 
avoided a possible death sentence with his plea. He was sentenced 
to two consecutive life terms. Authorities said Henderson and Aaron 
McKinney posed as homosexuals and lured Shepard out of a bar last 
October, kidnapped and pistol-whipped him and left him tied to a 
fence. 

</P>
<P>
	Court OKs Searches of Car Passengers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Passengers' personal belongings are fair game  
when police officers search a car for criminal evidence against the 
driver, the Supreme Court ruled. The 6-3 decision reinstated a 
Wyoming drug conviction and expanded the already considerable 
police power to stop and search vehicles without a court warrant. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow, Nasdaq End at New Highs  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology issues led Wall Street to a new  
closing high today with the Dow industrials soaring 174.82 to end 
at 10,007.33. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 1,689-1,321. The 
Nasdaq rose 58.55 to 2,551.92, passing its previous high close of 
2,510.09. 

</P>
<P>
	High Tech Execs Back Bush  
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Fifty-five executives with ties to the  
high-tech world urged Texas Gov. George W. Bush to run for 
president, saying they liked his views on education, litigation and 
regulation. ``We need visionary leaders who understand the New 
Economy,'' the executives wrote in an advertisement they placed in 
today's editions of the San Jose Mercury News' business section. 
Among the Bush backers are Jim Barksdale, president and CEO of 
Netscape; Bob Herbold, chief operating officer of Microsoft; Jeff 
Henley, chief financial officer of Oracle; and Steve Behm, a vice 
president of Cisco Systems. 

</P>
<P>
	Red Sox Beat Royals 5-3  
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Jose Offerman, signed from Kansas City  
to replace Mo Vaughn's bat, went 4-for-5 and John Valentin homered 
today to lead the Red Sox over the Kansas City Royals 5-3 on 
opening day. Pedro Martinez struck out nine in six innings as 
Boston won its opener for the sixth time in seven years. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  

</P>
</TEXT>
