<DOCNO> APW19990405.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 12:05:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Business Sentiment Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese businesses grew slightly more confident  
about the country's economy during the first quarter, but they were 
still far from optimistic about the future, according to a survey 
released by Japan's central bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan said Monday business sentiment at major  
manufacturers improved slightly during the past three months, 
rising to minus 47 in March from December's minus 49, the lowest 
figure since February 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The report suggested Japan's massive economic stimulus measures  
-- including tax cuts and increased government spending -- have begun 
to break its economic slide. But analysts said the improvement has 
not come as quickly as many had hoped. 
</P>
<P>
	``This shows that the government isn't getting too much bang for  
its yen,'' said Andrew Shipley, economist at Schroders Securities 
in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The improvement in business sentiment was the first since June  
1997. The index measures the percentage of firms seeing business 
conditions improve minus the percentage seeing conditions worsen. 
The central bank began conducting what's known as the ``tankan'' 
survey in 1967. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturers predicted their outlook would improve further by  
the time of the next survey. 
</P>
<P>
	But there were still plenty of signs that Japan economy has a  
long way to go in its recovery from its worst recession since World 
War II. Big companies surveyed forecast their capital spending 
would decline by 9.4 percent this fiscal year -- worse than their 
projections of a 5.4 percent drop for the last fiscal year, which 
ended March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	``A full-fledged recovery has yet to start,'' Koji Tanami,  
Japan's top Finance Ministry official said at a press conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although the tankan showed some bright results such how people  
feel about future business conditions and the forecast for 
corporate profits, it indicated that capital investment has not 
emerged yet,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The tankan report was followed by other economic data that  
showed Japan's economy remains bogged down. 
</P>
<P>
	Average household spending tumbled 3.8 percent in December,  
further dimming hopes for an upswing in consumption, Japan's 
Management and Coordination Agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the country's Economic Planning Agency said that the  
February index of leading indicators of the economy stood at 42.9, 
below the boom-or-bust threshold of 50.0 for the second straight 
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
