<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 14:55:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rep. Urges China Donation Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Linking alleged Democratic campaign  
fund-raising abuses with a visit to Washington by China's premier, 
a member of Congress who has investigated the charges is pressing 
President Clinton to demand answers about possible Chinese 
influence on U.S. elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional investigators and the Justice Department should be  
allowed into China to interview principal witnesses, Rep. Dan 
Burton wrote Clinton on Monday. The president plays host this week 
to Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji. 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Times reported during the weekend that  
cooperating witness Johnny Chung has told Justice Department 
investigators that China's chief military intelligence officer 
ordered that $300,000 be directed to Chung for political 
contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	Burton, R-Ind., chairs the House Government Reform and Oversight  
Committee, which has been investigating foreign donations in the 
1996 presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I ... urge you to insist that China provide U.S. investigators  
... with bank records ... that would demonstrate the origins of the 
millions of dollars that flowed'' from China to the Democratic 
Party and the Clinton-Gore campaign, Burton wrote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 14:25:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Wants To Host Davis Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Tennis Australia will appeal to the  
International Tennis Federation in a bid to get Australia's Davis 
Cup quarterfinal against the United States switched to Melbourne. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Davis Cup rules, Australia would serve as the host of the  
match as the last game between the nations was in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the ITF decided two years ago to celebrate the 100th  
anniversary of the Davis Cup by ensuring a U.S. match would be 
played in Boston, the city where the Cup was born. 
</P>
<P>
	Scheduled for July 16-18, the tie will feature the two most  
successful countries in Cup history and commemorate the first Cup 
match between the United States and Britain in 1900, a 3-0 U.S. 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennis Australia president Geoff Pollard said the appeal would  
be based on the fact that the United States played host to the last 
match in Washington in September 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``Secondly, I believe Australia can stage a better celebration  
in Melbourne Park with a capacity crowd of 15,000 in the world's 
best tennis venue as opposed to a match in Boston with a crowd of 
5,000,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Based on our record, Australia has as much right to  
commemorate the centenary as the USA and therefore will appeal to 
the ITF to maintain normal home-and-away rights that have been 
integral to the competition throughout its 100-year history.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
