<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Twins Guarantee Win in Jays Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Mark it down. The Minnesota Twins will beat  
the Toronto Blue Jays in their season opener. In fact, they've 
guaranteed it. 
</P>
<P>
	Undaunted by a bargain-basement roster that includes 10 rookies,  
the Twins have come up with a gutsy marketing plan that 
``guarantees'' a win each Tuesday night this season. 
</P>
<P>
	If the players don't come through, each fan's ticket stub is  
worth a free seat to a future home game any day except Fridays and 
Saturdays. 
</P>
<P>
	Considering the Twins' inexperience, that could make the opener  
a 2-for-1 night for the more than 40,000 fans expected Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Which guy in the front office is playing tomorrow night,'' Ron  
Coomer quipped Monday as he dressed for the Twins' last preseason 
workout. ``They've got to do whatever they've got to do to sell 
tickets. That's fine by me. I don't care what they do. Our job is 
down on the field. We help out as much as we can to do what they 
need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It would help the marketing strategy considerably to beat Pat  
Hentgen on Tuesday and David Wells on Wednesday. But that's a tough 
draw for Minnesota's kiddie corps. 
</P>
<P>
	Hentgen, the 1996 AL Cy Young winner and a 15-game winner in  
1997, slumped to 12-11 with a 5.17 ERA last season. He's looking to 
make Tuesday the start of a more Hentgen-esque season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any time you get opening day it's a great honor,'' said  
Hentgen, 82-53 with a 3.88 ERA in six seasons. ``Considering our 
staff right now, I think on paper we've got one of the better ones 
in the AL.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Especially if Wells keeps rolling.  
</P>
<P>
	The burly, bawdy lefty pitched a perfect game against the Twins  
at Yankee Stadium last season and led New York to the World Series 
title. He was bothered by a sore back shortly after the trade that 
sent Roger Clemens to the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Wells, who will face rookie Mike Lincoln on Wednesday night,  
doesn't like the idea of facing so many young guys to start the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Usually when you first come up and you go against a good team,  
you usually come out on top,'' Wells said. ``But not me. I lost. I 
lost to the Yankees in 1987 and `The Gator' (Ron Guidry). I just 
hope Lincoln's off Wednesday and we kick some butt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lincoln is one of seven Twins who spent all or most of last  
season at Double-A New Britain. He led the Rock Cats in wins (15) 
and innings (173 1-3), and his 3.22 ERA was the lowest among the 
team's starters. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rock Cats had an outstanding season, finishing 83-59, and  
the players hope that success and their familiarity with one 
another will help them make the leap to the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know the feeling of winning and losing together. We know  
what one guy can do and what he can't do,'' said Torii Hunter, who 
spent six games with the Twins last season and outplayed Jacque 
Jones and Chris Latham to win the center-field job. ``It's not like 
this team is just made up of players from another organization. We 
grew up together, so we should be able to play together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday night's crowd should be close to the 43,848 who saw the  
'98 opener, the largest crowd for an opener in Minnesota since 
1993. Season ticket sales also are expected to top last year's 
6,043 by about 1,000, thanks mostly to a $99 special. 
</P>
<P>
	The fans seem at least mildly interested in the fresh start  
created by this year's cost cutting. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want to be in the minor leagues,'' Hunter said.  
``We're hungry. We want to stay here. So gives us a chance. We'll 
give you 100 percent. Nothing less.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
