<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Subway Pusher Fit for Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A man who has said ghosts inhabit and control  
his body is mentally fit to stand trial on charges he killed a 
woman by pushing her in front of a subway train, a judge ruled 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Carol Berkman ruled that Andrew Goldstein, 29, can  
understand the charges and court proceedings and help his lawyer 
present a defense. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said the state's standard for finding a person  
mentally fit is ``not particularly high,'' and Goldstein, who has a 
10-year history of mental illness, is ``not so impaired that he 
cannot participate in his trial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goldstein is charged with second-degree murder in the death of  
Kendra Webdale, 32. Goldstein told police and psychiatrists that 
voices told him to shove Ms. Webdale and that an irresistible 
``ghost'' or ``spirit'' took control of his body just before the 
push. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
