<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Mostly Lower / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly  
lower early today on the Chicago Board of Trade as prospects for 
increased world supplies continued to weigh on prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans were pressured by expectations for record U.S. spring  
plantings and the beginning of harvesting bumper competing crops in 
Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and wheat fell amid beneficial rainfall in the Midwest,  
that should aid spring planting and excellent crop conditions in 
winter wheat regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 3/4 cent to $2.87 a bushel; May corn  
fell 1 3/4 cents to $2.20 1/4 a bushel; May oats fell 1 3/4 cents to $1.12 3/4 
a bushel; and May soybeans fell 1 3/4 cents to $4.81 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and pork bellies futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while lean hogs were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .70 cent to 65.15 cents a pound; May  
feeder cattle rose .70 cent to 73.60 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
rose .05 cent to 53 cents a pound; July pork rose .10 cent to 51.80 
cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
