<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 08:25:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> High Court To Review Death Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to review the  
death sentence of a convicted Virginia killer whose scheduled 
Tuesday execution it postponed last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices said they will decide whether death row inmate  
Terry Williams should get a federal court hearing on his claims 
that he was denied adequate legal help during his sentencing trial. 
</P>
<P>
	A decision is not expected until sometime next year, so today's  
brief order postponed Williams' execution indefinitely. If the 
court eventually rules against Williams, however, Virginia 
authorities would be free to set a new execution date. 
</P>
<P>
	The court on Friday had ordered Williams' execution postponed  
until it could consider his appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the issues the justices are to study is whether Williams  
should be required to prove that he would have received a life 
prison term instead of a death sentence if he had had an effective 
lawyer at the sentencing trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, 43, has been on death row for more than 13 years --  
longer than any of the 40 Virginia prisoners currently housed 
there. He was sentenced to death for the robbery and murder of a 
Danville man in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Williams vs. Taylor, 98-8384.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 14:59:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers' Lindros Still in Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Doctors won't know until midweek when  
hospitalized Flyers captain Eric Lindros can return to 
Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	And it will take several more days to determine if his collapsed  
lung mends fast enough to let him skate in the playoffs that start 
in less than three weeks, Flyers team physician Dr. Gary Dorshimer 
said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorshimer said those answers depend on what happens after  
doctors at Nashville's Baptist Hospital discontinue the suction in 
a tube in Lindros' chest to determine if the lung can remain 
inflated without the assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	Still in pain from the injury, Lindros had hoped to return for  
the playoffs, refusing to ``rule anything out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though there was speculation Lindros was injured when hit during  
the Flyers' 2-1 win Thursday night at Nashville, he said he felt 
pain but didn't think it was serious. ``I went out and had a 
cheeseburger and fries,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Later Thursday and early Friday, Dorshimer said Lindros  
experienced ``a progressive feeling of weakness, tiredness and 
shortness of breath and then eventually lightheadedness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the lightheadedness, a Flyers spokesman disputed a USA  
Today report Monday that Lindros had collapsed in his Nashville 
hotel room. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it is a matter of semantics. I don't think he  
collapsed, but he was taken by ambulance'' to the hospital, team 
spokesman Joe Klueg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros felt chest pains Friday. Roommate Keith Jones told The  
Philadelphia Inquirer that Lindros was ``a hurtin' pup'' by the 
time Jones called Flyers trainer John Worley, who called the 
ambulance. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorshimer said Lindros did not appear to have a broken rib or  
punctured lung, but apparently broke a blood vessel. Blood seeping 
into his chest cavity caused his right lung to collapse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 05:35:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Libyan Suspects Handed Over  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Libya handed over two suspects today for  
trial in the 1988 Pan Am airliner bombing that killed 270 people. 
Lamen Khalifa Fhimah and Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi are to be 
tried under Scottish law in the Netherlands. The move is expected 
to lead to the withdrawal of sanctions against Libya that barred 
international air travel to and from the North African nation. Most 
of the passengers aboard Pan Am Flight 103 were American and 
British, and the United States had insisted for a decade that the 
men be tried in the United States or Britain. It dropped the demand 
last August. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Forces Blast Serb Targets  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO airstrikes hit Serb targets  
today that reportedly included an air force building, army barracks 
and the capital's airport in the 13th day of bombing against 
Yugoslavia. The latest attacks also took out a bridge and both ends 
of a railway tunnel in an area where Serb tanks and troops are 
believed to be on the move. The attacks signal an escalation of 
firepower to halt Serb attacks on Kosovo's Albanian majority. 

</P>
<P>
	US Sends Helicopters to Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- NATO leaders will meet later today to discuss  
how to use Apache attack helicopters the United States is sending 
to Kosovo. The choppers will be used to launch direct attacks 
against Serb troops and tanks. The helicopters would be based in 
Albania. The United States also plans to send 18 multiple rocket 
launchers and 2,000 soldiers to protect the weapons and their 
crews. While foggy and rainy weather has hampered NATO air strikes, 
the Apaches fly in all weather conditions. A Pentagon spokesman 
says it would take up to 10 days to deploy the Apaches from their 
base in Germany. 

</P>
<P>
	China Detains Dissident  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China has banned a prominent dissident from  
returning home to visit the grave of his late father. Wang Xizhe is 
renowned in China's dissident circles, with 25 years of activism. 
He was stopped from boarding a South Korean airlines jet. Wang's 
attempt to go to Beijing was seen as a test of a blacklist of 
exiled activists. In protest, Wang unfurled a sign. ``The right to 
return home cannot be taken away!'' it read in Chinese, according 
to exiled dissidents who spoke with Wang. 

</P>
<P>
	Va. Workers Strike Newport News  
</P>
<P>
	NEWPORT NEWS, Va. (AP) -- Thousands of workers at the Navy's only  
source of nuclear-powered aircraft carriers are on strike for the 
first time in 20 years. The president of the shipyard's United 
Steelworkers of America local says workers want higher wages than 
the company is offering. The shipyard builds all the Navy's 
Nimitz-class nuclear-powered aircraft carriers, and is currently is 
building the aircraft carrier Ronald Reagan and is repairing the 
carriers USS Nimitz and the USS Harry S. Truman. 

</P>
<P>
	Report Says US, NKorea Talked Nukes  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- U.S. officials visited North Korea  
last week to discuss a planned inspection of a suspected nuclear 
weapons site in the communist country, the North's media reported 
today. North Korea's foreign news outlet, KCNA, said technical 
experts of both countries met in the capital, Pyongyang, from 
Wednesday through Saturday to discuss ``technical matters.'' The 
discussions included ``details and method of the on-site visit to 
the facility in Kumchang-ri'' in May and equipment the U.S. 
inspectors will be allowed to carry, KCNA said. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock Prices Close Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose today after the central bank  
announced a rise in corporate sentiment, but sharp early gains were 
wiped out by profit-taking. The Nikkei gained 44.59 points to close 
at 16,334.78. 

</P>
<P>
	Rockies 8, Padres 2  
</P>
<P>
	MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) -- Mexican native Vinny Castilla had four  
hits to lead the Colorado Rockies to an 8-2 victory over the San 
Diego Padres last night in the first baseball opener played outside 
the United States and Canada. Dante Bichette also had four hits 
with a homer and four RBIs, helping Jim Leyland win his debut as 
Rockies manager. Padres ace Andy Ashby was pounded for six runs in 
one-plus innings. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
