<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Protests Held at Gay Death Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- Young people dressed as angels stood  
silently today outside the courthouse where one of the man accused 
of killing a gay student is on trial, trying to block from view a 
group of anti-gay demonstrators. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside the ring of a dozen angels organized by friends of slain  
university student Matthew Shepard, about a dozen anti-gay 
demonstrators from Kansas shouted slogans and waved signs, 
including one that said ``God Hates Fags.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``These ... creatures are sending this nation to hell in a  
handbasket,'' said the Rev. Fred Phelps of Westboro Baptist Church 
in Topeka, Kan. 
</P>
<P>
	Phelps and members of his church picketed Shepard's funeral in  
Casper with anti-gay signs. They also demonstrated at a vigil in 
Alabama for Billy Jack Gaither, who may have been murdered because 
he was gay. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside the courthouse, jury selection for the trial of Russell  
Henderson was delayed until Tuesday because of an afternoon hearing 
today. Opening arguments were slated for Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Henderson, 21, is charged with first-degree murder, kidnapping  
and aggravated robbery in the attack on Shepard, a University of 
Wyoming student who was found barely alive, bloodied and tied to a 
fence Oct. 7. Shepard died five days later. 
</P>
<P>
	The subject of the hearing was not disclosed.  
</P>
<P>
	It could be for any of a number of issues, including a plea  
bargain, questions about jury selection, or a request for a new 
attorney for Henderson, said Jason Tangeman, attorney for 
codefendant Aaron McKinney. 
</P>
<P>
	A handful of police officers formed a buffer zone between the  
two groups of demonstrators. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could no longer sit idly by and watch others bring forth  
messages that were nothing more than vindictive and hate-filled,'' 
said Romaine Patterson, 21, a friend of Shepard's who organized the 
angels' counterdemonstration. ``As a young person, I feel it is 
necessary to show the great nation that we live in that there 
doesn't need to be this kind of violence and hatred in our world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McKinney, 21, faces an August trial in Shepard's killing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
