<DOCNO> APW19990405.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 15:55:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Padres To Hoist NL Pennant Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- After getting their international duties -- and  
first loss -- out of the way, the San Diego Padres have one more day 
of hoopla before getting on with their season of change. 
</P>
<P>
	With a crowd of more than 60,000 expected, the Padres will raise  
the 1998 NL pennant at Qualcomm Stadium and the players will 
receive their league championship rings before their home opener 
Tuesday afternoon against the Colorado Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	``It should be neat,'' general manager Kevin Towers said. ``You  
don't get that opportunity that often, to put a National League 
championship ring on your finger. It will certainly bring back some 
fond memories, once you get back to Qualcomm and see the sellout 
crowd, and get the music going again, it's going to get the 
adrenaline flying once again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was at Qualcomm Stadium where the best season in club history  
ended with losses in Games 3 and 4 of the World Series to the New 
York Yankees. Gone from that Padres team are Kevin Brown, Greg 
Vaughn, Ken Caminiti, Steve Finley and Joey Hamilton. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego's most famous offseason acquisition was country singer  
Garth Brooks, who attended spring training as a non-roster player 
in part to help jump-start his baseball-related Touch 'Em All 
Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	The singing cowboy's gone his separate way, and now it's the  
Padres who could use a kick-start after their anemic showing in an 
8-2 loss to the Rockies on Sunday night in Monterrey, Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Padres, including batting star Tony Gwynn, weren't thrilled  
at having to make a 2,000-mile round trip to play the opener as the 
``home'' team. 
</P>
<P>
	``You only have one opener,'' Gwynn said before Sunday's game.  
``In our case we were supposed to open at home. That's what you're 
supposed to do, you're supposed to raise the flag, get your rings, 
kind of celebrate what happened here last year, the start of 
something new this year. We've got to do it on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand baseball going global. I understand planting our  
flag in new places, but our flag's already planted here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Padres and Rockies were invited to move the game to  
Monterrey by major league baseball, which billed it as the 
International Opener. The Padres were picked in part because 
they're the defending NL champions and because they moved a series 
to Monterrey in 1996, and one to Honolulu in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	But they were hardly ambassadors of good baseball Sunday night,  
allowing 18 hits while collecting just six themselves, including 
Gwynn's RBI single that left him 71 short of 3,000 hits. Andy 
Ashby, who moved up to ace after Brown signed his $105 million 
contract with Los Angeles, was knocked out after failing to get an 
out in the five-run second. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't give us a chance to win,'' Ashby said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Rockies had a great time, as Dante Bichette went 4-for-5  
with four RBIs and a homer, and Mexican hero Vinny Castilla also 
went 4-for-5. Their ace, Darryl Kile, got off to a good start after 
a miserable 1998, helping make Jim Leyland a winner in his debut as 
Colorado's manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Padres left-hander Sterling Hitchcock, MVP of the NL  
championship series win over Atlanta, will start Tuesday for the 
Padres. 
</P>
<P>
	Hitchcock wouldn't discuss his assignment. ``I don't talk before  
I pitch,'' he said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hitchcock started last year in the bullpen because the Padres  
didn't have a healthy lefty there, and now he's the No. 2 starter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rockies will start Pedro Astacio, who is 6-1 with a 2.55 ERA  
in 15 career games against San Diego. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
