<DOCNO> APW19990405.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 13:35:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Finds Stainless Steel Is Dumped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration moved a step closer  
to slapping punitive tariffs on Japan, Spain and four other 
countries Monday with a ruling that they illegally price some 
stainless steel in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Shipments of stainless round wire from those countries would be  
subject to tariffs of as much as 36 percent if an independent 
fact-finding agency determines that their pricing practices have 
injured or could injure U.S. producers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department ruling represents the latest in a string  
of victories for the U.S. steel industry, which has yet to lose a 
key ruling in trade complaints filed to combat low-priced imports. 
</P>
<P>
	Those successes paradoxically have made it more difficult for  
domestic producers to put foreign steel products under quotas or 
stronger sanctions to fend off imports blamed for thousands of 
layoffs and bankruptcies at three U.S. companies. Administration 
officials cite the favorable rulings as evidence the normal 
administrative process works. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten U.S. manufacturers sought tariffs a year ago, accusing  
Canada, India, Japan, South Korea, Spain and Taiwan of dumping 
round wire in the U.S. market at prices below production costs or 
home-market prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Stainless steel round wire, used to produce springs, wire rope  
and fasteners in construction and other applications, represents a 
small portion of the overall steel industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, Monday's dumping determination by the Commerce  
Department adds to relief the U.S. steel industry could get in 
response to the import surge. 
</P>
<P>
	A crucial decision covering the most common steel product,  
hot-rolled carbon steel, is due this month. The Commerce Department 
already has found evidence of dumping by Japan, Russia and Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan and Brazil face steel tariffs in the hot-rolled case,  
while Russia has agreed to curb exports instead of similar tariffs. 
A U.S. comment period for implementing the Russian agreement closed 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. International Trade Commission is to rule by mid-May on  
whether round wire dumping has or could hurt the U.S. industry. 
That's the last step before tariffs are imposed. 
</P>
<P>
	Tariffs proposed by the Commerce Department ranged from 3  
percent for stainless round wire from South Korea to 36 percent for 
the product from Spain's main producer. Japanese round wire could 
be subject to tariffs of up to 30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Stainless steel round wire is a $300 million-a-year domestic  
industry, and imports add another $100 million, industry officials 
said. Shipments from the six countries under Commerce Department 
scrutiny account for one-third of all imports. 
</P>
<P>
	The government already has imposed tariffs on stainless wire  
rod, the precursor to round wire, and has found six countries 
guilty of dumping stainless plates in coils, which could lead to 
more tariffs if injury is proven. Other complaints are pending. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases acted on Monday were filed by ACS Industries Inc. of  
Woonsocket, R.I.; Al Tech Specialty Steel Corp. of Dunkirk, N.Y.; 
Branford Wire &AMP; Manufacturing Co. of Mountain Home, N.C.; Carpenter 
Technology Corp. of Reading, Pa.; Handy &AMP; Herman Specialty Wire 
Group of Cockeysville, Md; Industrial Alloys Inc. of Pomona, Calif; 
Loos &AMP; Co. Inc. of Pomfret, Conn.; Sandvik Steel Co. of Clarks 
Summit, Pa.; Sumiden Wire Products Corp. of Stockton, Calif.; and 
Techalloy Co. Inc. of Mahwah, N.J. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 14:25:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  White House Holds Easter Egg Roll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Alexander Hamilton was eager to compete in the  
Easter egg roll at the White House. When the whistle blew, the 
3-year-old inched his egg forward with a plastic spoon. Then he 
froze in his tracks and frowned. 
</P>
<P>
	Adult-sized bunnies scampering across the South Lawn, noisy  
children rolling eggs, dads with cameras, the Marine Band -- it was 
all too overwhelming for the tyke from Round Hill, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like that game,'' said Alexander, who stood at that  
moment closer to the White House than his famous namesake ever did. 
</P>
<P>
	Young Alexander defiantly crossed hs arms and refused to budge  
his egg. His mother, Nora Hamilton, finished the job. 
</P>
<P>
	``Come on,'' she whispered. ``Let's see what the bunnies look  
like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dads pushing strollers, moms wearing fuzzy pink bunny ears and  
children toting Easter baskets showed up Monday at the White House 
for the annual Easter egg roll. Standing on a stage decorated with 
brightly colored tulips, President Clinton and first lady Hillary 
Rodham Clinton greeted the crowd of an estimated 30,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The president urged families to pray for troops and refugees  
involved in the Balkan crisis. He also thanked volunteers and the 
White House staff for dyeing 7,200 eggs for the event. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's more than we ask them to prepare for a state dinner,''  
joked Clinton, who wore a navy tie decorated with Easter eggs. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, with children poised at starting lines, the president  
shouted ``On your mark, ready, set go!'' 
</P>
<P>
	The egg roll has been an American tradition since the mid-19th  
century. The celebration took place on the Capitol grounds until 
1878, when it was moved to the White House by Lucy Hayes, wife of 
President Rutherford B. Hayes. 
</P>
<P>
	Drizzle and a chilly breeze dampened the start of this year's  
event, but by noon, the sun had poked through and skies were a 
picture-perfect blue. 
</P>
<P>
	Cameras and camcorders were everywhere. Children were  
photographed in front of the White House, stuffing their mouths 
with candy, dancing to music, rolling in the green grass and 
listening to stories, including one read by actress Jamie Lee 
Curtis. They also posed for snapshots with a bunny wearing a purple 
pinafore and with actors dressed up like Presidents George 
Washington and Teddy Roosevelt. 
</P>
<P>
	Billy Muran, 6, of Brookville, N.Y., rolled his egg to the  
finish line with ease before stirring up some mischief. He took his 
spoon and pummeled his purplish-colored egg into the damp grass. 
</P>
<P>
	Jay Duff, 5, of Richmond, Va. didn't roll his egg. He rested it  
in his plastic spoon and slid the spoon across the grass. That 
wasn't the idea, but he got applause for his innovative approach. 
</P>
<P>
	Taron Stiney, 6, of Washington, D.C., wielded his spoon like a  
golf club. A couple of chip shots later and his pink egg rolled 
across the finish line. Busy trying to break open a plastic egg 
filled with a candy prize, Taron had little interest in discussing 
the finer points of his egg-rolling technique. 
</P>
<P>
	``He loves Easter,'' said his mother, Zaraider Stiney. ``What  
kid doesn't?'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 08:15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ameritech Sells Cellular Units </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Ameritech Corp. is selling its cellular business  
in three states to GTE Corp. for $3.27 billion to help satisfy 
federal stipulations for Ameritech's merger with SBC 
Communications. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale of the businesses in the Chicago and St. Louis areas  
and northwestern Indiana is contingent upon regulatory approval of 
the SBC deal, Ameritech said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department recently gave the green light to that  
deal with the condition that the two Baby Bells sell off wireless 
properties in areas where they have overlapping operations that 
would dominate the market. 
</P>
<P>
	But last week, the government's top telecommunications regulator  
said he has ``serious concerns'' about the deal, which would create 
the nation's largest local phone company. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Communications Commission Chairman Bill Kennard sent  
letters to SBC and Ameritech on Thursday asking to hold talks this 
month to explore ``whether it would be possible to craft 
conditions'' addressing his concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	The properties being sold to GTE will be operated by Georgetown  
Partners, a minority-owned firm that will own a 7 percent stake in 
the businesses being sold. 
</P>
<P>
	``This sale demonstrates that the SBC-Ameritech merger will  
bring substantial new competition into the Midwest (and) broaden 
the ownership of these properties to include greater diversity from 
the community,'' Ameritech chief executive Richard Notebaert said. 
</P>
<P>
	GTE said the acquisitions would make it the largest cellular  
service provider in the United States in terms of subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	Combined with a pending purchase from Bell Atlantic, the  
purchase would give GTE 13 million cellular customers and a 
presence in two-thirds of the largest U.S. markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``These properties will both enhance our ability to bundle  
products and services in areas where we also offer local phone 
service and facilitate expansion into the local phone markets in 
key Midwest cities such as Chicago and St. Louis,'' GTE Chairman 
Charles Lee said. 
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio-based SBC and Chicago-based Ameritech announced  
plans to merge last May. The proposed stock deal, now worth more 
than $60 billion, has the approval of shareholders from both 
companies and several major unions. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal also must be cleared by the Illinois Commerce  
Commission and the Public Utilities Commission of Ohio. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 14:25:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  White House Holds Easter Egg Roll </HEADLINE>
