<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Journalist Gary Blonston Dies at 56 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gary Blonston, chief of the Knight Ridder  
Washington bureau whose journalism career spanned more than three 
decades, died Sunday at his home of cancer. He was 56. 
</P>
<P>
	Blonston served as reporter, editor and writing coach in his  
nearly 36 years in the field. He worked at The Miami Herald, the 
Detroit Free Press and the San Jose Mercury News before coming to 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Jonathan Wolman, former Washington bureau chief of The  
Associated Press and now the AP's managing editor, said of 
Blonston: ``He ran one of the best bureaus in town, constantly 
juggling between hard news coverage and the sort of perspective 
pieces that newspapers need from Washington. He had a refined sense 
of irony, just what you need to make sense of it all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blonston was a principal writer on two Pulitzer Prize-winning  
projects. One was during his time at the Free Press, where he came 
under gunfire while covering Detroit's 1967 riots. Blonston also 
worked on the Mercury News' reporting of the 1989 Loma Prieta 
earthquake in the San Francisco Bay area. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1968, Blonston found himself in the middle of rioting  
protesters and police officers outside the Democratic National 
Convention. Coughing from tear gas, he dictated his story to an 
editor on deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Blonston also freelanced for newspapers and magazines, on topics  
ranging from politics to prehistoric art. During a 1967 strike at 
the Free Press -- when Blonston was working at Chrysler Corp. -- he 
wrote a book on the history of the Plymouth. In 1996, he published 
``William Morris,'' a book about a famed glass blower. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in 1942 in Cleveland, Blonston spent much of his childhood  
in central Florida. He earned bachelor's and master's degrees in 
journalism from Northwestern University. He began his newspaper 
career with The Miami Herald in 1964, moving to the Free Press two 
years later. 
</P>
<P>
	He moved to San Jose in 1987, then to Knight Ridder's Washington  
bureau. He became bureau chief in August 1995, supervising a staff 
of 60 reporters and editors. 
</P>
<P>
	Blonston is survived by his wife, Susan Goldberg, a deputy  
managing editor at USA Today, two children from a previous marriage 
and a sister. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
