<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3:30 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UN Ends Sanctions Against Libya  
</P>
<P>
	THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- The United Nations today suspended  
sanctions against Libya after the African nation handed over two 
suspects in the deadly bombing of a jetliner over Scotland. The 
sanctions prevented air travel to and from Libya, and isolated it 
from the West for the past seven years. Former Libyan intelligence 
agents Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah are 
accused of planting a suitcase bomb that blew up Pan Am Flight 103 
on Dec. 21, 1988, killing 270 people. They will be tried under 
Scottish law. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Reiterates Kosovo Stance  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Expressing U.S. determination in the campaign  
against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, President Clinton 
today reaffirmed his commitment to assist Kosovo refugees and vowed 
to ``persist until we prevail.'' Clinton also said that clearing 
weather in the Balkans was enabling NATO forces to target Serb 
forces moving through Kosovo and dismissed criticism that his 
administration didn't heed military concerns about the likely 
success of using airstrikes to stop Milosevic. The ethnic cleansing 
in the Balkans called for action, Clinton said. 

</P>
<P>
	Cohen Warns Yugoslavia of Attacks  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen says  
Serb military and police forces are ``open and vulnerable'' to 
stepped-up NATO air assaults. Cohen warned the Serbs that NATO 
attacks against Yugoslavia will be greatly expanded in the coming 
days. ``We're going after his tanks, his armored units, his 
artillery, those forces on the ground that are carrying out this 
horrific ethnic cleansing. They are going to be targeted now and 
taken out,'' Cohen said. 

</P>
<P>
	Suspect in Gay Attack Pleads Guilty  
</P>
<P>
	LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- A man pleaded guilty today in the slaying  
of gay college student Matthew Shepard, cutting short a trial that 
could have ended with the death penalty. Russell Henderson, 21, a 
high school dropout and roofer, pleaded guilty to felony murder, 
with robbery as the related crime, and kidnapping. He could get two 
life sentences, one on each count. Henderson had been charged with 
first-degree murder, kidnapping and aggravated robbery in the 
beating death of Shepard. 

</P>
<P>
	Defendants Have Right to Silence  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Criminal defendants who plead guilty have a  
constitutional right to remain silent at sentencing without judges 
holding it against them, the Supreme Court ruled today. The 
justices said judges cannot impose harsher punishment if such 
defendants refuse to give details about the crime. The ruling would 
stop prosecutors from indicting someone in a drug case without 
specifying the amount of drugs involved, obtain a guilty plea and 
then use the defendant's testimony at sentencing to establish the 
amount of drugs. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Whitewater Prosecutor Testifies  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A prosecutor was called as a witness  
today at the trial of Whitewater figure Susan McDougal. Ray Jahn 
helped convict Mrs. McDougal on fraud charges in 1996. Jahn said he 
didn't want to hurt President Clinton during Mrs. McDougal's trial, 
and in fact hoped to exonerate Clinton. Jahn said as a Democrat, he 
didn't want a criminal probe of the president. Mrs. McDougal says 
Jahn pressured her to give perjured testimony that falsely 
implicated the Clintons in wrongdoing. McDougal is on trial for 
contempt and obstruction, for refusing to answer questions before a 
grand jury. 

</P>
<P>
	Egg Hunt Held at White House  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President and Mrs. Clinton greeted thousands  
of people today on the South Lawn for the 121st annual Easter egg 
roll. Using white plastic spoons, the children propelled 
hard-boiled eggs along the lawn to a finish line. For their effort, 
they got a plastic egg filled with candy and other gifts. Prior to 
the event, the president asked the crowd to pray for troops and 
refugees in the Balkans. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 164  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 164.83 to 9,997.34. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,591-1,307. The Nasdaq was up 55.85 to 
2,549.22. 

</P>
<P>
	Wizards Fire Bickerstaff  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bernie Bickerstaff was fired as coach of the  
Washington Wizards today after the team dropped to a 13-19 record 
in the shortened season. Assistant Jim Brovelli was appointed 
interim head coach. The Wizards are 4 1/2 games out of a playoff spot. 
Bickerstaff was in his 10th season as an NBA coach. His record was 
338-348, including 77-71 with the Wizards. He began his coaching 
career in Washington in 1973, serving as an assistant until 1985. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
</TEXT>
