<HEADLINE> Ex-Reporter Reveals Chiquita Source </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- A newspaper reporter who admitted intercepting  
voice mail from Chiquita testified Monday that a former attorney 
for the banana company was a confidential source for his stories. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Gallagher was the lead reporter for The Cincinnati  
Enquirer's series in May 1998 that questioned Chiquita's business 
practices in Central America. The newspaper later renounced the 
series, fired Gallagher, apologized to Chiquita Brands 
International on the front page and paid the Cincinnati-based 
company more than $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In September, Gallagher pleaded guilty to illegally intercepting  
communications and obtaining unauthorized access to Chiquita's 
computer systems. 
</P>
<P>
	He never testified about how he obtained the voice mail  
messages, but agreed to cooperate with prosecutors. On Monday, he 
was called to testify by attorneys representing George Ventura, a 
Salt Lake City lawyer who formerly worked for Chiquita. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura goes on trial April 19 on charges that he helped steal  
the voice mail messages. Attorneys were in court Monday to argue 
about evidence to be allowed in that trial, and whether charges of 
illegal interception of communication should be dismissed. 
</P>
<P>
	Under questioning from Ventura's attorney Marc Mezibov,  
Gallagher said Ventura was one of about six people he promised 
confidentiality in return for their help on the Chiquita series. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallagher, 40, could be sentenced to 2 1/2 years in prison, but his  
plea bargain notes that there is no mandatory prison term. His 
sentencing was delayed until May 13, after he testifies at 
Ventura's trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
