<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Already Sell Out Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The Cleveland Indians go into the 1999 season  
with a hefty payroll but also financially secure with a bankroll 
from a sold out home schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	Since moving to Jacobs Field in 1994, the Indians have never had  
a losing record, and they've been to the World Series twice. The 
Indians have sold out their last 292 home games. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland opens its season Tuesday night at Anaheim. The home  
opener is scheduled for Monday against Kansas City. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians announced last week that all Jacobs Field tickets  
for the 1999 season, about 3.5 million, have been sold at an 
average ticket price of $19.37. That assures a guaranteed revenue 
source of about $67 million. Ticket sales last year provided about 
38 percent of total revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland will open the season with a payroll of about $69  
million, among the top six in baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	``We try to budget so as to ensure a profit for just the regular  
season,'' Ron McQuate, Indians director of corporate planning and 
development, said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Real estate developer Richard E. Jacobs maintains control of the  
team, largely through his privately held shares in an unusual 
public-private partnership. Cleveland Indians Baseball Co., the 
public portion of the team, sold 4 million shares in its initial 
offering last June. The stock was sold initially at $15 a share, 
but has been selling recently on the NASDAQ market at about $8.50. 
</P>
<P>
	From June, when the public structure of the team took effect,  
through the end of last year, the team produced a profit of nearly 
$7.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	But last year leading up to June, the Indians operated at a loss  
of $9.7 million, according to disclosure document filed last week 
with the Securities and Exchange Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Combining the two periods, the 1998 net loss of about $2.5  
million contrasts with a $22.6 million profit in 1997. But it 
wasn't really a loss, McQuate says. 
</P>
<P>
	About $11.5 million subtracted from the public side of the  
ledger was actually the profit paid to Jacobs' private portion of 
the franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	McQuate said several unusual factors explain why last year was  
not as profitable as 1997. The Indians in 1997 accounted for 
receiving $9.2 million in expansion fees from the Arizona 
Diamondbacks and Tampa Bay Devil Rays. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians were involved in 18 postseason games in 1997, when  
they advanced to the seventh game of the World Series. They were in 
10 postseason games in 1998. As a result, revenue from postseason 
games was about $4.3 million less last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The team also saw a $2 million drop in merchandise sales,  
largely the result of the lack of a World Series appearance, 
McQuate said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
