<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 05:15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> What's the News in Washington? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The coded first message sent pulsing over the  
wire from the U.S. Capitol to Baltimore could once be quoted by 
every school child: ``What hath God wrought?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The reply, bounding across the 35 miles of wooden poles and  
metal wires, seemed far more practical and to the point. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's the news in Washington?'' it asked.  
</P>
<P>
	Operators in a room at the U.S. Capitol and at a railroad depot  
on Pratt Street in Baltimore soon began providing answers -- at 
least to the second question: News from Congress went out and news 
from Baltimore, which was host to the 1844 Democratic National 
Convention, came back. 
</P>
<P>
	When Samuel Finley Breese Morse opened the wire between the  
Capitol and Baltimore on May 24, 1844, he already knew he had 
successfully harnessed a force of nature, a development 
foreshadowed by Benjamin Franklin's experiments with electricity in 
the 18th century. 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically, Morse, then 53, knew that after a dozen years of  
experiments he could, in fact, transmit messages over long 
distances, leapfrogging both space and time. 
</P>
<P>
	The challenge was to prove to the public and to Congress, which  
had paid $30,000 to build the line to Baltimore, that the Morse 
magnetic telegraph had practical applications. 
</P>
<P>
	That became clear almost immediately.  
</P>
<P>
	Among the first messages received in Washington was news that  
the Democrats had nominated Sen. Silas Wright of New York for 
second place on the fall ticket with dark horse James Knox Polk. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright was in the Capitol. He declined the vice presidency by  
telegraph. 
</P>
<P>
	But could the system be trusted? Could the odd little device be  
telling the truth? 
</P>
<P>
	In Baltimore, the convention's presiding officer reported that  
delegates so much doubted the validity of Wright's electronic 
refusal that they adjourned for a day to await ``reliable'' 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	A committee, sent by rail from Baltimore, reported that Wright  
had indeed refused to be nominated as vice president. George 
Mifflin Dallas later was nominated, and he and Polk went on to win 
the vice presidency and presidency, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	``The exchange demonstrated the telegraph's validity ... As the  
news came over the wire, Morse gathered up messages and posted them 
in the Capitol Rotunda ...,'' said Donald A. Ritchie, the associate 
historian of the Senate, in ``Press Gallery,'' a 1991 history of 
``Congress and the Washington Correspondents'' published by Harvard 
University Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Most people knew an important bridge had been crossed.  
</P>
<P>
	``Information will be literally winged with the rapidity of  
lightning,'' the Baltimore weekly, Niles National Register, 
reported on June 22. ``Both space and time is annihilated ....'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Morse, Congress proved more difficult to move than electric  
pulses. 
</P>
<P>
	At first, the proposal that Congress pay to demonstrate the new  
technology nearly drowned in ridicule. 
</P>
<P>
	The lowest moment came when the House failed by only six votes  
to approve an amendment that would have diverted half the money to 
a study of the message-sending potential of hypnotism. 
</P>
<P>
	There was less difficulty in the Senate, but as its session  
neared an end, the telegraph bill appeared hopelessly buried and 
its late-night resurrection a near-miracle. 
</P>
<P>
	``My personal funds were reduced to the fraction of a dollar,  
and had the ... bill failed from any cause, there would have been 
little prospect of another attempt on my part to introduce my new 
invention to the world,'' Morse wrote a friend. 
</P>
<P>
	But even when the demonstration proved an unqualified success,  
the government declined to buy Morse's patents or to sponsor a 
national telegraph system. Officials refused to believe the system 
could ever pay for itself. 
</P>
<P>
	In private hands, the telegraph proved to be a technological  
milestone, the forerunner of the telephone, radio, television and 
eventually the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Lawrence L. Knutson has reported on Congress, the  
White House and Washington's history for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990405.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-05 05:57:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Riot Police Patrol Israeli Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAZARETH, Israel (AP) -- Riot police patrolled the town of Jesus'  
boyhood after clashes erupted between Christians and Muslims over a 
planned millennium pilgrimage site on a spot where Muslims want to 
build a mosque. 
</P>
<P>
	The violence marred Easter Sunday celebrations in Nazareth, a  
city of 60,000 in northern Israel that has long prided itself on 
its tolerance but has seen growing tensions between the Muslim 
majority and the Christian minority in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	In Sunday's clashes, seven people were injured, 30 cars were  
damaged and six Muslim stone-throwers were arrested, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	``My house was attacked with stones today,'' said Salim Suliman,  
a 68-year-old Christian shopkeeper. ``I never imagined that this 
would happen. We always lived in tolerance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, thousands of young Muslim men gathered at the  
disputed downtown site near the Church of the Annunciation where 
the Christian mayor wants to build a plaza for millennium pilgrims. 
</P>
<P>
	Muslims say the land belongs to the Islamic Trust, or waqf, and  
demand that a mosque be built there. Last year, Muslim activists 
set up a protest tent where they have been holding daily prayers. 
</P>
<P>
	During the confrontations, some Muslims hurled insults and  
curses at Christian worshippers leaving the church where Roman 
Catholic tradition holds that the Angel Gabriel appeared before 
Mary and told her she was pregnant. Other youths, wielding clubs, 
smashed windshields of cars with crosses dangling from the mirrors. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of Israeli riot police were deployed to end the fighting  
but made little effort to halt the violence. At one point, 
policemen stood and watched as Muslim youths smashed the window of 
a Mercedes. Police said Muslim protesters responded to the arrests 
by pelting troops with stones outside the mosque. Israeli forces 
then fired tears gas, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Overnight, police patrolled the streets of Nazareth to prevent a  
renewed outbreak of violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Muslim activists want to build a mosque and Islamic studies  
center on the spot where city planners had hoped to build a 
Venetian-style plaza for tourists. The dispute is in court, and the 
plaza construction is on hold. 
</P>
<P>
	Rafieh Shihaberi, a 53-year-old Muslim engineer from Nazareth,  
said the religious tensions are destructive but the mosque must be 
expanded. 
</P>
<P>
	``What is happening in Nazareth is not in the interest of either  
Muslims or Christians,'' Shihaberi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
